 2015}}</ref> China, Colombia,<ref>{{cite web|title=New Colombia Resources Inc Subsidiary, Sannabis, Produces First Batch of Medical Marijuana Based Products in Colombia to Fill Back Orders|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/new-colombia-resources-inc-subsidiary-sannabis-produces-first-batch-of-medical-marijuana-based-products-in-colombia-to-fill-back-orders-879870332.html|website=prnewswire.com|publisher=PR Newswire|access-date=12 January 2015}}</ref> India,<ref name=UNDRUG2013 /> Jamaica,<ref name=\"UNDRUG2013\"/> Lebanon,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/video.cfm?c_id=1503076&gal_cid=1503076&gallery_id=139379|title=Lebanon cannabis trade thrives in shadow of Syrian war|first = Rana | last = Moussaoui | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=AFP|date=Nov 25, 2013}}</ref> Mexico,<ref name=Garelli/> Morocco,<ref name=UNDRUG2013 /> Netherlands, Pakistan, Paraguay,<ref name=Garelli>{{cite news|title=Mexico, Paraguay top pot producers, U.N. report says|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/americas/11/25/paraguay.mexico.marijuana/|access-date=28 September 2013|newspaper=CNN International|date=25 November 2008| first = Sanie Lopez | last = Garelli | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> Spain,<ref name=UNDRUG2013 /> Thailand, Turkey, United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite web | last=Jackman | first=Robert | title=How Britain became the world's largest exporter of medical marijuana | website=The Spectator | date=2019-01-12 | url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2019/01/how-britain-became-the-worlds-largest-expert-in-medical-marijuana/amp/ | ref=harv | access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> United States<ref name=UNDRUG2013 />\n|wholesale =\n|retail =\n|legal_AU = S9\n|legal_CA = Unscheduled\n|legal_DE = Medical cannabis from state-controlled production: [[Anlage III]], other cannabis: [[Anlage I|I]]\n|legal_UK = Class B\n|legal_US = [[Schedule I Controlled Substance|Schedule I]] (legal recreationally in 11 states & DC; medically legal in 33 states)\n|legal_UN = Narcotic Schedule I\n}}\n'''Cannabis''', also known as '''marijuana''' among other names,{{efn|Also referred to as ''marihuana'', ''pot'', ''weed'', ''dope'', and ''ganja'' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u0251\u02d0|n|d\u0292|\u0259}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/pot|title=Pot&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|access-date=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/weed|title=Weed&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary |access-date=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/dope |title=Dope&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|access-date=17 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/ganja |title=Ganja&nbsp;\u2013 Definition |publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|access-date=17 July 2017}}</ref> among many other nicknames (''grass'', ''herb'', ''skunk'', ''Mary Jane'', etc.).<ref name=\"M.D.Strain2011\">{{cite book|first1=Pedro|last1=Ruiz|first2=Eric C.|last2=Strain|name-list-format=vanc|title=Substance Abuse: A Comprehensive Textbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w4ZUJAdleTsC&pg=PA214|year=2011|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|isbn=978-1-60547-277-5|page=214}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/grass|title=Grass&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary |access-date=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/herb |title=Herb&nbsp;\u2013 Definition |publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|access-date=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=skunk |title=Skunk&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language|access-date=17 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/Mary%20Jane|title=Mary Jane&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|access-date=17 July 2017}}</ref>}} is a [[psychoactive drug]] from the [[Cannabis|''Cannabis'' plant]] used for [[medical cannabis|medical]] or [[Recreational drug use|recreational]] purposes.<ref>{{cite book|author=Vij|title=Textbook Of Forensic Medicine And Toxicology: Principles And Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vp8FAsnfGF4C&pg=PT672|year=2012|publisher=Elsevier India|isbn=978-81-312-1129-8|page=672}}See also article on [[marijuana (word)|''Marijuana'' as a word]].</ref><ref>{{ShorterOxfordEnglishDictionary}}</ref><ref name=\"Dictionaries2007m\">{{cite book|author=|title=Spanish Word Histories and Mysteries: English Words That Come From Spanish|url=https://archive.org/details/spanishwordhisto00houg|url-access=registration|year=2007|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|isbn=978-0-547-35021-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/spanishwordhisto00houg/page/142 142]}}</ref> The primary psychoactive component of cannabis is [[tetrahydrocannabinol]] (THC), which is one of the 483 known compounds in the plant,<ref name=\"Russo2013\">{{cite book|first=Ethan B.|last=Russo|name-list-format=vanc|title=Cannabis and Cannabinoids: Pharmacology, Toxicology, and Therapeutic Potential|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qH-2Lj9x7L4C&pg=PP28|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-61493-4|page=28}}</ref> including at least 65 other [[cannabinoids]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Newton|first1=David E.| name-list-format = vanc | title = Marijuana: a reference handbook|date=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=9781610691499|page=7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iWMf95ze8QEC&pg=PA7}}</ref> Cannabis can be used by [[Cannabis smoking|smoking]], [[Vaporizer (inhalation device)|vaporizing]], [[Cannabis edible|within food]], or [[Tincture of cannabis|as an extract]].<ref name=NIH2016/>\n\n<!-- Effects -->\nCannabis has [[effects of cannabis|mental and physical effects]]. It causes a \"[[euphoria|high]]\", or stoned feeling and other effects, including a general [[altered state of consciousness|change in perception]], difficulty thinking, [[Cannabis and memory|impaired short-term memory]], altered sense of time, impaired [[motor skill|body movement]],<ref name=NIH2016/> relaxation,<ref name=\"pmid18365950\"/> and an increase in [[appetite]], otherwise known as \"munchies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adai.uw.edu/marijuana/factsheets/appetite.htm |title=Marijuana: Factsheets: Appetite |publisher=Adai.uw.edu |access-date=12 July 2013}}</ref> At high doses, mental effects include [[Cannabis and psychosis|psychosis]], delusions, hallucinations,<ref name=\"NIH2016\" /> paranoia, and [[Ideas of reference and delusions of reference|ideas of reference]], sometimes with anxiety and panic.<ref name=\"D'Souza\" /> Its physical effects include increased heart rate, difficulty breathing, nausea, and behavioral problems in children whose mothers used cannabis during pregnancy.<ref name=\"NIH2016\" /> Short-term side effects may include a [[xerostomia|dry mouth]], red eyes, and feelings of [[paranoia]] or [[anxiety]].<ref name=NLMNIH>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/000952.htm|title=Marijuana intoxication: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia|publisher=Nlm.nih.gov|access-date=12 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Crippa JA, Zuardi AW, Mart\u00edn-Santos R, Bhattacharyya S, Atakan Z, McGuire P, Fusar-Poli P|title=Cannabis and anxiety: a critical review of the evidence|journal=Human Psychopharmacology|volume=24|issue=7|pages=515\u201323|date=October 2009|pmid=19693792|doi=10.1002/hup.1048}}</ref> Long-term [[adverse effect]]s may include addiction, decreased [[neurocognition|mental ability]] in those who started regular use as [[adolescent]]s, chronic [[cough|coughing]], and susceptibility to [[Respiratory tract infection|respiratory infections]].<ref name=\"Abuse 2019\">{{cite web |publisher=National Institute on Drug Abuse, US National Institutes of Health| title=Commonly Abused Drugs Charts: Marijuana (Cannabis) | date=2019-07-22 | url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/drugs-abuse/commonly-abused-drugs-charts#marijuana-cannabis-| access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> There is a strong relation between cannabis use and the risk of psychosis,<ref name=Leweke2016rev>{{cite journal|vauthors=Leweke FM, Mueller JK, Lange B, Rohleder C|title=Therapeutic Potential of Cannabinoids in Psychosis|journal=Biological Psychiatry|volume=79|issue=7|pages=604\u201312|date=April 2016|pmid=26852073|doi=10.1016/j.biopsych.2015.11.018 |quote=Epidemiological data indicate a strong relationship between cannabis use and psychosis and schizophrenia beyond transient intoxication with an increased risk of any psychotic outcome in individuals who had ever used cannabis}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ortiz-Medina |first1=MB |last2=Perea |first2=M |last3=Torales |first3=J |last4=Ventriglio |first4=A |last5=Vitrani |first5=G |last6=Aguilar |first6=L |last7=Roncero |first7=C |title=Cannabis consumption and psychosis or schizophrenia development. |journal=The International Journal of Social Psychiatry |date=November 2018 |volume=64 |issue=7 |pages=690\u2013704 |doi=10.1177/0020764018801690 |pmid=30442059|quote=Cannabis use doubles the risk of developing psychosis in vulnerable people.}}</ref> though the [[cause and effect]] is debated.<ref name=\"doi:10.1007/s11920-015-0657-y\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Ksir C, Hart CL|title=Cannabis and Psychosis: a Critical Overview of the Relationship|journal=Current Psychiatry Reports|volume=18|issue=2|pages=12|date=February 2016|pmid=26781550|doi=10.1007/s11920-015-0657-y }}</ref> Onset of effects is felt within minutes when smoked, and about 30 to 60 minutes when cooked and eaten.<ref name=NIH2016/><ref name=\"Ri2010\" /> The effects last for two to six hours, depending on the amount of consumption.<ref name=Ri2010>{{cite book|last1=Riviello|first1=Ralph J. | name-list-format = vanc |title=Manual of forensic emergency medicine : a guide for clinicians|date=2010|publisher=Jones and Bartlett Publishers|location=Sudbury, Mass.|isbn=9780763744625|page=41|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=keng9ELAE2IC&pg=PA41}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Usage -->\nCannabis is mostly used for recreational use or as a medicinal drug, although it may also be used for [[Entheogenic use of cannabis|spiritual purposes]]. In 2013, between 128 and 232 million people used cannabis (2.7% to 4.9% of the global population between the ages of 15 and 65).<ref name=WDR2015>{{cite book|title=World Drug Report 2015|chapter-url=http://www.unodc.org/documents/wdr2015/WDR15_Drug_use_health_consequences.pdf|access-date=26 June 2015|chapter=Status and Trend Analysis of {{sic|nolink=y|Illict}} Drug Markets|page=23}}</ref> It is the most commonly used [[illegal drug]] both in the world and the United States,<ref name=NIH2016>{{cite web|title=DrugFacts: Marijuana|url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/publications/drugfacts/marijuana|publisher=National Institute on Drug Abuse, US National Institutes of Health|access-date=20 January 2020|date=1 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=WDR2015/> though it is also legal in some jurisdictions. The countries with the highest use among adults {{as of|2018|lc=y}} are Zambia, the United States, Canada, and Nigeria.<ref>{{cite web |title=UNODC Statistics Online |url=https://data.unodc.org/ |website=data.unodc.org |accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref> In 2016, 51% of people in the United States had used cannabis in their lifetimes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Salvanto |first1=Anthony |last2=Backus |first2=Fred |last3=De Pinto |first3=Jennifer |last4=Dutton |first4=Sarah |title=Marijuana use and support for legal marijuana continue to climb |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/marijuana-use-and-support-for-legal-marijuana-continue-to-climb/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=CBS News |date=April 20, 2016}}</ref> About 12% had used it in the past year, and 7.3% had used it in the past month.<ref name=\"6 facts about marijuana\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/04/14/6-facts-about-marijuana/|title=6 facts about marijuana|last=Motel|first=Seth|name-list-format=vanc|website=Pew Research Center|access-date=26 June 2015|date=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n<!-- History, society and culture -->\nWhile cannabis plants have been grown since at least the 3rd millennium BCE,<ref name=\"Booth2003\">{{cite book|first=Martin|last=Booth|authorlink=Martin Booth|name-list-format=vanc|title=Cannabis: A History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mjn6sCiHoFIC&pg=PA36|year=2003|publisher=Transworld|isbn=978-1-4090-8489-1|page=36}}</ref> evidence suggests that it was being smoked for psychoactive effects at least 2,500 years ago in the [[Pamir Mountains]].<ref name=\"NatGeo2019Jun\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/culture/2019/06/earliest-evidence-cannabis-marijuana-smoking-china-tombs/ |title=Earliest evidence for cannabis smoking discovered in ancient tombs|date= 2019-06-12|first=Michelle |last=Donahue |work=National Geographic}}</ref> Since the early 20th century, cannabis has been subject to legal restrictions. The possession, use, and cultivation of cannabis is [[Legality of cannabis|illegal in most countries of the world]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erowid.org/plants/cannabis/cannabis_law.shtml|title=Cannabis: Legal Status|publisher=Erowid.org|access-date=30 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"UN-WDR-2010\">{{cite book|last=UNODC|title=World Drug Report 2010|publisher=United Nations Publication|page=198|url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/data-and-analysis/WDR-2010.html |access-date=2010-07-19}}</ref> In 2013, Uruguay became the first country to legalize recreational use of cannabis.<ref name=\"newsweek2018\">{{cite news |last1=Lemon |first1=Jason |title=Where Is Weed Legal Around The World? You Can Now Officially Smoke Pot In Canada |url=https://www.newsweek.com/where-weed-legal-around-world-you-can-now-officially-smoke-pot-canada-1173623 |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=Newsweek |date=17 October 2018}}</ref> Other countries to do so are Canada, Georgia, and South Africa, along with 11 states and the District of Columbia in the United States (though the drug remains federally illegal).<ref name=\"newsweek2018\" /><ref name=\"ncsl rec\">{{cite web |title=Marijuana Overview |url=http://www.ncsl.org/research/civil-and-criminal-justice/marijuana-overview.aspx |website=National Conference of State Legislatures |accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> Medical use of cannabis, requiring the approval of a physician, has been legalized in a greater number of countries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Sean |title=These 30 Countries Have Legalized Medical Marijuana in Some Capacity |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2018/07/21/these-30-countries-have-legalized-medical-marijuan.aspx |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=The Motley Fool |date=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Uses==\n===Medical===\n{{Main|Medical cannabis}}\n[[File:Bodily effects of cannabis.svg|thumb|upright=1.1|Main short-term physical effects of cannabis]]\nMedical cannabis, or medical marijuana, can refer to the use of cannabis and its [[cannabinoids]] to treat disease or improve symptoms; however, there is no single agreed-upon definition.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Murnion B|title=Medicinal cannabis| journal=Australian Prescriber|volume=38|issue =6|pages=212\u20135|date=December 2015|pmid=26843715|pmc=4674028|doi=10.18773/austprescr.2015.072 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=What is medical marijuana?|url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/publications/drugfacts/marijuana-medicine|website=National Institute of Drug Abuse|access-date=19 April 2016|date=July 2015|quote=The term medical marijuana refers to using the whole unprocessed marijuana plant or its basic extracts to treat a disease or symptom.}}</ref> The rigorous scientific study of cannabis as a medicine has been hampered by production restrictions and by the fact that it is classified as an illegal drug by many governments.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=|title=Release the strains|journal=Nature Medicine|volume=21|issue=9|pages=963|date=September 2015|pmid=26340110|doi=10.1038/nm.3946}}</ref> There is limited evidence suggesting cannabis can be used to [[antiemetic|reduce nausea and vomiting]] during [[chemotherapy]], to improve appetite in people with [[HIV/AIDS]], or to treat [[chronic pain]] and [[muscle spasms]].<ref name=\"Borgelt2013\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Borgelt LM, Franson KL, Nussbaum AM, Wang GS|date=February 2013|title=The pharmacologic and clinical effects of medical cannabis|journal=Pharmacotherapy|volume=33|issue=2|pages=195\u2013209|doi=10.1002/phar.1187|pmid=23386598|citeseerx=10.1.1.1017.1935}}</ref><ref name=JAMA2015>{{cite journal|vauthors=Whiting PF, Wolff RF, Deshpande S, Di Nisio M, Duffy S, Hernandez AV, Keurentjes JC, Lang S, Misso K, Ryder S, Schmidlkofer S, Westwood M, Kleijnen J|title=Cannabinoids for Medical Use: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis|journal=JAMA|volume=313|issue=24|pages=2456\u201373|date=23 June 2015|pmid=26103030|doi=10.1001/jama.2015.6358|hdl=10757/558499}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Jensen B, Chen J, Furnish T, Wallace M|title=Medical Marijuana and Chronic Pain: a Review of Basic Science and Clinical Evidence|journal=Current Pain and Headache Reports|volume=19|issue=10|pages=50|date=October 2015|pmid=26325482|doi=10.1007/s11916-015-0524-x}}</ref> Its use for other medical applications is insufficient for drawing conclusions about safety or efficacy.\n\n<!-- Side effects -->\nShort-term use increases the risk of both minor and major adverse effects.<ref name=JAMA2015/> Common side effects include dizziness, feeling tired and vomiting.<ref name=JAMA2015/> The [[long-term effects of cannabis]] are not clear.<ref name=JAMA2015/> There are concerns surrounding [[Cannabis and memory|memory and cognition problems]], risk of addiction, risk of [[schizophrenia]] in young people, and the risk of children taking it by accident.<ref name=Borgelt2013/>\n\n===Recreational===\n{{Main|Effects of cannabis}}\nCannabis has psychoactive and physiological effects when consumed.<ref name=\"OnaiviSugiura2005\">{{cite book|first1=Emmanuel S.|last1=Onaivi|first2=Takayuki|last2=Sugiura|first3=Vincenzo|last3=Di Marzo|name-list-format=vanc|title=Endocannabinoids: The Brain and Body's Marijuana and Beyond|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BxfLB4n3uoMC&pg=PA58|year=2005|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-30008-7|page=58}}</ref> The immediate desired effects from consuming cannabis include relaxation and [[euphoria]] (the \"high\" or \"stoned\" feeling), a general [[altered state of consciousness|alteration of conscious perception]], increased awareness of sensation, increased [[libido]]<ref name=\"pmid18365950\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Osborne GB, Fogel C|title=Understanding the motivations for recreational marijuana use among adult Canadians|journal=Substance Use & Misuse|volume=43|issue=3\u20134|pages=539\u201372; discussion 573\u20139, 585\u20137|date=2008|pmid=18365950|doi=10.1080/10826080701884911|url=http://cannabislink.ca/info/MotivationsforCannabisUsebyCanadianAdults-2008.pdf }}</ref> and [[Cannabis and time perception|distortions in the perception of time]] and space. At higher doses, effects can include altered [[body image]], auditory and/or visual [[illusion]]s, [[pseudohallucination]]s and [[ataxia]] from selective impairment of [[Reflex arc|polysynaptic]] [[reflex]]es. In some cases, cannabis can lead to [[dissociation (psychology)|dissociative]] states such as [[depersonalization]]<ref name=\"medscape1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/468728_3|title=Medication-Associated Depersonalization Symptoms }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid15889607\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Shufman E, Lerner A, Witztum E|title=[Depersonalization after withdrawal from cannabis usage]|language=Hebrew|journal=Harefuah|volume=144|issue=4|pages=249\u201351, 303|date=April 2005|pmid=15889607|url=http://www.ima.org.il/Ima/FormStorage/Type3/05-04-07.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050430224332/http://www.ima.org.il/Ima/FormStorage/Type3/05-04-07.pdf|archive-date=30 April 2005}}</ref> and [[derealization]].<ref name=\"Johnson1990\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Johnson BA|title=Psychopharmacological effects of cannabis|journal=British Journal of Hospital Medicine|volume=43|issue=2|pages=114\u20136, 118\u201320, 122|date=February 1990|pmid=2178712}}</ref>\n\nSome immediate undesired side effects include a decrease in short-term memory, dry mouth, impaired motor skills and reddening of the eyes.<ref name=\"HallPacula2003ew\">{{cite book|first1=Wayne|last1=Hall|first2=Rosalie Liccardo|last2=Pacula|name-list-format=vanc |title=Cannabis Use and Dependence: Public Health and Public Policy|url=https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence|url-access=registration|year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-80024-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence/page/n35 38]}}</ref> Aside from a subjective change in perception and mood, the most common short-term physical and neurological effects include increased heart rate, increased appetite and consumption of food, lowered blood pressure, impairment of short-term and working memory,<ref name=\"Mathre1997\">{{cite book|editor-first=Mary Lynn|editor-last=Mathre|name-list-format=vanc|title=Cannabis in Medical Practice: A Legal, Historical, and Pharmacological Overview of the Therapeutic Use of Marijuana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1AWGDhIOvk0C&pg=PA144|year=1997|publisher=University of Virginia Medical Center|isbn=978-0-7864-8390-7|pages=144\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"memoryhindered\">{{cite book|vauthors=Riedel G, Davies SN|chapter=Cannabinoid function in learning, memory and plasticity|volume=168|issue=168|pages=445\u201377|year=2005|pmid=16596784|doi=10.1007/3-540-26573-2_15|isbn=978-3-540-22565-2|series=Handbook of Experimental Pharmacology |title=Cannabinoids}}</ref> [[Motor coordination|psychomotor coordination]], and concentration. Some users may experience an episode of acute [[psychosis]], which usually abates after six hours, but in rare instances, heavy users may find the symptoms continuing for many days.<ref name=\"Barceloux2012\" />\n\nA reduced [[quality of life]] is associated with heavy cannabis use, although the relationship is inconsistent and weaker than for tobacco and other substances.<ref name=Gold2017>{{cite journal|vauthors=Goldenberg M, IsHak WW, Danovitch I|title=Quality of life and recreational cannabis use|journal=The American Journal on Addictions|volume=26|issue=1|pages=8\u201325|date=January 2017|pmid=28000973|doi=10.1111/ajad.12486 }}</ref> The direction of [[causality|cause and effect relationship]], however, is unclear.<ref name=Gold2017/>\n\n===Spiritual===\n[[File:Ganja Smoking - Gangasagar Fair Transit Camp - Kolkata 2013-01-12 2646.JPG|thumb|upright=1.2|A man smoking cannabis]]\n{{Main|Entheogenic use of cannabis}}\nCannabis has held sacred status in several religions and has served as an [[entheogen]] \u2013 a [[chemical substance]] used in [[religion|religious]], [[shamanism|shamanic]], or [[spirituality|spiritual]] contexts<ref>{{cite journal |title=Brazilian Archives of Biology and Technology \u2013 Jurema-Preta (Mimosa tenuiflora [Willd.] Poir.): a review of its traditional use, phytochemistry and pharmacology |journal=Brazilian Archives of Biology and Technology |volume=51 |issue=5 |pages=937\u2013947 |doi=10.1590/S1516-89132008000500010 |year=2008 |last1=Souza |first1=Rafael Sampaio Octaviano de |last2=Albuquerque |first2=Ulysses Paulino de |last3=Monteiro |first3=J\u00falio Marcelino |last4= de Amorim |first4=Elba L\u00facia Cavalcanti | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> \u2013 in the Indian subcontinent since the [[Vedic period]] dating back to approximately 1500 BCE, but perhaps as far back as 2000 BCE. There are several references in Greek mythology to a powerful drug that eliminated anguish and sorrow. [[Herodotus]] wrote about early ceremonial practices by the [[Scythians]], thought to have occurred from the 5th to 2nd century BCE. In modern culture, the spiritual use of cannabis has been spread by the disciples of the [[Rastafari movement]] who use cannabis as a [[sacrament]] and as an aid to meditation. The earliest known reports regarding the sacred status of cannabis in the Indian subcontinent come from the [[Atharva Veda]], estimated to have been composed sometime around 1400 BCE.<ref>{{cite book|title=Forces of Habit: Drugs and the Making of the Modern World|last=Courtwright|first=David|name-list-format=vanc|year=2001|publisher=Harvard Univ. Press|location=|isbn=978-0-674-00458-0|page=39|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GHqV3elHYvMC&pg=PP10&dq=Forces+of+Habit#v=onepage&q=atharva}}</ref>\n\n===Available forms===\n{{Main|Cannabis consumption}}\n[[File:Unrolled joint.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|A joint prior to rolling, with a paper handmade filter on the left]]\nCannabis is consumed in many different ways:<ref name=\"Golub2012a\">{{cite book|first=Andrew|last=Golub|name-list-format=vanc |title=The Cultural/Subcultural Contexts of Marijuana Use at the Turn of the Twenty-First Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KFMtFv2tmbYC&pg=PA82|year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-44627-6|page=82}}</ref>\n* [[Cannabis smoking|Smoking]], which typically involves burning and inhaling vaporized cannabinoids (\"smoke\") from [[One hitter (smoking)|small pipes]], [[bong]]s (portable versions of [[hookah]]s with a water chamber), paper-wrapped [[joint (cannabis)|joints]] or tobacco-leaf-wrapped [[blunt (cigar)|blunts]], and other items.<ref name=\"TasmanKay2011\">{{cite book|first1=Allan|last1=Tasman|first2=Jerald|last2=Kay|first3=Jeffrey A.|last3=Lieberman|first4=Michael B.|last4=First|first5=Mario | last5=Maj|name-list-format=vanc|title=Psychiatry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vVG7zz7eaxcC&pg=RA9-PT2217|year=2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-96540-4|page=9}}</ref>\n* [[vaporizer (cannabis)|Vaporizer]], which heats any form of cannabis to {{convert|165|\u2013|190|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}},<ref name=\"Rosenthal2002b\">{{cite book|first=Ed|last=Rosenthal|name-list-format=vanc|title=Ask Ed: Marijuana Gold: Trash to Stash |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=obbSwmSB6okC&pg=PT15|year=2002|publisher=Perseus Books Group|isbn=978-1-936807-02-4|page=15}}</ref> causing the active ingredients to evaporate into [[vapor]] without burning the plant material (the boiling point of [[tetrahydrocannabinol|THC]] is {{convert|157|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} at atmospheric pressure).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cannabis-med.org/data/pdf/2001-03-04-7.pdf|title=Cannabis and Cannabis Extracts: Greater Than the Sum of Their Parts?|publisher=Cannabis-med.org|accessdate=7 April 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Cannabis tea]], which contains relatively small concentrations of THC because THC is an oil ([[lipophilic]]) and is only slightly water-soluble (with a solubility of 2.8&nbsp;mg per liter).<ref name=\"Physical Properties \u2013 Dronabinol\">{{ChemID|1972-08-3|Dronabinol}}</ref> Cannabis tea is made by first adding a [[saturated fat]] to hot water (e.g. cream or any milk except skim) with a small amount of cannabis.<ref name=\"Ph.D.Rosenthal2008yt\">{{cite book|first1=Dale|last1=Gieringer|first2=Ed|last2=Rosenthal|name-list-format = vanc |title=Marijuana medical handbook: practical guide to therapeutic uses of marijuana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OuAHxDKcpS8C&pg=PA182|year=2008|publisher=QUICK AMER Publishing Company|isbn=978-0-932551-86-3|page=182}}</ref>\n* [[Cannabis foods|Edibles]], where cannabis is added as an ingredient to one of a variety of foods, including butter and baked goods. In India it is commonly made into a beverage, [[bhang]].\n* [[Capsule (pharmacy)|Capsules]], typically containing [[hash oil|cannabis oil]], and other [[dietary supplement]] products, for which some 220 were approved in Canada in 2018.<ref name=\"canada2018\">{{cite web|title=Health products containing cannabis or for use with cannabis: Guidance for the Cannabis Act, the Food and Drugs Act, and related regulations|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/health-canada/services/drugs-health-products/drug-products/applications-submissions/guidance-documents/guidance-cannabis-act-food-and-drugs-act-related-regulations/document.html |publisher=Government of Canada|date=11 July 2018|accessdate=19 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Adverse effects==\n{{See also|Long-term effects of cannabis}}\n{{Further|Cannabis in pregnancy}}\n[[File:Rational harm assessment of drugs radar plot.svg|thumb|Addiction experts in psychiatry, chemistry, pharmacology, forensic science, epidemiology, and the police and legal services engaged in [[Delphi method|delphic analysis]] regarding 20 popular recreational drugs. Cannabis was ranked 11th in dependence, 17th in physical harm, and 10th in social harm.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Nutt D, King LA, Saulsbury W, Blakemore C | title = Development of a rational scale to assess the harm of drugs of potential misuse|journal=Lancet|volume=369|issue=9566|pages=1047\u201353|date=March 2007|pmid=17382831|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(07)60464-4 }}</ref>]]\n\n===Short term===\nAcute effects may include anxiety and panic, impaired attention and memory, an increased risk of psychotic symptoms,{{efn|Psychotic episodes are well-documented and typically resolve within minutes or hours, while symptoms may last longer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhra.gov.uk/home/groups/par/documents/websiteresources/con084961.pdf |title=Sativex Oral Mucosal Spray Public Assessment Report. Decentralized Procedure. |page=93 |publisher=United Kingdom Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency |access-date=2015-05-07 |quote=There is clear evidence that recreational cannabis can produce a transient toxic psychosis in larger doses or in susceptible individuals, which is said to characteristically resolve within a week or so of absence (Johns 2001). Transient psychotic episodes as a component of acute intoxication are well-documented (Hall et al 1994) }}</ref> The use of a single joint can temporarily induce some psychiatric symptoms.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Katie |title=Single cannabis joint linked with temporary psychiatric symptoms, review finds |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/health/cannabis-psychiatric-symptoms-wellness/index.html |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=CNN |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>}} the inability to think clearly, and an increased risk of accidents.<ref name=\"W. Hall, N. Solowij 1611\u201316\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Hall W, Solowij N|title=Adverse effects of cannabis|journal =Lancet|volume=352|issue=9140|pages=1611\u20136|date=November 1998|pmid=9843121|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(98)05021-1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Abnormal Psychology|last1=Oltmanns|first1=Thomas|first2=Robert|last2=Emery|publisher = Pearson|year=2015|isbn=978-0205970742|location=New Jersey|page=294|name-list-format=vanc}}</ref><ref name=D'Souza>{{cite journal|vauthors=D'Souza DC, Sewell RA, Ranganathan M|title=Cannabis and psychosis/schizophrenia: human studies|journal=European Archives of Psychiatry and Clinical Neuroscience|volume=259|issue=7|pages=413\u201331|date=October 2009|pmid=19609589|pmc=2864503|doi=10.1007/s00406-009-0024-2 }}</ref> Cannabis impairs a person's driving ability, and [[Tetrahydrocannabinol|THC]] was the illicit drug most frequently found in the blood of drivers who have been involved in vehicle crashes. Those with THC in their system are from three to seven times more likely to be the cause of the accident than those who had not used either cannabis or alcohol, although its role is not necessarily causal because THC stays in the bloodstream for days to weeks after intoxication.<ref name=NIH-2>{{cite web |last1=Abuse |first1=National Institute on Drug |title=Does marijuana use affect driving? |url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/publications/research-reports/marijuana/does-marijuana-use-affect-driving |website=www.drugabuse.gov |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Li MC, Brady JE, DiMaggio CJ, Lusardi AR, Tzong KY, Li G|title=Marijuana use and motor vehicle crashes|journal=Epidemiologic Reviews|volume=34|issue=1|pages=65\u201372|date=4 October 2011|pmid=21976636|pmc=3276316|doi=10.1093/epirev/mxr017 }}</ref>{{efn|A 2016 review also found a statistically significant increase in crash risk associated with marijuana use, but noted that this risk was \"of low to medium magnitude.\"<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Rogeberg O, Elvik R|title=The effects of cannabis intoxication on motor vehicle collision revisited and revised|journal=Addiction|volume=111|issue=8|pages=1348\u201359|date=August 2016|pmid=26878835|doi=10.1111/add.13347|url=https://zenodo.org/record/897625}}</ref> The increase in risk of motor vehicle crash for cannabis use is between 2 and 3 times relative to baseline, whereas that for comparable doses of alcohol is between 6 and 15 times.<ref name=hall2015>{{cite journal|vauthors=Hall W|title=What has research over the past two decades revealed about the adverse health effects of recreational cannabis use?|journal=Addiction|volume=110|issue=1|pages=19\u201335|date=January 2015|pmid=25287883|doi=10.1111/add.12703|url=https://espace.library.uq.edu.au/view/UQ:346328/Hall_2014_20ycann_OA_post.pdf}}</ref>}}\n\nAccording to the United States Department of Health and Human Services, there were 455,000 emergency room visits associated with cannabis use in 2011. These statistics include visits in which the patient was treated for a condition induced by or related to recent cannabis use. The drug use must be \"implicated\" in the emergency department visit, but does not need to be the direct cause of the visit. Most of the illicit drug emergency room visits involved multiple drugs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.samhsa.gov/data/sites/default/files/DAWN2k11ED/DAWN2k11ED/DAWN2k11ED.pdf|work=Drug Abuse Warning Network|title=National Estimates of Drug-Related Emergency Department Visits|publisher=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services|date = 2011 | access-date = 8 May 2015}}</ref> In 129,000 cases, cannabis was the only implicated drug.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.samhsa.gov/data/sites/default/files/Nation_2011_AllMA.xls |title=National Estimates of Drug-related Emergency Department Visits, 2004 \u2013 2011|work=Drug Abuse Warning Network|publisher=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services }}</ref><ref name=NEJM2014>{{cite journal|vauthors=Volkow ND, Baler RD, Compton WM, Weiss SR|title=Adverse health effects of marijuana use|journal=The New England Journal of Medicine|volume=370|issue=23|pages=2219\u201327|date=June 2014|pmid=24897085|pmc=4827335|doi=10.1056/NEJMra1402309}}</ref>\n\nThe short term effects of cannabis can be altered if it has been laced with [[opioid]] drugs such as [[heroin]] or [[fentanyl]].<ref>[https://www.medpagetoday.com/primarycare/opioids/74071 \"Growing Array of Street Drugs Now Laced with Fentanyl\"], ''MedPageToday'', July 17, 2018</ref> The added drugs are meant to enhance the psychoactive properties, add to its weight, and increase profitability, despite the increased danger of overdose.<ref>[https://americanaddictioncenters.org/marijuana-rehab/what-can-marijuana-be-laced-with \"What Can Marijuana Be Laced With?\"], ''American Addiction Centers'', updated Nov. 26, 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/opinion/oped/bs-ed-op-1207-fentanyl-opioid-20181206-story.html \"Is the opioid epidemic now the fentanyl epidemic?\"], ''The Baltimore Sun'', Dec. 7, 2018</ref>{{efn|Advocates of legalizing marijuana for recreational use, such as Illinois state Senator [[Heather Steans]], has said that legalizing it would help reduce such hazardous added drugs: \"Over 95 percent are buying it on the black market. You don't know what you\u2019re buying. It's not a safe product. We've seen it laced with rat poison, fentanyl, all sorts of things. It's funding the cartels and other criminal activity.\"<ref>[https://www.sj-r.com/news/20181215/medical-officials-oppose-effort-to-legalize-recreational-use-of-marijuana \"Medical officials oppose effort to legalize recreational use of marijuana\"], ''State Journal-Register'', (Springfield, IL), Dec. 15, 2018</ref>}}\n\n===Long term===\nHeavy, long-term exposure to marijuana may have biologically based physical, mental, behavioral and social health consequences and may be \"associated with diseases of the liver (particularly with co-existing [[hepatitis C]]), lungs, heart, and vasculature\".<ref name=\"Gordon2013\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Gordon AJ, Conley JW, Gordon JM|title=Medical consequences of marijuana use: a review of current literature|journal=Current Psychiatry Reports|volume=15|issue=12|pages=419|date=December 2013|pmid=24234874|doi=10.1007/s11920-013-0419-7|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1232874}}</ref> Mothers who used marijuana during pregnancy have children with more depression, hyperactivity, and inattention.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nomura |first1=Y |last2=Marks |first2=DJ |last3=Halperin |first3=JM |title=Prenatal exposure to maternal and paternal smoking on attention deficit hyperactivity disorders symptoms and diagnosis in offspring. |journal=The Journal of Nervous and Mental Disease |date=September 2010 |volume=198 |issue=9 |pages=672\u20138 |doi=10.1097/NMD.0b013e3181ef3489 |pmid=20823730|pmc=3124822 }}</ref> It is recommended that cannabis use be stopped before and during [[pregnancy]] as it can result in negative outcomes for both the mother and baby.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Committee Opinion No. 637: Marijuana Use During Pregnancy and Lactation|journal=Obstetrics and Gynecology|volume=126|issue=1|pages=234\u20138|date=July 2015|pmid=26241291|doi=10.1097/01.AOG.0000467192.89321.a6|author1=American College of Obstetricians Gynecologists Committee on Obstetric Practice}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Gunn JK, Rosales CB, Center KE, Nu\u00f1ez A, Gibson SJ, Christ C, Ehiri JE|title=Prenatal exposure to cannabis and maternal and child health outcomes: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=BMJ Open|volume=6|issue=4|pages=e009986|date=April 2016|pmid=27048634|pmc=4823436|doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2015-009986}}</ref> However, maternal use of marijuana during pregnancy does not appear to be associated with low birth weight or early delivery after controlling for tobacco use and other confounding factors.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors = Conner SN, Bedell V, Lipsey K, Macones GA, Cahill AG, Tuuli MG|title=Maternal Marijuana Use and Adverse Neonatal Outcomes: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis|journal=Obstetrics and Gynecology|volume=128|issue=4|pages=713\u201323|date=October 2016|pmid=27607879|doi=10.1097/AOG.0000000000001649}}</ref> A 2014 review found that while cannabis use may be less harmful than alcohol use, the recommendation to substitute it for [[alcoholism|problematic drinking]] was premature without further study.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Subbaraman MS|title = Can cannabis be considered a substitute medication for alcohol?|journal=Alcohol and Alcoholism|volume=49|issue=3|pages=292\u20138|date=8 January 2014|pmid=24402247|pmc=3992908|doi=10.1093/alcalc/agt182}}</ref> Various surveys conducted between 2015 and 2019 found that many users of cannabis substitute it for prescription drugs (including opioids), alcohol, and tobacco; most of those who used it in place of alcohol or tobacco either reduced or stopped their intake of the latter substances.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/opinion/healthcare/428593-marijuana-access-is-associated-with-decreased-use-of-alcohol-tobacco-and|title=Marijuana access is associated with decreased use of alcohol, tobacco and other prescription drugs|last=Armentano|first=Paul|date=5 February 2019|work=The Hill}}</ref>\n\nA limited number of studies have examined the [[Cannabis-associated respiratory disease|effects of cannabis smoking]] on the respiratory system.<ref name=\"MaistoGalizio2014\">{{cite book | first1 = Stephen | last1 = Maisto | first2 = Mark | last2 = Galizio | first3 = Gerard | last3 = Connors | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drug Use and Abuse|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5F08AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA278|year=2014|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-305-17759-8|page=278}}</ref> Chronic heavy marijuana smoking is associated with coughing, production of sputum, wheezing, and other symptoms of chronic bronchitis.<ref name=\"W. Hall, N. Solowij 1611\u201316\"/> The available evidence does not support a causal relationship between cannabis use and [[chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Owen KP, Sutter ME, Albertson TE | title = Marijuana: respiratory tract effects | journal = Clinical Reviews in Allergy & Immunology | volume = 46 | issue = 1 | pages = 65\u201381 | date = February 2014 | pmid = 23715638 | doi = 10.1007/s12016-013-8374-y }}</ref> Short-term use of cannabis is associated with [[bronchodilation]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Tetrault JM, Crothers K, Moore BA, Mehra R, Concato J, Fiellin DA | title = Effects of marijuana smoking on pulmonary function and respiratory complications: a systematic review | journal = Archives of Internal Medicine | volume = 167 | issue = 3 | pages = 221\u20138 | date = February 2007 | pmid = 17296876 | pmc = 2720277 | doi = 10.1001/archinte.167.3.221 }}</ref> Other side effects of cannabis use include [[cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome]] (CHS).<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Sorensen CJ, DeSanto K, Borgelt L, Phillips KT, Monte AA|title=Cannabinoid Hyperemesis Syndrome: Diagnosis, Pathophysiology, and Treatment-a Systematic Review|journal=Journal of Medical Toxicology|volume=13|issue=1|pages=71\u201387|date=March 2017|pmid=28000146|pmc=5330965|doi=10.1007/s13181-016-0595-z}}</ref>\n\nCannabis smoke contains thousands of organic and inorganic chemical compounds. This [[tar (tobacco residue)|tar]] is chemically similar to that found in tobacco smoke,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hashibe M, Straif K, Tashkin DP, Morgenstern H, Greenland S, Zhang ZF | title = Epidemiologic review of marijuana use and cancer risk | journal = Alcohol | volume = 35 | issue = 3 | pages = 265\u201375 | date = April 2005 | pmid = 16054989 | doi = 10.1016/j.alcohol.2005.04.008 }}</ref> and over fifty known [[carcinogen]]s have been identified in cannabis smoke,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Does smoking cannabis cause cancer? |publisher=Cancer Research UK |date=2010-09-20 |url=http://cancerhelp.cancerresearchuk.org/about-cancer/cancer-questions/does-smoking-cannabis-cause-cancer |access-date=2013-01-09 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729115046/http://cancerhelp.cancerresearchuk.org/about-cancer/cancer-questions/does-smoking-cannabis-cause-cancer |archive-date=2012-07-29 |df= }}</ref> including; nitrosamines, reactive aldehydes, and [[Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon|polycylic hydrocarbons]], including benz[a]pyrene.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tashkin |first=Donald |date=March 1997 |title=Effects of marijuana on the lung and its immune defenses |publisher=UCLA School of Medicine |url=http://www.ukcia.org/research/EffectsOfMarijuanaOnLungAndImmuneDefenses.php |access-date=2012-06-23}}</ref> Cannabis smoke is also inhaled more deeply than tobacco smoke.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gates P, Jaffe A, Copeland J | title = Cannabis smoking and respiratory health: consideration of the literature | journal = Respirology | volume = 19 | issue = 5 | pages = 655\u201362 | date = July 2014 | pmid = 24831571 | doi = 10.1111/resp.12298 }}</ref> {{as of|2015}}, there is no consensus regarding whether cannabis smoking is associated with an increased risk of cancer.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Huang YH, Zhang ZF, Tashkin DP, Feng B, Straif K, Hashibe M | title = An epidemiologic review of marijuana and cancer: an update | journal = Cancer Epidemiology, Biomarkers & Prevention | volume = 24 | issue = 1 | pages = 15\u201331 | date = January 2015 | pmid = 25587109 | pmc = 4302404 | doi = 10.1158/1055-9965.EPI-14-1026 }}</ref> Light and moderate use of cannabis is not believed to increase risk of lung or upper airway cancer. Evidence for causing these cancers is mixed concerning heavy, long-term use. In general there are far lower risks of pulmonary complications for regular cannabis smokers when compared with those of tobacco.<ref name=\"Tashkin2013\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tashkin DP | title = Effects of marijuana smoking on the lung | journal = Annals of the American Thoracic Society | volume = 10 | issue = 3 | pages = 239\u201347 | date = June 2013 | pmid = 23802821 | doi = 10.1513/annalsats.201212-127fr }}</ref> A 2015 review found an association between cannabis use and the development of testicular [[germ cell tumor]]s (TGCTs), particularly non-[[seminoma]] TGCTs.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gurney J, Shaw C, Stanley J, Signal V, Sarfati D | title = Cannabis exposure and risk of testicular cancer: a systematic review and meta-analysis | journal = BMC Cancer | volume = 15 | issue = 1 | pages = 897 | date = November 2015 | pmid = 26560314 | pmc = 4642772 | doi = 10.1186/s12885-015-1905-6 }}</ref> Another 2015 meta-analysis found no association between lifetime cannabis use and risk of head or neck cancer.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = de Carvalho MF, Dourado MR, Fernandes IB, Ara\u00fajo CT, Mesquita AT, Ramos-Jorge ML | title = Head and neck cancer among marijuana users: a meta-analysis of matched case-control studies | journal = Archives of Oral Biology | volume = 60 | issue = 12 | pages = 1750\u20135 | date = December 2015 | pmid = 26433192 | doi = 10.1016/j.archoralbio.2015.09.009 }}</ref> Combustion products are not present when using a [[Vaporizer (inhalation device)|vaporizer]], consuming THC in pill form, or consuming [[cannabis foods]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Loflin M, Earleywine M | title = No smoke, no fire: What the initial literature suggests regarding vapourized cannabis and respiratory risk | journal = Canadian Journal of Respiratory Therapy | volume = 51 | issue = 1 | pages = 7\u20139 | date = 2015 | pmid = 26078621 | pmc = 4456813 | doi =  }}</ref>\n\nThere is concern that cannabis may contribute to cardiovascular disease,<ref name=\"Riecher-R\u00f6ssler2014a\">{{cite book| vauthors = Riecher-R\u00f6ssler A |title=Comorbidity of Mental and Physical Disorders|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_pDgBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA88|year=2014|publisher=Karger Medical and Scientific Publishers|isbn=978-3-318-02604-7|page=88}}</ref> but as of 2018, evidence of this relationship was unclear.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ravi D, Ghasemiesfe M, Korenstein D, Cascino T, Keyhani S | title = Associations Between Marijuana Use and Cardiovascular Risk Factors and Outcomes: A Systematic Review | journal = Annals of Internal Medicine | volume = 168 | issue = 3 | pages = 187\u2013194 | date = February 2018 | pmid = 29357394 | pmc = 6157910 | doi = 10.7326/M17-1548 }}</ref> Research in these events is complicated because cannabis is often used in conjunction with tobacco, and drugs such as alcohol and cocaine.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Thomas G, Kloner RA, Rezkalla S | title = Adverse cardiovascular, cerebrovascular, and peripheral vascular effects of marijuana inhalation: what cardiologists need to know | journal = The American Journal of Cardiology | volume = 113 | issue = 1 | pages = 187\u201390 | date = January 2014 | pmid = 24176069 | doi = 10.1016/j.amjcard.2013.09.042 }}</ref> Smoking cannabis has also been shown to increase the risk of [[myocardial infarction]] by 4.8 times for the 60 minutes after consumption.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Franz CA, Frishman WH | title = Marijuana Use and Cardiovascular Disease | journal = Cardiology in Review | volume = 24 | issue = 4 | pages = 158\u201362 | date = 9 February 2016 | pmid = 26886465 | doi = 10.1097/CRD.0000000000000103 }}</ref>\n\n====Neuroimaging====\nAlthough global abnormalities in [[white matter]] and [[grey matter]] are not associated with cannabis abuse, reduced [[hippocampus|hippocampal]] volume is consistently found. [[Amygdala]]r abnormalities are sometimes reported, although findings are inconsistent.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Rocchetti M, Crescini A, Borgwardt S, Caverzasi E, Politi P, Atakan Z, Fusar-Poli P | title = Is cannabis neurotoxic for the healthy brain? A meta-analytical review of structural brain alterations in non-psychotic users | journal = Psychiatry and Clinical Neurosciences | volume = 67 | issue = 7 | pages = 483\u201392 | date = November 2013 | pmid = 24118193 | doi = 10.1111/pcn.12085 }}</ref><ref name=\"Batalla2013\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Batalla A, Bhattacharyya S, Y\u00fccel M, Fusar-Poli P, Crippa JA, Nogu\u00e9 S, Torrens M, Pujol J, Farr\u00e9 M, Martin-Santos R | title = Structural and functional imaging studies in chronic cannabis users: a systematic review of adolescent and adult findings | journal = PLOS One | volume = 8 | issue = 2 | pages = e55821 | date = 2013 | pmid = 23390554 | pmc = 3563634 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0055821 | quote = The most consistently reported brain alteration was reduced hippocampal volume which was shown to persist even after several months of abstinence in one study and also to be related to the amount of cannabis use Other frequently reported morphological brain alterations related to chronic cannabis use were reported in the amygdala the cerebellum and the frontal cortex...These findings may be interpreted as reflecting neuroadaptation, perhaps indicating the recruitment of additional regions as a compensatory mechanism to maintain normal cognitive performance in response to chronic cannabis exposure, particularly within the prefrontal cortex area. | bibcode = 2013PLoSO...855821B }}</ref><ref name=\"Weinstein2016\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Weinstein A, Livny A, Weizman A | title = Brain Imaging Studies on the Cognitive, Pharmacological and Neurobiological Effects of Cannabis in Humans: Evidence from Studies of Adult Users | journal = Current Pharmaceutical Design | volume = 22 | issue = 42 | pages = 6366\u20136379 | date = 2016 | pmid = 27549374 | doi = 10.2174/1381612822666160822151323 | quote = 1)The studies reviewed so far demonstrated that chronic cannabis use has been associated with a volume reduction of the hippocampus...3)The overall conclusion arising from these studies is that recent cannabis users may experience subtle neurophysiological deficits while performing on working memory tasks, and that they compensate for these deficits by \"working harder\" by using additional brain regions to meet the demands of the task. }}</ref>  Preliminary evidence suggests that this effect is largely mediated by THC, and that CBD may even have a protective effect.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lorenzetti V, Solowij N, Y\u00fccel M | title = The Role of Cannabinoids in Neuroanatomic Alterations in Cannabis Users | journal = Biological Psychiatry | volume = 79 | issue = 7 | pages = e17\u201331 | date = April 2016 | pmid = 26858212 | doi = 10.1016/j.biopsych.2015.11.013 }}</ref>\n\nCannabis use is associated with increased recruitment of task-related areas, such as the [[dorsolateral prefrontal cortex]], which is thought to reflect compensatory activity due to reduced processing efficiency.<ref name=\"Weinstein2016\"/><ref name=\"Batalla2013\"/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Blest-Hopley G, Giampietro V, Bhattacharyya S | title = Residual effects of cannabis use in adolescent and adult brains \u2013 A meta-analysis of fMRI studies | journal = Neuroscience and Biobehavioral Reviews | volume = 88 | pages = 26\u201341 | date = May 2018 | pmid = 29535069 | doi = 10.1016/j.neubiorev.2018.03.008 | quote = This may reflect the multitude of cognitive tasks employed by the various studies included in these meta-analyses, all of which involved performing a task thereby requiring the participant to reorient their attention and attempt to solve the problem at hand and suggest that greater engagement of this region indicates less efficient cognitive performance in cannabis users in general, irrespective of their age.| url = https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/files/88441182/Residual_effects_of_cannabis_BLEST_HOPLEY_Publishedonline10March2018_GREEN_AAM_CC_BY_NC_ND_.pdf }}</ref> Cannabis use is also associated with downregulation of [[Cannabinoid receptor type 1|CB<sub>1</sub>]] receptors.  The magnitude of down regulation is associated with cumulative cannabis exposure, and is reversed after one month of abstinence.<ref name=\"Curran2016\"/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Parsons LH, Hurd YL | title = Endocannabinoid signalling in reward and addiction | journal = Nature Reviews. Neuroscience | volume = 16 | issue = 10 | pages = 579\u201394 | date = October 2015 | pmid = 26373473 | pmc = 4652927 | doi = 10.1038/nrn4004 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Zehra A, Burns J, Liu CK, Manza P, Wiers CE, Volkow ND, Wang GJ | title = Cannabis Addiction and the Brain: a Review | journal = Journal of Neuroimmune Pharmacology | volume = 13 | issue = 4 | pages = 438\u2013452 | date = March 2018 | pmid = 29556883 | pmc = 6223748 | doi = 10.1007/s11481-018-9782-9 }}</ref> There is limited evidence that chronic cannabis use can reduce levels of [[glutamate]] metabolites in the human brain.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Colizzi M, McGuire P, Pertwee RG, Bhattacharyya S | title = Effect of cannabis on glutamate signalling in the brain: A systematic review of human and animal evidence | journal = Neuroscience and Biobehavioral Reviews | volume = 64 | pages = 359\u201381 | date = May 2016 | pmid = 26987641 | doi = 10.1016/j.neubiorev.2016.03.010 | url = https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/effect-of-cannabis-on-glutamate-signalling-in-the-brain-a-systematic-review-of-human-and-animal-evidence(9b3d72d2-d3ae-44a6-b9a5-4c13e9690b9d).html }}</ref>\n\n====Cognition====\nA 2015 meta analysis found that, although a longer period of abstinence was associated with smaller magnitudes of impairment, both retrospective and prospective memory were impaired in cannabis users.  The authors concluded that some, but not all, of the deficits associated with cannabis use were reversible.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Schoeler T, Kambeitz J, Behlke I, Murray R, Bhattacharyya S | title = The effects of cannabis on memory function in users with and without psychotic disorder: findings from a combined meta-analysis | journal = Psychological Medicine | volume = 46 | issue = 1 | pages = 177\u201388 | date = January 2016 | pmid = 26353818 | doi = 10.1017/S0033291715001646 | url = https://epub.ub.uni-muenchen.de/43978/ }}</ref>  A 2012 meta analysis found that deficits in most domains of cognition persisted beyond the acute period of intoxication, but was not evident in studies where subjects were abstinent for more than 25 days.<ref name=\"Schreiner 2012\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Schreiner AM, Dunn ME | title = Residual effects of cannabis use on neurocognitive performance after prolonged abstinence: a meta-analysis | journal = Experimental and Clinical Psychopharmacology | volume = 20 | issue = 5 | pages = 420\u2013429 | date = October 2012 | pmid = 22731735 | doi = 10.1037/a0029117 | quote = Therefore, results indicate evidence for small neurocognitive effects that persist after the period of acute intoxication...As hypothesized, the meta-analysis conducted on studies eval- uating users after at least 25 days of abstention found no residual effects on cognitive performance...These results fail to support the idea that heavy cannabis use may result in long-term, persistent effects on neuropsychological functioning. }}</ref>  Few high quality studies have been performed on the long-term effects of cannabis on cognition, and the results were generally inconsistent.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gonzalez R, Carey C, Grant I | title = Nonacute (residual) neuropsychological effects of cannabis use: a qualitative analysis and systematic review | journal = Journal of Clinical Pharmacology | volume = 42 | issue = S1 | pages = 48S\u201357S | date = November 2002 | pmid = 12412836 | doi = 10.1002/j.1552-4604.2002.tb06003.x }}</ref>  Furthermore, [[effect size]]s of significant findings were generally small.<ref name=\"Schreiner 2012\"/>  One review concluded that, although most cognitive faculties were unimpaired by cannabis use, residual deficits occurred in [[executive function]]s.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Crean RD, Crane NA, Mason BJ | title = An evidence based review of acute and long-term effects of cannabis use on executive cognitive functions | journal = Journal of Addiction Medicine | volume = 5 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u20138 | date = March 2011 | pmid = 21321675 | pmc = 3037578 | doi = 10.1097/ADM.0b013e31820c23fa | quote = Cannabis appears to continue to exert impairing effects in executive functions even after 3 weeks of abstinence and beyond. While basic attentional and working memory abilities are largely restored, the most enduring and detectable deficits are seen in decision-making, concept formation and planning. }}</ref>  Impairments in executive functioning are most consistently found in older populations, which may reflect heavier cannabis exposure, or developmental effects associated with adolescent cannabis use.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Broyd SJ, van Hell HH, Beale C, Y\u00fccel M, Solowij N | title = Acute and Chronic Effects of Cannabinoids on Human Cognition-A Systematic Review | journal = Biological Psychiatry | volume = 79 | issue = 7 | pages = 557\u201367 | date = April 2016 | pmid = 26858214 | doi = 10.1016/j.biopsych.2015.12.002 | url = http://ro.uow.edu.au/sspapers/2164 }}</ref> One review found three prospective cohort studies that examined the relationship between self reported cannabis use and [[intelligence quotient|intelligence quotient (IQ)]].  The study following the largest number of heavy cannabis users reported that IQ declined between ages 7\u201313 and age 38. Poorer school performance and increased incidence of leaving school early were both associated with cannabis use, although a causal relationship was not established.<ref name=\"Curran2016\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Curran HV, Freeman TP, Mokrysz C, Lewis DA, Morgan CJ, Parsons LH | title = Keep off the grass? Cannabis, cognition and addiction | journal = Nature Reviews. Neuroscience | volume = 17 | issue = 5 | pages = 293\u2013306 | date = May 2016 | pmid = 27052382 | doi = 10.1038/nrn.2016.28 | url = http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1489385/1/Curran%2520et%2520al%2520NRN-2016%2520pdf.pdf }}</ref> Cannabis users demonstrated increased activity in task-related brain regions, consistent with reduced processing efficiency.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ganzer F, Br\u00f6ning S, Kraft S, Sack PM, Thomasius R | title = Weighing the Evidence: A Systematic Review on Long-Term Neurocognitive Effects of Cannabis Use in Abstinent Adolescents and Adults | journal = Neuropsychology Review | volume = 26 | issue = 2 | pages = 186\u2013222 | date = June 2016 | pmid = 27125202 | doi = 10.1007/s11065-016-9316-2 }}</ref>\n\n===Psychiatric===\n{{See also|Cannabis and psychosis}}\nAt an epidemiological level, a [[dose\u2013response relationship]] exists between cannabis use and increased risk of [[psychosis]]<ref name=Leweke2016rev/><ref name=\"Marconi2016\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Marconi A, Di Forti M, Lewis CM, Murray RM, Vassos E | title = Meta-analysis of the Association Between the Level of Cannabis Use and Risk of Psychosis | journal = Schizophrenia Bulletin | volume = 42 | issue = 5 | pages = 1262\u20139 | date = September 2016 | pmid = 26884547 | pmc = 4988731 | doi = 10.1093/schbul/sbw003 }}</ref><ref name=\"Moore 2007\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Moore TH, Zammit S, Lingford-Hughes A, Barnes TR, Jones PB, Burke M, Lewis G | title = Cannabis use and risk of psychotic or affective mental health outcomes: a systematic review | journal = Lancet | volume = 370 | issue = 9584 | pages = 319\u201328 | date = July 2007 | pmid = 17662880 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(07)61162-3 | url = http://orca.cf.ac.uk/619/1/Appendix%201%20%28search%20strategy%29%20Cannabis%20use%20and%20risk%20of%20developing%20psychotic%20or%20affective%20mental%20health%20outcomes%20a%20systematic%20review.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Semple DM, McIntosh AM, Lawrie SM | title = Cannabis as a risk factor for psychosis: systematic review | journal = Journal of Psychopharmacology | volume = 19 | issue = 2 | pages = 187\u201394 | date = March 2005 | pmid = 15871146 | doi = 10.1177/0269881105049040 }}</ref> and earlier onset of psychosis.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Large M, Sharma S, Compton MT, Slade T, Nielssen O | title = Cannabis use and earlier onset of psychosis: a systematic meta-analysis | journal = Archives of General Psychiatry | volume = 68 | issue = 6 | pages = 555\u201361 | date = June 2011 | pmid = 21300939 | doi = 10.1001/archgenpsychiatry.2011.5 }}</ref> Although the epidemiological association is robust, evidence to prove a causal relationship is lacking.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = McLaren JA, Silins E, Hutchinson D, Mattick RP, Hall W | title = Assessing evidence for a causal link between cannabis and psychosis: a review of cohort studies | journal = The International Journal on Drug Policy | volume = 21 | issue = 1 | pages = 10\u20139 | date = January 2010 | pmid = 19783132 | doi = 10.1016/j.drugpo.2009.09.001 | quote = The contentious issue of whether cannabis use can cause serious psychotic disorders that would not otherwise have occurred cannot be answered based on the existing data }}</ref>  But a biological causal pathway is plausible, especially if there is a genetic predisposition to mental illness, in which case cannabis may be a trigger.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/17/health/cannabis-marijuana-schizophrenia|title=Does Marijuana Use Cause Schizophrenia?|last=Carey|first=Benedict|date=2019-01-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-01-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\nIt is not clear whether cannabis use affects the rate of suicide.<ref name=\"Calabria2010\"/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Borges G, Bagge CL, Orozco R | title = A literature review and meta-analyses of cannabis use and suicidality | journal = Journal of Affective Disorders | volume = 195 | pages = 63\u201374 | date = May 2016 | pmid = 26872332 | doi = 10.1016/j.jad.2016.02.007 }}</ref> Cannabis may also increase the risk of depression, but insufficient research has been performed to draw a conclusion.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lev-Ran S, Roerecke M, Le Foll B, George TP, McKenzie K, Rehm J | title = The association between cannabis use and depression: a systematic review and meta-analysis of longitudinal studies | journal = Psychological Medicine | volume = 44 | issue = 4 | pages = 797\u2013810 | date = March 2014 | pmid = 23795762 | doi = 10.1017/S0033291713001438 }}</ref><ref name=\"Moore 2007\"/>  Cannabis use is associated with increased risk of anxiety disorders, although causality has not been established.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kedzior KK, Laeber LT | title = A positive association between anxiety disorders and cannabis use or cannabis use disorders in the general population\u2014a meta-analysis of 31 studies | journal = BMC Psychiatry | volume = 14 | pages = 136 | date = May 2014 | pmid = 24884989 | pmc = 4032500 | doi = 10.1186/1471-244X-14-136 }}</ref>\n\nA February 2019 review found that cannabis use during adolescence was associated with an increased risk of developing depression and suicidal behavior later in life, while finding no effect on anxiety.<ref name=\"Gobbi\">{{cite journal | last=Gobbi | first=Gabriella | last2=Atkin | first2=Tobias | last3=Zytynski | first3=Tomasz | last4=Wang | first4=Shouao | last5=Askari | first5=Sorayya | last6=Boruff | first6=Jill | last7=Ware | first7=Mark | last8=Marmorstein | first8=Naomi | last9=Cipriani | first9=Andrea | last10=Dendukuri | first10=Nandini | last11=Mayo | first11=Nancy | title=Cannabis Use in Adolescence and Risk of Depression, Anxiety, and Suicidality in Young Adulthood | journal=JAMA Psychiatry | volume=76 | issue=4 | pages=426\u2013434 | date=13 February 2019 | doi=10.1001/jamapsychiatry.2018.4500 | pmid=30758486 | pmc=6450286 }}</ref>\n\n===Reinforcement disorders===\n{{Main|Cannabis dependence}}\nAbout 9% of those who experiment with marijuana eventually become dependent according to [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders|DSM-IV (1994)]] criteria.<ref name=\"NEJM2014\"/>  A 2013 review estimates daily use is associated with a 10\u201320% rate of dependence.<ref name=\"Borgelt2013\"/> The highest risk of cannabis dependence is found in those with a history of poor academic achievement, deviant behavior in childhood and adolescence, rebelliousness, poor parental relationships, or a parental history of drug and alcohol problems.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hall W, Degenhardt L | title = Adverse health effects of non-medical cannabis use | journal = Lancet | volume = 374 | issue = 9698 | pages = 1383\u201391 | date = October 2009 | pmid = 19837255 | doi = 10.1016/s0140-6736(09)61037-0 }}</ref>  Of daily users, about 50% experience withdrawal upon cessation of use (i.e. are dependent), characterized by sleep problems, irritability, dysphoria, and craving.<ref name=\"Curran2016\"/>  Cannabis withdrawal is less severe than withdrawal from alcohol.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Subbaraman MS | title = Can cannabis be considered a substitute medication for alcohol? | journal = Alcohol and Alcoholism | volume = 49 | issue = 3 | pages = 292\u20138 | date = 2014 | pmid = 24402247 | pmc = 3992908 | doi = 10.1093/alcalc/agt182 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[DSM-V]] criteria, 9% of those who are exposed to cannabis develop cannabis use disorder, compared to 20% for [[cocaine]], 23% for [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]] and 68% for [[nicotine]].  Cannabis abuse disorder in the DSM-V involves a combination of DSM-IV criteria for cannabis abuse and dependence, plus the addition of craving, minus the criterion related to legal troubles.<ref name=\"Curran2016\"/>\n\n==Overdose==\nTHC, the principal [[psychoactive constituent]] of the cannabis plant, has low [[toxicity]]. The dose of THC needed to kill 50% of tested rodents is extremely high. Cannabis has not been reported to cause fatal [[overdose]] in humans.<ref name=\"Calabria2010\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Calabria B, Degenhardt L, Hall W, Lynskey M | title = Does cannabis use increase the risk of death? Systematic review of epidemiological evidence on adverse effects of cannabis use | journal = Drug and Alcohol Review | volume = 29 | issue = 3 | pages = 318\u201330 | date = May 2010 | pmid = 20565525 | doi = 10.1111/j.1465-3362.2009.00149.x }}</ref>\n\n==Pharmacology==\n\n===Mechanism of action===\n{{see also|Effects of cannabis#Biochemical mechanisms in the brain}}\nThe high [[lipophilicity|lipid-solubility]] of cannabinoids results in their persisting in the body for long periods of time.<ref name=\"HallPacula2003hj\">{{cite book| first1 = Wayne | last1 = Hall | first2 = Rosalie Liccardo | last2 = Pacula | name-list-format = vanc|title=Cannabis Use and Dependence: Public Health and Public Policy|url=https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence| url-access = registration |year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-80024-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence/page/n12 15]}}</ref> Even after a single administration of THC, detectable levels of THC can be found in the body for weeks or longer (depending on the amount administered and the sensitivity of the assessment method).<ref name=\"HallPacula2003hj\" /> A number of investigators have suggested that this is an important factor in marijuana's effects, perhaps because cannabinoids may accumulate in the body, particularly in the lipid membranes of neurons.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.lycaeum.org/drugwar/marij1.html | first = Leo E. | last = Hollister  | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 1986 |title=Health aspects of cannabis |journal=Pharma Review |issue=38 |pages=1\u201320 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130415094338/http://www.lycaeum.org/drugwar/marij1.html |archive-date=2013-04-15 |access-date=2011-02-17 |display-authors=etal |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nNot until the end of the 20th century was the specific mechanism of action of THC at the neuronal level studied.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}} Researchers have subsequently confirmed that THC exerts its most prominent effects via its actions on two types of [[cannabinoid receptors]], the [[CB1 receptor|CB<sub>1</sub> receptor]] and the [[CB2 receptor|CB<sub>2</sub> receptor]], both of which are [[G protein-coupled receptor]]s.<ref name=\"IovannaIsmailov2009\">{{cite book | first1 = Juan | last1 = Iovanna | first2 = Uktam | last2 = Ismailov | name-list-format = vanc |title=Pancreatology: From Bench to Bedside|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3B5dp9BXaKwC&pg=PA40|year=2009|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-642-00152-9|page=40}}</ref> The CB<sub>1</sub> receptor is found primarily in the brain as well as in some peripheral tissues, and the CB<sub>2</sub> receptor is found primarily in peripheral tissues, but is also expressed in [[neuroglia|neuroglial cells]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wilson RI, Nicoll RA | title = Endocannabinoid signaling in the brain | journal = Science | volume = 296 | issue = 5568 | pages = 678\u201382 | date = April 2002 | pmid = 11976437 | doi = 10.1126/science.1063545 | bibcode = 2002Sci...296..678W }}</ref> THC appears to alter mood and cognition through its agonist actions on the CB<sub>1</sub> receptors, which inhibit a [[secondary messenger system]] ([[adenylate cyclase]]) in a dose-dependent manner. These actions can be blocked by the selective CB<sub>1</sub> receptor [[receptor antagonist|antagonist]] [[rimonabant]] (SR141716), which has been shown in clinical trials to be an effective treatment for [[smoking cessation]], [[weight loss]], and as a means of controlling or reducing [[metabolic syndrome]] risk factors.<ref name=\"pmid15134285\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fernandez JR, Allison DB | title = Rimonabant Sanofi-Synth\u00e9labo | journal = Current Opinion in Investigational Drugs | volume = 5 | issue = 4 | pages = 430\u20135 | date = April 2004 | pmid = 15134285 | doi = | url = }}</ref> However, due to the [[dysphoria|dysphoric]] effect of CB<sub>1</sub> receptor antagonists, this drug is often discontinued due to these side effects.<ref name=\"RahmanReitz2005\">{{cite book| first1 = Atta | last1 = Ur-Rahman | first2 = Allen B. | last2 = Reitz | name-list-format = vanc |title=Frontiers in Medicinal Chemistry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tCyDoIHToBQC&pg=PA150|year=2005|publisher=Bentham Science Publishers|isbn=978-1-60805-205-9|page=150}}</ref>\n\nVia CB<sub>1</sub> receptor activation, THC indirectly increases [[dopamine]] release and produces [[psychotropic]] effects.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Oleson EB, Cheer JF | title = A brain on cannabinoids: the role of dopamine release in reward seeking | journal = Cold Spring Harbor Perspectives in Medicine | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = a012229 | date = August 2012 | pmid = 22908200 | pmc = 3405830 | doi = 10.1101/cshperspect.a012229 }}</ref> [[Cannabidiol]] (CBD) also acts as an [[allosteric modulator]] of the [[\u03bc-opioid receptor|\u03bc-]] and [[\u03b4-opioid receptor]]s.<ref name=\"pmid16489449\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kathmann M, Flau K, Redmer A, Tr\u00e4nkle C, Schlicker E | title = Cannabidiol is an allosteric modulator at mu- and delta-opioid receptors | journal = Naunyn-Schmiedeberg's Archives of Pharmacology | volume = 372 | issue = 5 | pages = 354\u201361 | date = February 2006 | pmid = 16489449 | doi = 10.1007/s00210-006-0033-x }}</ref> THC also potentiates the effects of the [[glycine receptor]]s.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hejazi N, Zhou C, Oz M, Sun H, Ye JH, Zhang L | title = Delta9-tetrahydrocannabinol and endogenous cannabinoid anandamide directly potentiate the function of glycine receptors | journal = Molecular Pharmacology | volume = 69 | issue = 3 | pages = 991\u20137 | date = March 2006 | pmid = 16332990 | doi = 10.1124/mol.105.019174 }}</ref> It is unknown if or how these actions contribute to the effects of cannabis.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Xiong W, Cheng K, Cui T, Godlewski G, Rice KC, Xu Y, Zhang L | title = Cannabinoid potentiation of glycine receptors contributes to cannabis-induced analgesia | journal = Nature Chemical Biology | volume = 7 | issue = 5 | pages = 296\u2013303 | date = May 2011 | pmid = 21460829 | pmc = 3388539 | doi = 10.1038/nchembio.552 }}</ref>\n\n==Chemistry==\n===Detection in body fluids===\n{{Main|Cannabis drug testing}}\n\nTHC and its major (inactive) metabolite, THC-COOH, can be measured in blood, urine, hair, oral fluid or sweat using [[chromatographic]] techniques as part of a drug use testing program or a forensic investigation of a traffic or other criminal offense.<ref name=\"Barceloux2012\">{{cite book| first= Donald G. | last = Barceloux | name-list-format = vanc |title=Medical Toxicology of Drug Abuse: Synthesized Chemicals and Psychoactive Plants | chapter = Chapter 60: Marijuana (Cannabis sativa L.) and synthetic cannabinoids |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9JLiJcjdqkcC&pg=PA910|access-date=14 July 2013|date=3 February 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-10605-1|pages=910\u2013}}</ref> The concentrations obtained from such analyses can often be helpful in distinguishing active use from passive exposure, elapsed time since use, and extent or duration of use. These tests cannot, however, distinguish authorized cannabis smoking for medical purposes from unauthorized recreational smoking.<ref name=\"Baselt2008\">{{cite book | first = Randall Clint | last = Baselt  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Disposition of Toxic Drugs and Chemicals in Man |year=2008 |publisher=Biomedical Publications |isbn=978-0-9626523-7-0 |pages=1513\u20131518}}</ref> Commercial cannabinoid [[immunoassay]]s, often employed as the initial screening method when testing physiological specimens for marijuana presence, have different degrees of cross-reactivity with THC and its metabolites.<ref name=\"ShawKwong2001\">{{cite book | first1 = Leslie M. | last1 = Shaw | first2 = Tai C. | last2 = Kwong | name-list-format = vanc |title=The Clinical Toxicology Laboratory: Contemporary Practice of Poisoning Evaluation | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=pXvFGqz44pYC&pg=PA51 |year=2001 |publisher=Amer. Assoc. for Clinical Chemistry |isbn=978-1-890883-53-9 |page=51}}</ref> Urine contains predominantly THC-COOH, while hair, oral fluid and sweat contain primarily THC.<ref name=\"Barceloux2012\" /> Blood may contain both substances, with the relative amounts dependent on the recency and extent of usage.<ref name=\"Barceloux2012\" />\n\nThe [[Duquenois\u2013Levine test]] is commonly used as a [[Presumptive and confirmatory tests|screening test]] in the field, but it cannot definitively confirm the presence of cannabis, as a large range of substances have been shown to give false positives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266888426|title=The Non-Specificity of the Duquenois-Levine Field Test for Marijuana|website=ResearchGate}}</ref> Researchers at John Jay College of Criminal Justice reported that dietary zinc supplements can mask the presence of THC and other drugs in urine.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Venkatratnam A, Lents NH | title = Zinc reduces the detection of cocaine, methamphetamine, and THC by ELISA urine testing | journal = Journal of Analytical Toxicology | volume = 35 | issue = 6 | pages = 333\u201340 | date = July 2011 | pmid = 21740689 | doi = 10.1093/anatox/35.6.333 }}</ref> However, a 2013 study conducted by researchers at the University of Utah School of Medicine refute the possibility of self-administered zinc producing false-negative urine drug tests.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lin CN, Strathmann FG | title = Elevated urine zinc concentration reduces the detection of methamphetamine, cocaine, THC and opiates in urine by EMIT | journal = Journal of Analytical Toxicology | volume = 37 | issue = 9 | pages = 665\u20139 | date = July 10, 2013 | pmid = 23843421 | doi = 10.1093/jat/bkt056 | url = http://jat.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2013/07/09/jat.bkt056.full.pdf }}</ref>\n\n==Varieties and strains==\n[[File:Cannab2 new.png|thumb|right|Types of cannabis]]\n\nCBD is a [[5-HT1A receptor|5-HT<sub>1A</sub> receptor]] agonist, which may also contribute to an [[anxiolytic]] effect.<ref name=\"joy\">{{Cite book |title=Marijuana and Medicine: Assessing The Science Base |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences Press]] |year=1999 |url=https://www.nap.edu/catalog/6376/marijuana-and-medicine-assessing-the-science-base |isbn=978-0-585-05800-9 | vauthors = Joy JE, Watson SJ, Benson JA |doi=10.17226/6376 |pmid=25101425 }}</ref> This likely means the high concentrations of CBD found in ''[[Cannabis indica]]'' mitigate the [[anxiogenic]] effect of THC significantly.<ref name=\"joy\" /> It is often claimed that sativa strains provide a more stimulating psychoactive high while indica strains are more sedating with a body high.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://herb.co/marijuana/news/indica-vs-sativa-whats-the-difference|title=The Ultimate Guide on Indicas vs. Sativas|last=Elliott|first=Steve | name-list-format = vanc |website=Herb|access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref> However this is disputed by researchers.<ref name=\"pmid28861479\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Piomelli D, Russo EB | title = The Cannabis sativa Versus Cannabis indica Debate: An Interview with Ethan Russo, MD | journal = Cannabis and Cannabinoid Research | volume = 1 | issue = 1 | pages = 44\u201346 | date = 2016 | pmid = 28861479 | pmc = 5576603 | doi = 10.1089/can.2015.29003.ebr }}</ref>\n\n===Psychoactive ingredients===\nAccording to the [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] (UNODC), \"the amount of THC present in a cannabis sample is generally used as a measure of cannabis potency.\"<ref name=\"Why Does Cannabis Potency Matter?\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/frontpage/2009/June/why-does-cannabis-potency-matter.html |title=Why Does Cannabis Potency Matter? |date=2009-06-29 |publisher=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime}}</ref> The three main forms of cannabis products are the flower/fruit, resin (hashish), and oil (hash oil). The UNODC states that cannabis often contains 5% THC content, resin \"can contain up to 20% THC content\", and that \"Cannabis oil may contain more than 60% THC content.\"<ref name=\"Why Does Cannabis Potency Matter?\" />\n\nA 2012 review found that the THC content in marijuana had increased worldwide from 1970 to 2009.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cascini F, Aiello C, Di Tanna G | title = Increasing delta-9-tetrahydrocannabinol (\u0394-9-THC) content in herbal cannabis over time: systematic review and meta-analysis | journal = Current Drug Abuse Reviews | volume = 5 | issue = 1 | pages = 32\u201340 | date = March 2012 | pmid = 22150622 | doi = 10.2174/1874473711205010032 }}</ref> It is unclear, however, whether the increase in THC content has caused people to consume more THC or if users adjust based on the potency of the cannabis. It is likely that the higher THC content allows people to ingest less tar. At the same time, CBD levels in seized samples have lowered, in part because of the desire to produce higher THC levels and because more illegal growers cultivate indoors using artificial lights. This helps avoid detection but reduces the CBD production of the plant.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2014/jan/17/cannabis-memory-loss-cbd|title=Cannabis and memory loss: dude, where's my CBD?| first = Dana | last = Smith  | name-list-format = vanc |newspaper=the Guardian|date=2014-01-17}}</ref>\n\nAustralia's [[National Cannabis Prevention and Information Centre]] (NCPIC) states that the buds ([[infructescence]]s) of the female cannabis plant contain the highest concentration of THC, followed by the leaves. The stalks and seeds have \"much lower THC levels\".<ref name=\"urlCannabis Potency\">{{Cite web |url=http://ncpic.org.au/ncpic/publications/factsheets/article/cannabis-potency |title=Cannabis Potency |publisher=National Cannabis Prevention and Information Centre |access-date=2011-12-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111206100249/http://ncpic.org.au/ncpic/publications/factsheets/article/cannabis-potency |archive-date=2011-12-06 |df= }}</ref> The UN states that the leaves can contain ten times less THC than the buds, and the stalks one hundred times less THC.<ref name=\"Why Does Cannabis Potency Matter?\" />\n\nAfter revisions to [[Cannabis reclassification in the United Kingdom|cannabis scheduling]] in the UK, the government moved cannabis back from a [[class C drug|class C]] to a [[class B drug]]. A purported reason was the appearance of high potency cannabis. They believe [[Skunk (cannabis strain)|skunk]] accounts for between 70 and 80% of samples seized by police<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7386889.stm |title=BBC: Cannabis laws to be strengthened. May 2008 20:55 UK |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-05-07 |access-date=2010-09-20}}</ref> (despite the fact that skunk can sometimes be incorrectly mistaken for all types of herbal cannabis).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Di Forti M, Morgan C, Dazzan P, Pariante C, Mondelli V, Marques TR, Handley R, Luzi S, Russo M, Paparelli A, Butt A, Stilo SA, Wiffen B, Powell J, Murray RM | title = High-potency cannabis and the risk of psychosis | journal = The British Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 195 | issue = 6 | pages = 488\u201391 | date = December 2009 | pmid = 19949195 | pmc = 2801827 | doi = 10.1192/bjp.bp.109.064220 | displayauthors = 8 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1577798/Use-of-extra-strong-skunk-cannabis-soars.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Christopher |last=Hope |title=Use of extra strong 'skunk' cannabis soars |date=2008-02-06}}</ref> Extracts such as [[hashish]] and [[hash oil]] typically contain more THC than high potency cannabis infructescences.<ref name=\"Doweiko2011\">{{cite book| first = Harold | last = Doweiko  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Concepts of Chemical Dependency|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RWMIAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA124|year=2011|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-133-17081-5|page=124}}</ref>\n\n==Preparations==\n<gallery>\nFile:Marijuana-Cannabis-Weed-Bud-Gram.jpg|Dried flower buds (marijuana)\nFile:Kief (yellow).jpg|A gram of [[kief]]\nFile:Hashish-2.jpg|Hashish\nFile:Drop of cannabis oil.jpg|Hash oil\nFile:Cannabis Butter.JPG|Infusion (dairy butter)\nFile:Resin.jpg|Pipe residue\n</gallery>\n\n===Marijuana===\n{{further|Marijuana (word)}}\nMarijuana or marihuana (herbal cannabis)<ref name=\"Dictionaries2007m\"/> consists of the dried flowers and fruits and subtending leaves and stems of the female ''Cannabis'' plant.<ref name=\"PotterBouchard2013\">{{cite book| first1 = Gary | last1 = Potter | first2 = Martin | last2 = Bouchard | first3 = Tom | last3 = Decorte | name-list-format = vanc |title=World Wide Weed: Global Trends in Cannabis Cultivation and its Control|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ENOhAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA17 |edition=revised |year=2013 |publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-1-4094-9438-6|page=17}}</ref><ref name=\"HallPacula2003\">{{cite book | first1 = Wayne | last1 = Hall | first2 = Rosalie Liccardo | last2 = Pacula | name-list-format = vanc |title=Cannabis Use and Dependence: Public Health and Public Policy|url=https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence| url-access = registration |year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-80024-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence/page/n10 13]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|title=Recommended Methods for the Identification and Analysis of Cannabis and Cannabis Products|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MLR3bFaUZj0C&pg=PA15|year=2009|publisher=United Nations Publications|isbn=978-92-1-148242-3|page=15}}</ref><ref name=\"Houck2015\">{{cite book|first = Max M. | last = Houck  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Forensic Chemistry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=POpDBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA131|date= 2015|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-0-12-800624-5|page=131}}</ref> This is the most widely consumed form,<ref name=\"Houck2015\"/> containing 3% to 20% THC,<ref name=\"AdlerAdler2012\">{{cite book| first1 = Patricia A. | last1 = Adler | first2 = Peter | last2 = Adler | first3 = Patrick K. | last3 =  O'Brien | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drugs and the American Dream: An Anthology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_s_9tfNlfGkC&pg=PA330|date=February 28, 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=978-0-470-67027-9|pages=330\u2013}}</ref> with reports of up to 33% THC.<ref name=\"MosherAkins2013\">{{cite book| first1 = Clayton J. | last1 = Mosher | first2 = Scott M. | last2 = Akins | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drugs and Drug Policy: The Control of Consciousness Alteration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2UQXBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA17|date=August 20, 2013|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-4833-2188-2|page=17}}</ref> This is the stock material from which all other preparations are derived. Although herbal cannabis and [[Hemp|industrial hemp]] derive from the same species and contain the psychoactive component (THC), they are distinct strains with unique biochemical compositions and uses. Hemp has lower concentrations of THC and higher concentrations of CBD, which gives lesser psychoactive effects.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naihc.org/hemp_information/hemp_facts.html |title=Hemp Facts |publisher=Naihc.org |access-date=2013-01-09}}</ref><ref name=\"Earleywine2002\">{{cite book |last=Earleywine |first=Mitch |title=Understanding Marijuana: A New Look at the Scientific Evidence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QUn92XLQqf8C&pg=PA3|date= 2002|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-988143-7|page=3}}</ref>\n\n===Kief===\n{{Main|Kief}}\n[[Kief]] is a powder, rich in [[trichome]]s,<ref name=\"Rosenthal2002\">{{cite book| first = Ed | last = Rosenthal  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Ask Ed : Marijuana Gold: Trash to Stash|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H_QDJ7CWf2sC&pg=PA116|year=2002|publisher=QUICK AMER Publishing Company|isbn=978-0-932551-52-8|page=116}}</ref> which can be sifted from the leaves, flowers and fruits of [[Cannabis sativa|cannabis plants]] and either [[One hitter (smoking)|consumed in powder form]] or compressed to produce cakes of [[hashish]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cannabisculture.com/articles/4220.html |title=Kief |publisher=Cannabisculture.com |date=2005-03-09 |access-date=2010-01-02 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605025019/http://www.cannabisculture.com/articles/4220.html |archive-date=2009-06-05 |df= }}</ref> The word \"kif\" derives from [[colloquial Arabic]] {{lang|ar|\u0643\u064a\u0641}} ''{{transl|ar|2=k\u0113f<span style=\"margin:1.5px\">/</span>k\u012bf}}'', meaning ''pleasure''.<ref name=\"Bukszpan2012\">{{cite book| first = David | last = Bukszpan  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Is That a Word?: From AA to ZZZ, the Weird and Wonderful Language of SCRABBLE|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eA8vlPcMXTUC&pg=PA94|year=2012|publisher=Chronicle Books|isbn=978-1-4521-0824-7|page=94}}</ref>\n\n===Hashish===\n{{Main|Hashish}}\n\nHashish (also spelled hasheesh, hashisha, or simply hash) is a concentrated [[resin]] cake or ball produced from pressed kief, the detached trichomes and fine material that falls off cannabis fruits, flowers and leaves.<ref name=\"urlHashish - Definitions from Dictionary.com\">{{cite web |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/Hashish |title=Hashish |publisher=dictionary.reference.com}}</ref> or from scraping the resin from the surface of the plants and rolling it into balls. It varies in color from black to golden brown depending upon purity and variety of cultivar it was obtained from.<ref name=\"Castle1\">{{cite book |author=Castle/Murray/D'Souza |title=Marijuana and Madness |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0QqyOSJEeykC&pg=PA35 |year=2004 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1-139-50267-2 |page=35}}</ref> It can be consumed orally or smoked, and is also vaporized, or 'vaped'.<ref name=\"Goldberg2012q\">{{cite book | first = Raymond | last = Goldberg  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drugs Across the Spectrum | edition = 7th |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U9TjZHWVGoIC&pg=PA255 |year=2012 |publisher=Cengage Learning |isbn=978-1-133-59416-1 |page=255}}</ref> The term \"rosin hash\" refers to a high quality solventless product obtained through heat and pressure.<ref>Alchimia Blog, ''[http://www.alchimiaweb.com/blogen/rosin-hash/ Rosin Hash]''</ref>\n\n===Tincture===\n{{main|Tincture of cannabis}}\n\nCannabinoids can be [[Extraction (chemistry)|extracted]] from cannabis plant matter using high-[[alcoholic proof|proof]] [[herbalism#Routes of administration|spirits]] (often [[rectified spirit|grain alcohol]]) to create a [[tincture]], often referred to as \"green dragon\".<ref name=\"Iversen2000s\">{{cite book |first = Leslie L. | last = Iversen  | name-list-format = vanc |title=The Science of Marijuana |url=https://archive.org/details/scienceofmarijua00iver |url-access = registration |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-515110-7 |page=[https://archive.org/details/scienceofmarijua00iver/page/17 17]}}</ref> [[Nabiximols]] is a branded product name from a tincture manufacturing pharmaceutical company.<ref name=\"CohenRudick2011\">{{cite book | first1 = Jeffrey A. | last1 = Cohen | first2 = Richard A. | last2 = Rudick | name-list-format = vanc |title=Multiple Sclerosis Therapeutics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LxQkUu2tfXcC&pg=PA670 |year=2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1-139-50237-5 |page=670}}</ref>\n\n===Hash oil===\n{{Main|Hash oil}}\n\nHash oil is a [[resin]]ous matrix of [[cannabinoid]]s obtained from the ''Cannabis'' plant by [[solvent extraction]],<ref name=\"King2009c\">{{cite book|first = Leslie A. | last = King  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Forensic Chemistry of Substance Misuse: A Guide to Drug Control|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x9Z1QZ5NIEIC&pg=PA78|year=2009|publisher=Royal Society of Chemistry|isbn=978-0-85404-178-7|page=78}}</ref> formed into a hardened or viscous mass.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/101445332 |title=Dabs\u2014marijuana's explosive secret |publisher=Cnbc.com |date=2014-02-24 |access-date=2014-02-28}}</ref> Hash oil can be the most potent of the main cannabis products because of its high level of psychoactive compound per its volume, which can vary depending on the plant's mix of essential oils and psychoactive compounds.<ref name=\"WD2009_98\">{{cite book |year=2009 |title=World Drug Report|publisher=United Nations Publications |page=[https://archive.org/details/worlddrugreport20000unse/page/98 98] |url=https://archive.org/details/worlddrugreport20000unse|url-access=registration |isbn=9789211482409}}</ref> [[Butane]] and [[Supercritical fluid|supercritical]] [[carbon dioxide]] hash oil have become popular in recent years.<ref>Alison Hallett for Wired. Feb. 20, 2013 [https://www.wired.com/2013/02/hash-oil-explosion/How Hash Oil is Blowing Up Across the U.S. \u2013Literally]</ref>\n\n===Infusions===\nThere are many varieties of cannabis infusions owing to the variety of non-volatile solvents used.<ref name=\"Kintz2014\">{{cite book|first = Pascal | last = Kintz  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Toxicological Aspects of Drug-Facilitated Crimes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YgnUAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA141|year=2014|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-0-12-416969-2|page=141}}</ref> The plant material is mixed with the solvent and then pressed and filtered to express the oils of the plant into the solvent. Examples of solvents used in this process are cocoa butter, dairy butter, cooking oil, [[glycerine]], and skin moisturizers. Depending on the solvent, these may be used in [[cannabis foods]] or applied topically.<ref name=\"McDonoughMagazine2012\">{{cite book | first1 = Elise | last1 = McDonough | name-list-format = vanc  |title=The Official High Times Cannabis Cookbook: More Than 50 Irresistible Recipes That Will Get You High |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W-vas6K75YYC&pg=PA17 |year=2012 |publisher=Chronicle Books |isbn=978-1-4521-0133-0 |page=17}}</ref>\n\n===Medical use===\n{{Further|Medical cannabis}}\n\nMedical marijuana refers to the use of the ''Cannabis'' plant as a physician-recommended [[herbal therapy]] as well as synthetic<ref name=\"Backes2014\">{{cite book|first = Michael | last = Backes  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Cannabis Pharmacy: The Practical Guide to Medical Marijuana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7z2FwBywoJ0C&pg=PT46|year=2014|publisher=Hachette Books|isbn=978-1-60376-334-9|page=46}}</ref> THC and cannabinoids. So far, the medical use of cannabis is legal only in a limited number of territories, including Canada,<ref name=canada2018/> [[Belgium]], Australia, the [[Netherlands]], Spain, and [[Medical cannabis in the United States|many U.S. states]]. This usage generally requires a prescription, and distribution is usually done within a framework defined by local laws. There is evidence supporting the use of cannabis or its derivatives in the treatment of chemotherapy-induced nausea and vomiting, neuropathic pain, and multiple sclerosis. Lower levels of evidence support its use for AIDS wasting syndrome, epilepsy, rheumatoid arthritis, and glaucoma.<ref name = NEJM2014 />\n\n[[File:Cannabissativadior.jpg|thumb|upright|''Cannabis sativa'' from [[Vienna Dioscurides]], c.&nbsp;512 CE]]\n\n==History==\n{{See also|History of cannabis|Timeline of cannabis law}}\n\n===Ancient history===\n\nCannabis is [[indigenous (ecology)|indigenous]] to Central Asia<ref>{{cite book|last=Schultes|first=Richard Evans|authorlink=Richard Evans Schultes|title=Hallucinogenic Plants|others=Illustrated by Elmer W. Smith|publisher=[[Western Publishing|Golden Press]]|location=New York|year=1976|isbn=978-0-307-24362-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/hallucinogenicpl00schu_0/page/31 31]|url=https://archive.org/details/hallucinogenicpl00schu_0/page/31}}</ref> and the Indian subcontinent,<ref>\"Marijuana and the Cannabinoids\", ElSohly (p. 8).</ref> and its uses for fabric and rope dates back to the [[Neolithic age]] in China and Japan.<ref name=\"StaffordBigwood1992\">{{cite book|first1=Peter G.|last1=Stafford|first2=Jeremy|last2=Bigwood|name-list-format=vanc|title=Psychedelics Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o4_pLqCOyDsC&pg=PA157|year=1992|publisher=Ronin Publishing|isbn=978-0-914171-51-5|page=157}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|vauthors=Barber EJ|year=1992|title=Prehistoric Textiles: The Development of Cloth in the Neolithic and Bronze Ages with Special Reference to the Aegean|publisher=Princeton University Press|pages=17}}</ref> It is unclear when cannabis first became known for its psychoactive properties. The oldest archeological evidence for the burning of cannabis was found in Romanian [[Kurgan|kurgans]] dated 3,500 BC, and scholars suggest that the drug was first used in ritual ceremonies by [[Proto-Indo-Europeans|Proto-Indo-European]] tribes living in the [[Pontic\u2013Caspian steppe|Pontic-Caspian steppe]] during the [[Chalcolithic|Chalcolithic period]], a custom they eventually spread throughout western Eurasia during the [[Indo-European migrations|Indo-Europan migrations]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=mTxQmQEACAAJ|title=The Horse, the Wheel, and Language: How Bronze-Age Riders from the Eurasian Steppes Shaped the Modern World|last=Anthony|first=David W.|date=2007|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-05887-0|location=|pages=362|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nBvFBAAAQBAJ|title=Seeking the Sacred with Psychoactive Substances: Chemical Paths to Spirituality and to God|last=Ellens|first=J. Harold|date=2014|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1440830884|location=|pages=24, 31|language=en}}</ref> Some research suggests that the ancient [[Indo-Iranians|Indo-Iranian]] drug [[soma (drink)|soma]], mentioned in the [[Veda]]s, sometimes contained cannabis. This is based on the discovery of a basin containing cannabis in a shrine of the [[second millennium BC]] in [[Turkmenistan]].<ref name=\"Rudgley-Encyclopedia\">{{cite book|last=Rudgley|first=Richard|name-list-format=vanc|year=1998|chapter-url=http://www.huxley.net/soma/index.html|chapter=Soma|title=The Encyclopedia of Psychoactive Substances|publisher=Little, Brown and Company|isbn=978-0-349-11127-8}}</ref> \n\nCannabis was known to the [[History of the Assyrian people|ancient Assyrians]], who discovered its psychoactive properties through the Iranians.<ref>{{cite book|last=Franck|first=Mel|name-list-format=vanc|title=Marijuana Grower's Guide|publisher=Red Eye Press|year=1997|isbn=978-0-929349-03-9|page=3}}</ref> Using it in some religious ceremonies, they called it ''qunubu'' (meaning \"way to produce smoke\"), a probable origin of the modern word \"cannabis\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Rubin|first=Vera D.|name-list-format=vanc|title=Cannabis and Culture|publisher=Campus Verlag|year=1976|isbn=978-3-593-37442-0|page=305}}</ref> The Iranians also introduced cannabis to the [[Scythia]]ns, [[Thracians]] and [[Dacia]]ns, whose [[shamanism|shamans]] (the ''[[kapnobatai]]''\u2014\"those who walk on smoke/clouds\") burned cannabis infructescences to induce [[trance]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Cunliffe|first=Barry W.|name-list-format=vanc|title=The Oxford Illustrated History of Prehistoric Europe|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|isbn=978-0-19-285441-4|page=405}}</ref> The plant was used in China before 2800 BC, and found therapeutic use in India by 1000 BC, where it was used [[cannabis edible|in food and drink]], including ''[[bhang]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Schultes|first=Richard Evans|title=Hallucinogenic Plants|others=Illustrated by Elmer W. Smith|publisher=Golden Press|location=New York|year=1976|isbn=978-0-307-24362-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/hallucinogenicpl00schu_0/page/34 34]|url=https://archive.org/details/hallucinogenicpl00schu_0/page/34}}</ref><ref name=vice>{{cite web|url=https://munchies.vice.com/en_us/article/kbx94a/httpmunchies-vice-comarticlesthe-bhang-lassi-is-how-hindus-drink-themselves-high-for-shiva |title=The Bhang Lassi Is How Hindus Drink Themselves High for Shiva |author=Staelens, Stefanie|website=Vice.com|accessdate=10 August 2017|date=2015-03-10 }}</ref>\n[[File:Bhang eaters before two huts (6124556163).jpg|thumb|left|300px|[[Hindus]] eating [[bhang]] (c. 1790)]]\n\nCannabis has an ancient history of ritual use and is found in [[pharmacological cult]]s around the world. The earliest evidence of cannabis smoking has been found in the 2,500-year-old tombs of Jirzankal Cemetery in the [[Pamir Mountains]] in Western China, where cannabis residue were found in burners with charred pebbles possibly used during funeral rituals.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ren M, Tang Z, Wu X, Spengler R, Jiang H, Yang Y, Boivin N | title = The origins of cannabis smoking: Chemical residue evidence from the first millennium BCE in the Pamirs | journal = Science Advances | volume = 5 | issue = 6 | pages = eaaw1391 | date = June 2019 | pmid = 31206023 | pmc = 6561734 | doi = 10.1126/sciadv.aaw1391 | bibcode = 2019SciA....5.1391R }}</ref><ref name=\"NatGeo2019Jun\" /> Hemp seeds discovered by archaeologists at [[Pazyryk burials|Pazyryk]] suggest early ceremonial practices like eating by the Scythians occurred during the 5th to 2nd century BC, confirming previous historical reports by [[Herodotus]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Walton|first=Robert P.|name-list-format=vanc|title=Marijuana, America's New Drug Problem|publisher=JB Lippincott|year=1938|page=6}}</ref> It was used by Muslims in various [[Sufi]] orders as early as the [[Mamluk]] period, for example by the [[Qalandariyya|Qalandars]].<ref>{{cite book|language=FR|title=Le haschich et l'extase|first=Ibn|last=Taymiyya|name-list-format=vanc|author-link=Ibn Taymiyya|isbn=978-2-84161-174-4|year=2001|publisher=Albouraq|location=Beyrouth}}</ref> Smoking pipes uncovered in Ethiopia and carbon-dated to around c. AD 1320 were found to have traces of cannabis.<ref name=\"Rubin1975\">{{cite book|first=Vera|last=Rubin|name-list-format=vanc|title=Cannabis and Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gCRNRGOhNA4C&pg=PA77|date=1 January 1975|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-081206-0|pages=77\u2013|quote=Cannabis Smoking in 13th-14th Century Ethiopia: Chemical Evidence}}</ref>\n\n===Modern history===\n\nFollowing an 1836\u20131840 travel in North Africa and the Middle East, French physician [[Jacques-Joseph Moreau]] wrote on the psychological effects of cannabis use; he was a member of Paris' [[Club des Hashischins]].{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} In 1842, Irish physician [[William Brooke O'Shaughnessy]], who had studied the drug while working as a medical officer in Bengal with the East India company, brought a quantity of cannabis with him on his return to Britain, provoking renewed interest in the West.<ref name=\"Iversen2007\">{{cite book|first=Leslie L.|last=Iversen|name-list-format=vanc|title=The Science of Marijuana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sshsCAAAQBAJ&pg=PT110|date=7 December 2007|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-988693-7|pages=110\u2013}}</ref> Examples of classic literature of the period featuring cannabis include ''[[Les paradis artificiels]]'' (1860) by [[Charles Baudelaire]] and ''[[The Hasheesh Eater]]'' (1857) by [[Fitz Hugh Ludlow]].\n\n[[File:Killerdrug.jpg|thumb|Cannabis propaganda from 1935]]\nCannabis was criminalized in various countries beginning in the 19th century. The British colonies of Mauritius banned cannabis in 1840 over concerns on its effect on Indian indentured workers;<ref>{{cite book|title=A Collection of the Laws of Mauritius and Its Dependencies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ktHAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA541|year=1867|publisher=By the authority of the Government|pages=541\u2013}}</ref> the same occurred in British Singapore in 1870.<ref name=\"Bunyapraphats\u014dn_1999\">{{cite book|first=Nanthawan|last=Bunyapraphats\u014dn|name-list-format=vanc|title=Medicinal and poisonous plants|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ifDwAAAAMAAJ|year=1999|publisher=Backhuys Publishers|isbn=978-90-5782-042-7|page=169}}</ref> In the United States, the first restrictions on sale of cannabis came in 1906 (in [[District of Columbia]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.druglibrary.org/schaffer/hemp/taxact/woodward.htm |title=Statement of Dr. William C. Woodward |publisher= Drug library |access-date= 2010-09-20}}</ref> Canada criminalized cannabis in ''The Opium and Narcotic Drug Act, 1923'',<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title  =The Opium and Narcotic Drug Act, 1923|abbr =S.C.|year =1923|chapter =22|link= https://archive.org/stream/actsofparl1923v01cana#page/134/mode/2up}}</ref> before any reports of the use of the drug in Canada, but eventually legalized its consumption for recreational and medicinal purposes in 2018.<ref name=canada2018/>\n\n[[File:Drug bottle containing cannabis.jpg|thumb|upright|Cannabis indica fluid extract, American Druggists Syndicate ({{nowrap|pre-1937}})]]\nIn 1925, a compromise was made at an international conference in [[The Hague]] about the [[International Opium Convention]] that banned exportation of \"Indian hemp\" to countries that had prohibited its use, and requiring importing countries to issue certificates approving the importation and stating that the shipment was required \"exclusively for medical or scientific purposes\". It also required parties to \"exercise an effective control of such a nature as to prevent the illicit international traffic in Indian hemp and especially in the resin\".<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.druglibrary.org/schaffer/history/e1920/willoughby.htm | vauthors = Willoughby WW |title=Opium as an international problem | location=Baltimore |publisher=The Johns Hopkins Press |year=1925 |access-date=2010-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{Google books|GJm-XDLJe1QC|Opium as an international problem: the Geneva conferences&nbsp;\u2013 Westel Woodbury Willoughby}}</ref> In the United States in 1937, the [[Marihuana Tax Act of 1937|Marihuana Tax Act]] was passed,<ref>{{USStatute|75|238|50|551|1937|8|2}}</ref> and prohibited the production of hemp in addition to cannabis.\n\nIn 1972, the Dutch government divided drugs into more- and less-dangerous categories, with cannabis being in the lesser category. Accordingly, possession of {{convert|30|g||||}} or less was made a misdemeanor.<ref name=\"Booth2005\">{{cite book| first = Martin | last = Booth  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Cannabis: A History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O7AoY6ljSygC&pg=PA338|date=1 June 2005|publisher=Picador|isbn=978-0-312-42494-7|pages=338\u2013}}</ref> Cannabis has been available for recreational use in [[Coffeeshop (Netherlands)|coffee shops]] since 1976.<ref name=\"Tonry2015\">{{cite book|author=Michael Tonry|title=Crime and Justice | volume = 44 | series = A Review of Research|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TMauCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT261|date=22 September 2015|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-34102-6|pages=261\u2013}}</ref> Cannabis products are only sold openly in certain local \"coffeeshops\" and possession of up to {{convert|5|g||||}} for personal use is decriminalized, however: the police may still confiscate it, which often happens in car checks near the border. Other types of sales and transportation are not permitted, although the general approach toward cannabis was lenient even before official [[decriminalization]].<ref>{{citation |url = http://eldd.emcdda.europa.eu/html.cfm/index5174EN.html# |title = Use drop-down menu on site to view Netherlands entry.) |publisher = Eldd.emcdda.europa.eu |date =  |access-date = 2011-02-17 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url = http://www.ukcia.org/research/dutch.php |title = Drugs Policy in the Netherlands |publisher = Ukcia.org |date =  |access-date = 2011-02-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.theatlanticwire.com/global/2011/05/amsterdam-ban-pot-sales-tourists/38248/ |title = Amsterdam Will Ban Tourists from Pot Coffee Shops |work = Atlantic Wire |access-date = 2011-06-23 |last =  |first =  |date = 27 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn Uruguay, President [[Jose Mujica]] signed legislation to [[Cannabis in Uruguay|legalize recreational cannabis]] in December 2013, making Uruguay the first country in the modern era to legalize cannabis. In August 2014, Uruguay legalized growing up to six plants at home, as well as the formation of growing clubs, and a state-controlled [[marijuana dispensary]] regime.\n\nAs of 17 October 2018 when recreational use of cannabis was legalized in Canada, [[dietary supplement]]s for human use and [[Holistic veterinary medicine|veterinary health products]] containing not more than 10 parts per million of THC [[extract]] were approved for marketing; [[Nabiximols]] (as Sativex) is used as a [[prescription drug]] in Canada.<ref name=canada2018/>\n\nThe United Nations' ''World Drug Report'' stated that cannabis \"was the world's most widely produced, trafficked, and consumed drug in the world in 2010\", and estimated between 128 million and 238 million users globally in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marijuana Now the Most Popular Drug in the World|url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2012/06/29/marijuana-now-the-most-popular-drug-in-the-world/|work=Time NewsFeed|publisher=Time Inc|access-date=16 March 2013| first = Eliana | last = Dockterman  | name-list-format = vanc |date=29 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=World Drug Report 2017 |chapter=Factsheet |chapter-url=https://www.unodc.org/wdr2017/index.html |publisher=United Nation Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC) |access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Society and culture==\n{{See also|Cannabis culture}}\n\n===Legal status===\n{{Main|Legality of cannabis}}\n{{See also|Prohibition of drugs|Drug liberalization}}\n[[File:Map-of-world-cannabis-laws.svg|thumb|right|380px|alt=Map of world cannabis laws|\n'''Legal status of cannabis possession for non-medical use'''\n----\n{{legend|#0d00f2|Legal}}\n{{legend|#ffb700|Illegal but decriminalized}}\n{{legend|#ff9e9e|Illegal but often unenforced}}\n{{legend|#ff3c3c|Illegal}}\n----\n<small>See also [[:File:Map-of-world-medical-cannabis-laws.svg|countries that have legalized medical use of cannabis]]</small>]]\n<!-- PLEASE, keep this section relatively compact, contributions are more than welcome at [[Legality of cannabis]]. THANKS. -->\nSince the beginning of the 20th century, most countries have enacted [[prohibition (drugs)|laws]] against the cultivation, possession or transfer of cannabis.<ref name=\"Levinson2002\">{{cite book|first = David | last = Levinson  | name-list-format = vanc  |title=Encyclopedia of Crime and Punishment|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aiQ09D7nWxYC&pg=PA572|year=2002|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-0-7619-2258-2|page=572}}</ref> These laws have impacted adversely on cannabis cultivation for non-recreational purposes, but there are many regions where handling of cannabis is legal or licensed. Many jurisdictions have lessened the penalties for possession of small quantities of cannabis so that it is punished by confiscation and sometimes a fine, rather than imprisonment, focusing more on those who traffic the drug on the [[black market]].\n\nIn some areas where cannabis use had been historically tolerated, new restrictions were instituted, such as the closing of cannabis coffee shops near the borders of the Netherlands,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.expatica.com/nl/leisure/arts_culture/many-dutch-coffee-shops-close-as-liberal-policies-change-46376.html |title=Many Dutch coffee shops close as liberal policies change, Exaptica |date=2007-11-27 |publisher=Expatica.com |access-date=2010-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429192229/http://www.expatica.com/nl/leisure/arts_culture/many-dutch-coffee-shops-close-as-liberal-policies-change-46376.html |archive-date=2011-04-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and closing of coffee shops near secondary schools in the Netherlands.<ref>[http://www.rnw.nl/internationaljustice/news/international/6061587/43-Amsterdam-coffee-shops-to-close-doors \"43 Amsterdam coffee shops to close door\"], Radio Netherlands, Friday 21 November 2008 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202130012/http://www.rnw.nl/internationaljustice/news/international/6061587/43-Amsterdam-coffee-shops-to-close-doors |date=December 2, 2008 }}</ref> In [[Copenhagen]], Denmark in 2014, mayor [[Frank Jensen]] discussed possibilities for the city to legalize cannabis production and commerce.<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Sullivan|first1=Feargus | name-list-format = vanc |title=Why the Mayor of Copenhagen Wants to Get Into the Marijuana Business|url=https://www.citylab.com/equity/2014/03/why-mayor-copenhagen-wants-get-marijuana-business/8527/|access-date=23 January 2018|date=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nSome jurisdictions use free voluntary treatment programs and/or mandatory treatment programs for frequent known users. Simple possession can carry long prison terms in some countries, particularly in East Asia, where the sale of cannabis may lead to a sentence of life in prison or even execution. Political parties, non-profit organizations, and causes based on the legalization of medical cannabis and/or legalizing the plant entirely (with some restrictions) have emerged in such countries as China and Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johnston|first1=Ian| name-list-format = vanc |title=As cannabis is widely legalised, China cashes in on an unprecedented boom|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/as-cannabis-is-widely-legalised-china-cashes-in-on-an-unprecedented-boom-9039191.html|publisher=Independent|access-date=23 January 2018|date=5 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Liljas|first1=Per| name-list-format = vanc |title=Could Thailand, which gave world the bong, legalise cannabis for medicinal use? After failed war on drugs, attitudes have softened|url=http://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/long-reads/article/2097464/could-thailand-which-gave-world-bong-legalise|publisher=Post Magazine|access-date=23 January 2018|date=3 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, the U.S. state of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] became the first state to officially legalize cannabis in a state law ([[Washington Initiative 502]]) (but still illegal by [[Cannabis in the United States|federal law]]),<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/12/07/uk-usa-marijuana-washington-idUSLNE8B502120121207|title=Marijuana goes legal in Washington state amid mixed messages |newspaper=Reuters |access-date=December 14, 2012|date=2012-12-07 }}</ref> with the state of [[Colorado]] following close behind ([[Colorado Amendment 64]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/11/07/politics/marijuana-legalization/index.html |title=2 states legalize pot, but don't 'break out the Cheetos' yet | first = Alan | last = Duke  | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=CNN.com |date=2012-11-08 |access-date=2013-01-02}}</ref> On 1 January 2013, the first marijuana \"club\" for private marijuana smoking (no buying or selling, however) was allowed for the first time in Colorado.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/marijuana-clubs-ring-year-colorado-legalized-pot-smoking/story?id=18108083 |title=Marijuana clubs ring in new year in Colorado as legalized pot smoking begins |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2013-01-01 |access-date=2013-01-02}}</ref> The California Supreme Court decided in May 2013 that local governments can ban medical marijuana dispensaries despite a state law in California that permits the use of cannabis for medical purposes. At least 180 cities across California have enacted bans in recent years.<ref>{{cite news|first = Horward | last = Mintz  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Medical pot: California Supreme Court allows cities to ban weed dispensaries |work=Marin Independent Journal |date=2013-05-06 |url=http://www.marinij.com/digitalfirstmedia/ci_23184556/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102202631/http://www.marinij.com/digitalfirstmedia/ci_23184556/ |archive-date=November 2, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, [[Uruguay]] became the first country to legalize growing, sale and use of cannabis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2013/dec/11/uruguay-marijuana-laws-around-world|title=Marijuana laws around the world: what you need to know| first = Vicky | last = Baker | name-list-format = vanc |newspaper=the Guardian|date=2013-12-11}}</ref>  After a long delay in implementing the retail component of the law, in 2017 sixteen pharmacies were authorized to sell cannabis commercially.<ref name=UrGuardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jul/19/uruguay-marijuana-sale-pharmacies|title=Uruguay pharmacies start selling cannabis straight to consumers|last=Reuters|date=19 July 2017|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> On 19 June 2018, the Canadian Senate passed a bill and the Prime Minister announced the effective legalization date as 17 October 2018.<ref name=canada2018/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4285946/marijuana-legal-date-october-17-canada-trudeau-confirms/|title=Marijuana to be legal in Canada starting October 17, Trudeau confirms|date=2018-06-20}}</ref> Canada is the second country to legalize the drug.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/20/health/canada-legalizes-marijuana/index.html|title=Canada becomes second nation in the world to legalize marijuana|first=Bani |last=Sapra}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, [[Uttarakhand]] became the first state of [[India]] to legalize the cultivation of hemp for industrial purposes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uttarakhand To Become First Indian State To Legalise Cannabis Cultivation|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/uttarakhand-to-become-first-indian-state-to-legalise-cannabis-cultivation-247769.html|website=Indiatimes|access-date=12 March 2017|language=en|date=2015-11-27}}</ref> Usage within the Hindu and Buddhist cultures of the [[Indian subcontinent]] is common, with many street vendors in India openly selling products infused with cannabis, and traditional medical practitioners in Sri Lanka selling products infused with cannabis for recreational purposes and well as for religious celebrations.<ref name=\":1\" /> It was criminalized in the Indian subcontinent by the Dutch and then the British. India and Sri Lanka have allowed cannabis to be taken in the context of traditional culture for recreational/celebratory purposes and also for medicinal purposes.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/pdf/india/publications/south_Asia_Regional_Profile_Sept_2005/13_srilanka.pdf|title=South Asia Regional Profile Report|last=|first=|date=|website=UNODC|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 October 2015, Australian health minister Sussan Ley presented a new law that will allow the [[Agriculture|cultivation]] of cannabis for scientific research and medical trials on patients.<ref>Alchimia Blog, ''[https://www.alchimiaweb.com/blogen/medical-marijuana-news-december-2015/ Medical marijuana news, December 2015]''</ref>\n\nOn 17 October 2018, Canada legalized cannabis for recreational adult use<ref name=\"Butler\">{{cite news |last=Butler|first=Patrick|date=17 October 2018|title=Cannabis is legal in Canada \u2014 here's what you need to know|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/marijuana-faq-legalization-need-to-know-1.4862207/|work=CBC|access-date=1 November 2018 }}</ref> making it the second country in the world to do so after Uruguay and the first G7 nation.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sapra|first=Bani|date=20 June 2018|title=Canada becomes second nation in the world to legalize marijuana|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/20/health/canada-legalizes-marijuana/index.html|work=CNN|access-date=1 November 2018 }}</ref> The [[List of licensed producers of medical marijuana in Canada|Canadian Licensed Producer]] system aims to become the Gold Standard in the world for safe and secure cannabis production,<ref>{{cite web|title=This Application Seems Rigorous. Are All These Hoops Necessary?|url=https://licensedproducerscanada.ca/faq/application-seems-rigorous-hoops-necessary|work=LicensedProducersCanada.com|access-date=1 November 2018}}</ref> including provisions for a robust craft cannabis industry where many expect opportunities for experimenting with different strains.<ref>{{cite web|title=Will Craft Cannabis Growers in Canada Succeed Like Craft Brewers?|url=https://licensedproducerscanada.ca/faq/will-craft-cannabis-growers-in-canada-succeed-like-craft-brewers|work=LicensedProducersCanada.com|access-date=1 November 2018}}</ref> Laws around use vary from province to province including age limits, retail structure, and growing at home.<ref name=\"Butler\"/>\n\nAs the drug has increasingly been seen as a health issue instead of criminal behavior, marijuana has also been legalized or [[Decriminalization|decriminalized]] in: [[Czech Republic]],<ref name=\"Cz expl rep\">{{Citation | last = Parliament of the Czech Republic | year = 1998 | title = Explanatory Report to Act No. 112/1998 Coll., which amends the Act No. 140/1961 Coll., the Criminal Code, and the Act No. 200/1990 Coll., on misdemeanors | location = Prague | page = | url = | access-date = | language = Czech}} \"''Podle \u010dl. 36 Jednotn\u00e9 \u00famluvy o omamn\u00fdch l\u00e1tk\u00e1ch ze dne 31. b\u0159ezna 1961 (\u010d. 47/1965 Sb.) se signat\u00e1\u0159i zavazuj\u00ed k trestn\u00edmu postihu tam uveden\u00fdch forem nakl\u00e1d\u00e1n\u00ed s drogami v\u010detn\u011b jejich dr\u017eby. N\u00e1vrh upou\u0161t\u00ed od dosavadn\u00ed beztrestnosti dr\u017eby omamn\u00fdch a psychotropn\u00edch l\u00e1tek a jed\u016f pro svoji pot\u0159ebu. Dosavadn\u00ed beztrestnost toti\u017e eliminuje v \u0159ad\u011b p\u0159\u00edpad\u016f mo\u017enost postihu dealer\u016f a distributor\u016f drog.''\"</ref> [[Colombia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2012/03/2012327125714281880.html|title=The summit of muted intentions| first = Jorge G | last = Castaneda  | name-list-format = vanc |work=aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noticiasrcn.com/nacional-pais/congreso-aprobo-ultimo-debate-uso-medicinal-marihuana|title=Congreso aprob\u00f3, en \u00faltimo debate, uso medicinal de la marihuana|date=25 May 2016}}</ref> [[Ecuador]],<ref>[http://www.elcomercio.com/seguridad/Dosis-maximas-droga-consumo-vigentes_0_941905849.html \"Dosis m\u00e1ximas de droga para consumo ya est\u00e1n vigentes\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624025336/http://www.elcomercio.com/seguridad/Dosis-maximas-droga-consumo-vigentes_0_941905849.html |date=2013-06-24 }} at [[El Comercio (Ecuador)|El Comercio]].com.</ref><ref>[http://www.elnuevoherald.com/2013/06/21/1505650/ecuador-aprueban-tenencia-de-drogas.html \"Ecuador: Aprueban tenencia de drogas para consumo\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625023421/http://www.elnuevoherald.com/2013/06/21/1505650/ecuador-aprueban-tenencia-de-drogas.html |date=2013-06-25 }} at ''[[El Nuevo Herald]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegrafo.com.ec/english-bulletin/item/ecuador-could-regulate-drug-sales.html|title=Ecuador could regulate the drug industry|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130624225110/http://www.telegrafo.com.ec/english-bulletin/item/ecuador-could-regulate-drug-sales.html|archive-date=2013-06-24|df=}}</ref> [[Portugal]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emcdda.europa.eu/system/files/publications/642/PolicyProfile_Portugal_WEB_Final_289201.pdf |title=Drug policy profiles \u2014 Portugal |date=2011-06-01 |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref> [[Cannabis in South Africa|South Africa]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/09/18/dagga-users-celebrate-following-concourt-ruling-on-private-use|title=Dagga users celebrate following ConCourt ruling on private use|last=Lindeque|first=Mia|access-date=2018-11-03|language=en}}</ref> and [[Canada]].<ref name=canada2018/> Medical marijuana was legalized in [[Mexico]] in mid-2017; legislators plan to legalize its recreational use by late 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Williams |first1=Sean |title=Mexico Aims to Legalize Recreational Marijuana Before October \u2013 |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/04/28/mexico-aims-to-legalize-recreational-marijuana-bef.aspx |website=The Motley Fool |accessdate=April 29, 2019 |language=en |date=April 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>[http://www.elpensador.com.mx/2009/10/17/Ley-de-Narcomenudeo/ Ley de Narcomenudeo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130224127/http://www.elpensador.com.mx/2009/10/17/Ley-de-Narcomenudeo/ |date=2010-11-30 }}, ''El Pensador'' {{in lang|es}}, 17 October 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.druglawreform.info/index.php?option=com_flexicontent&view=items&cid=97%3Alegislative-reform-of-drug-policies&id=220%3Amexico-the-law-against-small-scale-drug-dealing&Itemid=34&lang=en Mexico: The Law Against Small-Scale Drug Dealing. A Doubtful Venture], Jorge Hern\u00e1ndez Tinajero & Carlos Zamudio Angles, Series on Legislative Reform of Drug Policies Nr. 3, November 2009</ref>\n\n===Usage===\n{{Global estimates of illicit drug users}}\nIn 2013, between 128 and 232 million people used cannabis (2.7% to 4.9% of the global population between the ages of 15 and 65).<ref name=WDR2015/> Cannabis is by far the most widely used illicit substance.<ref name=\"CaulkinsHawken2012\">{{cite book | first1 = Jonathan P. | last1 = Caulkins | first2 = Angela | last2 = Hawken | first3 = Beau | last3 = Kilmer | first4 = Mark A.R. | last4 = Kleiman | name-list-format = vanc | title = Marijuana Legalization: What Everyone Needs to Know | publisher = Oxford University Press | isbn = 978-0199913732 | page = [https://archive.org/details/marijuanalegaliz0000unse/page/16 16] | date = 2012-09-27 | url = https://archive.org/details/marijuanalegaliz0000unse/page/16 }}</ref>\n\n====United States====\nBetween 1973 and 1978, eleven states decriminalized marijuana.<ref name=\"tandfonline.com\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1080/17541328.2015.1058480 | volume=8 | title=The business of getting high: head shops, countercultural capitalism, and the marijuana legalization movement | year=2015 | journal=The Sixties | pages=27\u201349 | first = Clark Davis | last = Joshua  | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> In 2001, [[Nevada]] reduced marijuana possession to a misdemeanor and since 2012, several other states have decriminalized and even legalized marijuana.<ref name=\"tandfonline.com\"/>\n\nIn 2015, almost half of the people in the United States had tried marijuana, 12% had used it in the past year, and 7.3% had used it in the past month.<ref name=\"6 facts about marijuana\"/> In 2014, daily marijuana use amongst US college students had reached its highest level since records began in 1980, rising from 3.5% in 2007 to 5.9% in 2014 and had surpassed daily [[cigarette]] use.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://record.umich.edu/articles/daily-marijuana-use-among-college-students-highest-1980|title=Daily marijuana use among college students highest since 1980|work=The University Record}}</ref>\n\nIn the US, men are over twice as likely to use marijuana as women, and 18{{ndash}}29-year-olds are six times more likely to use as over-65-year-olds.<ref name=\"gallup.com\">{{cite news |last1=McCarthy |first1=Justin |title=More Than Four in 10 Americans Say They Have Tried Marijuana |url=https://news.gallup.com/poll/184298/four-americans-say-tried-marijuana.aspx |work=Gallup |date=22 July 2015}}</ref> In 2015, a record 44% of the US population has tried marijuana in their lifetime, an increase from 38% in 2013 and 33% in 1985.<ref name=\"gallup.com\"/>\n\nMarijuana use in the United States is three times above the global average, but in line with other Western democracies. Forty-four percent of American 12th graders have tried the drug at least once, and the typical age of first-use is 16, similar to the typical age of first-use for alcohol but lower than the first-use age for other [[Illegal drug trade|illicit drugs]].<ref name=\"CaulkinsHawken2012\"/>\n\n===Economics===\n\n====Production====\n{{Main|Cannabis cultivation}}\n[[File:Woman selling Cannabis and Bhang in Guwahati, Assam, India.jpg|thumb|Woman selling cannabis and [[bhang]] in [[Guwahati]], Assam, [[India]]]]\n<!-- PLEASE, do not add more detail to this section, contributions are more than welcome at [[Cannabis (drug) cultivation]]. THANKS. -->\n\n''Sinsemilla'' (Spanish for \"without seed\") is the dried, seedless (i.e. [[Parthenocarpy|parthenocarpic]]) [[infructescence]]s of female [[Cannabis sativa|cannabis plants]]. Because THC production drops off once pollination occurs, the male plants (which produce little THC themselves) are eliminated before they shed pollen to prevent pollination, thus inducing the development of [[Parthenocarpy|parthenocarpic]] fruits gathered in dense [[infructescence]]s. Advanced cultivation techniques such as [[Cannabis (drug) cultivation#Hydroponic cultivation|hydroponics]], [[Cannabis (drug) cultivation#Feminized seeds|cloning]], [[Cannabis (drug) cultivation#Light|high-intensity artificial lighting]], and [[Cannabis (drug) cultivation#SOG|the sea of green method]] are frequently employed as a response (in part) to prohibition enforcement efforts that make outdoor cultivation more risky.\n\n{{anchor|Skunk}}\n\"Skunk\" refers to several named strains of potent cannabis, grown through selective breeding and sometimes [[hydroponics]]. It is a cross-breed of ''Cannabis sativa'' and ''C. indica'' (although other strains of this mix exist in abundance). Skunk cannabis potency ranges usually from 6% to 15% and rarely as high as 20%. The average THC level in coffee shops in the Netherlands is about 18\u201319%.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/data-and-analysis/WDR-2006.html |title=World Drug Report 2006 |publisher=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime}} Ch. 2.3.</ref>\n\nThe average levels of THC in cannabis sold in the [[United States Of America|United States]] rose dramatically between the [[1970s (decade)|1970s]] and [[2000s (decade)|2000]].<ref name=Giz /> This is disputed for various reasons, and there is little consensus as to whether this is a fact or an artifact of poor testing methodologies.<ref name=Giz /> According to Daniel Forbes writing for slate.com, the relative strength of modern strains are likely skewed because undue weight is given to much more expensive and potent, but less prevalent, samples.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2074151 |publisher=Slate.com |title=The Myth of Potent Pot | first = Daniel | last = Forbes  | name-list-format = vanc |date=2002-11-19}}</ref> Some suggest that results are skewed by older testing methods that included low-THC-content plant material such as leaves in the samples, which are excluded in contemporary tests. Others believe that modern strains actually are significantly more potent than older ones.<ref name=Giz>{{cite web|last=Turco|first=Bucky|title=Why is Weed Getting More Potent|work=Gizmodo|url=https://gizmodo.com/why-is-weed-getting-more-potent-1818662872|date=25 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Price====\nThe price or street value of cannabis varies widely depending on geographic area and potency.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unodc.org/pdf/WDR_2005/volume_2_chap7_cannabis.pdf |title=Cannabis: Wholesale, street prices and purity levels |publisher=UNODC.org |year=2005 |access-date=2013-01-09}}</ref> Prices and overall markets have also varied considerably over time.\n\n* In 1997, cannabis was estimated to be overall the number four value crop in the US, and number one or two in many states, including California, New York, and Florida.  This estimate is based on a value to growers of ~60% of retail value, or {{convert|3000|$/lb|$/kg}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Report on U.S. Domestic Marijuana Production|url=http://norml.org/index.cfm?Group_ID=4444|url-status=dead|publisher=NORML|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226011927/http://www.norml.org//index.cfm?Group_ID=4444|archive-date=December 26, 2009|access-date=2010-01-02}}</ref>\n* In 2006, cannabis was estimated to have been a $36&nbsp;billion market.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2006-12-20|title=Marijuana Called Top U.S. Cash Crop|url=http://abcnews.go.com/business/story?id=2735017&page=1|publisher=2008 ABCNews Internet Ventures}}</ref> This estimate has been challenged as exaggerated.<ref name=\"CaulkinsHawken2012\" /> The UN World Drug Report (2008) estimated that 2006 street prices in the US and Canada ranged from about US$8.8 to $25 per gram (approximately $250 to $700 per ounce), depending on quality.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.unodc.org/documents/wdr/WDR_2008/WDR_2008_eng_web.pdf|title=World drug report|author=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|publisher=United Nations Publications|year=2008|isbn=978-92-1-148229-4|location=|page=268}}</ref> Typical U.S. retail prices were $10\u201315 per gram (approximately $280\u2013420 per [[ounce]]). \n* In 2017, the U.S. was estimated to constitute 90% of the worldwide $9.5 billion trade in cannabis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investopedia.com/insights/how-federal-legalization-could-transform-us-cannabis-market/|title=How Federal Legalization Could Transform The US Cannabis Market|last=Sharma|first=Rakesh|date=2019-06-25|website=Investopedia|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n\nAfter some U.S. states legalized cannabis, street prices began to drop.  In Colorado, the price of smokable buds (infructescences) dropped 40 percent between 2014 and 2019, from $200 per ounce to $120 per ounce ($7 per gram to $4.19 per gram).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2019/05/23/pot-growers-push-organic-cannabis-cleaner-option-but-buyers-remain-skeptical/1206364001/|title=As marijuana prices drop, growers push 'organic' cannabis \u2013 with a higher price tag|last=Hughes|first=Trevor|date=2019-05-23|website=USA TODAY|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and Drug Addiction]] reports that typical retail prices in Europe for cannabis varied from \u20ac2 to \u20ac20 per gram in 2008, with a majority of European countries reporting prices in the range \u20ac4\u201310.<ref>{{cite book |author=European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and Drug Addiction |title=Annual report: the state of the drugs problem in Europe |year=2008 |publisher=Office for Official Publications of the European Communities |location=Luxembourg |isbn=978-92-9168-324-6 |url=http://www.emcdda.europa.eu/attachements.cfm/att_64227_EN_EMCDDA_AR08_en.pdf |page=38}}</ref>\n\n===Gateway drug===\n{{main|Gateway drug theory}}\nThe gateway hypothesis states that cannabis use increases the probability of trying \"harder\" drugs. The hypothesis has been hotly debated as it is regarded by some as the primary rationale for the United States prohibition on cannabis use.<ref name=\"Rand\">{{Cite web |date=2002-12-02 |url=https://www.rand.org/news/press.02/gateway.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061104124529/https://www.rand.org/news/press.02/gateway.html |archive-date=2006-11-04 |title=RAND study casts doubt on claims that marijuana acts as a \"gateway\" to the use of cocaine and heroin|publisher=RAND Corporation}}</ref><ref name=\"Benavie2009x\">{{cite book| first = Arthur | last = Benavie  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drugs: America's Holy War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DQxXDgLnKD8C&pg=PA90|year=2009|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-7890-3840-1|pages=90\u2013}}</ref> A Pew Research Center poll found that political opposition to marijuana use was significantly associated with concerns about the health effects and whether legalization would increase marijuana use by children.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people-press.org/2014/04/02/section-2-views-of-marijuana-legalization-decriminalization-concerns/ |title=Public Views of Marijuana \u2013 Legalization, Decriminalization, Concerns &#124; Pew Research Center for the People and the Press |website= |access-date=|date=2014-04-02 }}</ref>\n\nSome studies state that while there is no proof for the gateway hypothesis,<ref name=\"MosherAkins2007\">{{cite book | first1 = Clayton J. | last1 = Mosher | first2 = Scott | last2 = Akins | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drugs and Drug Policy: The Control of Consciousness Alteration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aDMvoMxx0-IC&pg=PA18|year=2007|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-0-7619-3007-5|page=18}}</ref> young cannabis users should still be considered as a risk group for intervention programs.<ref name=\"journalwatch\">{{cite journal | last = Saitz | first = Richard | name-list-format = vanc |title=Is marijuana a gateway drug? |journal=Journal Watch |date=2003-02-18 |volume=2003 |issue=218 |page=1 |url=http://general-medicine.jwatch.org/cgi/content/full/2003/218/1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030710150041/http://general-medicine.jwatch.org/cgi/content/full/2003/218/1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-07-10 }}</ref> Other findings indicate that [[hard and soft drugs|hard drug]] users are likely to be [[poly drug use|poly-drug users]], and that interventions must address the use of multiple drugs instead of a single hard drug.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Degenhardt L, Coffey C, Carlin JB, Moran P, Patton GC | title = Who are the new amphetamine users? A 10-year prospective study of young Australians | journal = Addiction | volume = 102 | issue = 8 | pages = 1269\u201379 | date = August 2007 | pmid = 17624977 | doi = 10.1111/j.1360-0443.2007.01906.x }}</ref> Almost two-thirds of the poly drug users in the 2009-2010 Scottish Crime and Justice Survey used cannabis.<ref>{{cite web|title=3 The Experience of Drug Users|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Publications/2011/01/21134813/7|work=2009/10 Scottish Crime and Justice Survey: Drug Use|publisher=The Scottish Government|access-date=5 November 2013|date=21 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe gateway effect may appear due to social factors involved in using any illegal drug. Because of the illegal status of cannabis, its consumers are likely to find themselves in situations allowing them to acquaint with individuals using or selling other illegal drugs.<ref name=\"morral2002\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Morral AR, McCaffrey DF, Paddock SM | title = Reassessing the marijuana gateway effect | journal = Addiction | volume = 97 | issue = 12 | pages = 1493\u2013504 | date = December 2002 | pmid = 12472629 | doi = 10.1046/j.1360-0443.2002.00280.x }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mpp.org/about/faq.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622204803/http://www.mpp.org/about/faq.html|archive-date=2008-06-22|title=Marijuana Policy Project \u2013 FAQ}}</ref> Studies have shown that alcohol and tobacco may additionally be regarded as gateway drugs;<ref name=\"pmid8246462\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Torabi MR, Bailey WJ, Majd-Jabbari M | title = Cigarette smoking as a predictor of alcohol and other drug use by children and adolescents: evidence of the \"gateway drug effect\" | journal = The Journal of School Health | volume = 63 | issue = 7 | pages = 302\u20136 | date = September 1993 | pmid = 8246462 | doi = 10.1111/j.1746-1561.1993.tb06150.x }}</ref> however, a more parsimonious explanation could be that cannabis is simply more readily available (and at an earlier age) than illegal hard drugs. In turn, alcohol and tobacco are typically easier to obtain at an earlier age than is cannabis (though the reverse may be true in some areas), thus leading to the \"gateway sequence\" in those individuals, since they are most likely to experiment with any drug offered.<ref name=\"Rand\" />\n\nA related alternative to the gateway hypothesis is the common liability to addiction (CLA) theory. It states that some individuals are, for various reasons, willing to try multiple recreational substances. The \"gateway\" drugs are merely those that are (usually) available at an earlier age than the harder drugs. Researchers have noted in an extensive review that it is dangerous to present the sequence of events described in gateway \"theory\" in causative terms as this hinders both research and intervention.<ref name=Vanyukov2012>{{cite journal | vauthors = Vanyukov MM, Tarter RE, Kirillova GP, Kirisci L, Reynolds MD, Kreek MJ, Conway KP, Maher BS, Iacono WG, Bierut L, Neale MC, Clark DB, Ridenour TA | title = Common liability to addiction and \"gateway hypothesis\": theoretical, empirical and evolutionary perspective | journal = Drug and Alcohol Dependence | volume = 123 Suppl 1 | issue =  | pages = S3\u201317 | date = June 2012 | pmid = 22261179 | pmc = 3600369 | doi = 10.1016/j.drugalcdep.2011.12.018 | type = Review }}</ref>\n\n==Research==\n{{Further|Medical cannabis#Research}}\n\nCannabis research is challenging since the plant is illegal in most countries.<ref>{{cite journal | author =  | url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=marijuana-research | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101107192934/http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=marijuana-research | archive-date = 7 November 2010 | url-status=dead | title = Marijuana Research: Current restrictions on marijuana research are absurd | journal = Scientific American |date=2004-11-22 |access-date=2013-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ponto LL | title = Challenges of marijuana research | journal = Brain | volume = 129 | issue = Pt 5 | pages = 1081\u20133 | date = May 2006 | pmid = 16627464 | doi = 10.1093/brain/awl092 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | first = Alok | last = Jha | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/may/31/ecstasy-cannabis-study-david-nutt |title=Ecstasy and cannabis should be freely available for study, says David Nutt |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2012-05-31 |access-date=2013-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stanford.edu/group/hopes/cgi-bin/wordpress/2012/05/medical-marijuana-policy-in-the-united-states/#medical-marijuana-and-research |title=Medical Marijuana Policy in the United States |publisher=Stanford.edu |date=2012-05-15 |access-date=2013-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | first = Chelsea | last = Conaboy | name-list-format = vanc | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/health-wellness/2012/10/18/research-into-marijuana-medical-benefits-limited-scientists-cite-challenge-studying-illegal-drug/f6Ydip4xF5VfFWEV9mpwYJ/story.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121021003220/https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/health-wellness/2012/10/18/research-into-marijuana-medical-benefits-limited-scientists-cite-challenge-studying-illegal-drug/f6Ydip4xF5VfFWEV9mpwYJ/story.html | archive-date = 21 October 2012 |title=Research into marijuana's medical benefits limited; scientists cite challenge of studying an illegal drug | work  = Boston Globe |date=2012-10-19 |access-date=2013-01-15}}</ref> Research-grade samples of the drug are difficult to obtain for research purposes, unless granted under authority of national regulatory agencies, such as the US [[Food and Drug Administration]].<ref name=\"fda20\">{{cite web |title=FDA and Cannabis: Research and Drug Approval Process |url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/public-health-focus/fda-and-cannabis-research-and-drug-approval-process |publisher=US Food and Drug Administration |accessdate=21 January 2020 |date=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere are also other difficulties in researching the effects of cannabis. Many people who smoke cannabis also smoke tobacco.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Peters EN, Budney AJ, Carroll KM | title = Clinical correlates of co-occurring cannabis and tobacco use: a systematic review | journal = Addiction | volume = 107 | issue = 8 | pages = 1404\u201317 | date = August 2012 | pmid = 22340422 | pmc = 3377777 | doi = 10.1111/j.1360-0443.2012.03843.x }}</ref> This causes confounding factors, where questions arise as to whether the tobacco, the cannabis, or both that have caused a cancer. Another difficulty researchers have is in recruiting people who smoke cannabis into studies. Because cannabis is an illegal drug in many countries, people may be reluctant to take part in research, and if they do agree to take part, they may not say how much cannabis they actually smoke.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cancerresearchuk.org/cancer-help/about-cancer/cancer-questions/does-smoking-cannabis-cause-cancer | title = Does smoking cannabis cause cancer? |work = Cancer Research UK (CRUK) | date = 2017-08-30 }}</ref>\n\nA 2015 review found that the use of high CBD-to-THC strains of cannabis showed significantly fewer [[positive symptoms]] such as delusions and hallucinations, better [[cognitive function]] and both lower risk for developing psychosis, as well as a later age of onset of the illness, compared to cannabis with low CBD-to-THC ratios.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Iseger TA, Bossong MG | title = A systematic review of the antipsychotic properties of cannabidiol in humans | journal = Schizophrenia Research | volume = 162 | issue = 1\u20133 | pages = 153\u201361 | date = March 2015 | pmid = 25667194 | doi = 10.1016/j.schres.2015.01.033 }}</ref> Reviews in 2019 found that research was insufficient to determine the safety and efficacy of using cannabis to treat schizophrenia, psychosis, or other [[mental disorder]]s.<ref name=\"black\">{{Cite journal|last=Black|first=Nicola|last2=Stockings|first2=Emily|last3=Campbell|first3=Gabrielle|last4=Tran|first4=Lucy T.|last5=Zagic|first5=Dino|last6=Hall|first6=Wayne D.|last7=Farrell|first7=Michael|last8=Degenhardt|first8=Louisa|date=December 2019|title=Cannabinoids for the treatment of mental disorders and symptoms of mental disorders: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=The Lancet. Psychiatry|volume=6|issue=12|pages=995\u20131010|doi=10.1016/S2215-0366(19)30401-8|issn=2215-0374|pmc=6949116|pmid=31672337}}</ref><ref name=\"mayo\">{{Cite journal|last=VanDolah|first=Harrison J.|last2=Bauer|first2=Brent A.|last3=Mauck|first3=Karen F.|date=September 2019|title=Clinicians' Guide to Cannabidiol and Hemp\u00a0Oils|journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings|volume=94|issue=9|pages=1840\u20131851|doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2019.01.003|issn=1942-5546|pmid=31447137}}</ref> There is preliminary evidence that cannabis interferes with the [[anticoagulant]] properties of [[prescription drug]]s used for [[thrombosis|treating blood clots]].<ref name=\"Greger\">{{cite journal | last=Greger | first=Jessica | last2=Bates | first2=Vernice | last3=Mechtler | first3=Laszlo | last4=Gengo | first4=Fran | title=A review of cannabis and interactions with anticoagulant and antiplatelet agents | journal=The Journal of Clinical Pharmacology | volume=60 | issue=4 | pages=432\u2013438 | issn=0091-2700 | doi=10.1002/jcph.1557 | pmid=31724188| year=2020 }}</ref> {{as of|2019}}, the [[Mechanism of action|mechanisms]] for the [[anti-inflammatory]] and possible [[Analgesic|pain relieving]] effects of cannabis were not defined, and there were no governmental regulatory approvals or clinical practices for use of cannabis as a drug.<ref name=mayo/>\n\n== By country ==\n{{main|Legality of cannabis}}\n\n[[Cannabis in Uruguay|Uruguay]] and [[Cannabis in Canada|Canada]] are the only countries that have fully legalized the consumption and sale of recreational cannabis nationwide.<!--Whereas decriminalization would simply remove laws restricting the use of cannabis products, as has been implemented in many countries, legalization allows for the taxation of legally produced cannabis--><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/06/all-eyes-on-canada-as-first-g7-nation-prepares-to-make-marijuana-legal|title=All eyes on Canada as first G7 nation prepares to make marijuana legal|last=Ross|first=Selena|date=6 June 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/20/health/canada-legalizes-marijuana/index.html|title=Canada becomes second nation in the world to legalize marijuana|last=Sapra|first=Bani|date=20 June 2018|work=[[CNN]]|access-date=}}</ref> In the [[Legality of cannabis by U.S. jurisdiction|United States, 11 states]] and the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]] have legalized the recreational use of cannabis \u2013 though the drug remains illegal at the federal level.<ref name=\"ncsl rec\" /> Laws vary from state to state when it comes to the commercial sale. Court rulings in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and [[South Africa]] have led to the legalization of cannabis consumption, but not legal sales. A policy of limited enforcement has also been adopted in many countries, in particular [[Spain]] and the [[Netherlands]] where the sale of cannabis is tolerated at licensed establishments.<ref name=\"clubs jane\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Tasha |title=\"New Amsterdam\" No More? Spain's Cannabis Clubs Fight to Stay Open |url=https://merryjane.com/culture/spains-cannabis-social-clubs-feature-june-2018 |accessdate=23 August 2018 |work=Merry Jane |date=5 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"coffeeshops\">{{cite news |last1=Haines |first1=Gavin |title=Everything you need to know about marijuana smoking in the Netherlands |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/netherlands/amsterdam/articles/everything-you-need-to-know-about-smoking-marijuana-in-the-netherlands/ |accessdate=22 July 2018 |work=The Telegraph |date=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Occupational health concerns of cannabis use]]\n* [[The Green Rush]]\n\n== References ==\n'''Footnotes'''\n<!-- Please do not add any more nicknames, this should give an overview of the most common ones. -->\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary|marijuana}}\n{{Commons category-inline|Cannabis}}\n* [[wikt:Appendix:Cannabis slang|Wiktionary Appendix of Cannabis Slang]]\n\n{{Cannabis|state=expanded}}\n{{Cannabinoids}}\n{{Cannabinoid receptor modulators}}\n{{Analgesics}}\n{{Euphoriants}}\n{{Psychoactive substance use}}\n{{Drug use}}\n{{Portalbar|Cannabis|Pharmacy and Pharmacology}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cannabis (Drug)}}\n[[Category:Appetite stimulants]]\n[[Category:Cannabis| ]]\n[[Category:Cannabis smoking]]\n[[Category:Entheogens]]\n[[Category:Euphoriants]]\n[[Category:Herbalism]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{About|the psychoactive drug|the plant from which it is harvested|Cannabis|other uses|Cannabis (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Marijuana}}\n{{Pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|psychoactive drug from the Cannabis plant}}\n{{pp-semi-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox botanical product\n|pronounce = {{small|(cannabis)}} {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u00e6|n|\u0259|b|\u026a|s}}<br>{{small|(marijuana)}} {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|m|\u00e6|r|\u0259|\u02c8|w|\u0251\u02d0|n|\u0259}}<ref>{{cite web |title=marijuana noun \u2013 Definition, pictures, pronunciation and usage notes {{!}} Oxford Advanced Learner's Dictionary at OxfordLearnersDictionaries.com |url=https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/marijuana |website=www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com |accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n|product = Cannabis\n|image = Hampa Cannabis sativa L. (n\u00e4rbild).jpg\n|caption = Close-up of flowering cannabis plant\n|plant = ''[[Cannabis sativa]]'', ''[[Cannabis indica]]'', ''[[Cannabis ruderalis]]''\n|part = [[Inflorescence|Flower]] and [[Infructescence|fruit]]\n|origin = [[Central Asia]] and [[Indian subcontinent]]<ref name=\"ElSohly2007\">{{cite book | first =Mahmoud A. | last1 = ElSohly | name-list-format = vanc |title=Marijuana and the Cannabinoids|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fxoJPVNKYUgC&pg=PA8|year=2007|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-59259-947-9|page=8}}</ref>\n|active = [[Tetrahydrocannabinol]], [[cannabidiol]], [[cannabinol]], [[tetrahydrocannabivarin]]\n|producers = Afghanistan,<ref name=UNDRUG2013>{{cite web|author=United Nations|title=World Drug Report 2013|url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/secured/wdr/wdr2013/World_Drug_Report_2013.pdf|publisher=[[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]]|access-date=13 December 2014}}</ref> Canada,<ref>{{cite web|title=Medical Use of Marijuana|url=http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/dhp-mps/marihuana/index-eng.php|website=Health Canada|access-date=12 January 2015}}</ref> China, Colombia,<ref>{{cite web|title=New Colombia Resources Inc Subsidiary, Sannabis, Produces First Batch of Medical Marijuana Based Products in Colombia to Fill Back Orders|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/new-colombia-resources-inc-subsidiary-sannabis-produces-first-batch-of-medical-marijuana-based-products-in-colombia-to-fill-back-orders-879870332.html|website=prnewswire.com|publisher=PR Newswire|access-date=12 January 2015}}</ref> India,<ref name=UNDRUG2013 /> Jamaica,<ref name=\"UNDRUG2013\"/> Lebanon,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/video.cfm?c_id=1503076&gal_cid=1503076&gallery_id=139379|title=Lebanon cannabis trade thrives in shadow of Syrian war|first = Rana | last = Moussaoui | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=AFP|date=Nov 25, 2013}}</ref> Mexico,<ref name=Garelli/> Morocco,<ref name=UNDRUG2013 /> Netherlands, Pakistan, Paraguay,<ref name=Garelli>{{cite news|title=Mexico, Paraguay top pot producers, U.N. report says|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/americas/11/25/paraguay.mexico.marijuana/|access-date=28 September 2013|newspaper=CNN International|date=25 November 2008| first = Sanie Lopez | last = Garelli | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> Spain,<ref name=UNDRUG2013 /> Thailand, Turkey, United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite web | last=Jackman | first=Robert | title=How Britain became the world's largest exporter of medical marijuana | website=The Spectator | date=2019-01-12 | url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2019/01/how-britain-became-the-worlds-largest-expert-in-medical-marijuana/amp/ | ref=harv | access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> United States<ref name=UNDRUG2013 />\n|wholesale =\n|retail =\n|legal_AU = S9\n|legal_CA = Unscheduled\n|legal_DE = Medical cannabis from state-controlled production: [[Anlage III]], other cannabis: [[Anlage I|I]]\n|legal_UK = Class B\n|legal_US = [[Schedule I Controlled Substance|Schedule I]] (legal recreationally in 11 states & DC; medically legal in 33 states)\n|legal_UN = Narcotic Schedule I\n}}\n'''Cannabis''', also known as '''marijuana''' among other names,{{efn|Also referred to as ''marihuana'', ''pot'', ''weed'', ''dope'', and ''ganja'' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u0251\u02d0|n|d\u0292|\u0259}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/pot|title=Pot&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|access-date=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/weed|title=Weed&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary |access-date=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/dope |title=Dope&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|access-date=17 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/ganja |title=Ganja&nbsp;\u2013 Definition |publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|access-date=17 July 2017}}</ref> among many other nicknames (''grass'', ''herb'', ''skunk'', ''Mary Jane'', etc.).<ref name=\"M.D.Strain2011\">{{cite book|first1=Pedro|last1=Ruiz|first2=Eric C.|last2=Strain|name-list-format=vanc|title=Substance Abuse: A Comprehensive Textbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w4ZUJAdleTsC&pg=PA214|year=2011|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|isbn=978-1-60547-277-5|page=214}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/grass|title=Grass&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary |access-date=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/herb |title=Herb&nbsp;\u2013 Definition |publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|access-date=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=skunk |title=Skunk&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language|access-date=17 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/Mary%20Jane|title=Mary Jane&nbsp;\u2013 Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|access-date=17 July 2017}}</ref>}} is a [[psychoactive drug]] from the [[Cannabis|''Cannabis'' plant]] used for [[medical cannabis|medical]] or [[Recreational drug use|recreational]] purposes.<ref>{{cite book|author=Vij|title=Textbook Of Forensic Medicine And Toxicology: Principles And Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vp8FAsnfGF4C&pg=PT672|year=2012|publisher=Elsevier India|isbn=978-81-312-1129-8|page=672}}See also article on [[marijuana (word)|''Marijuana'' as a word]].</ref><ref>{{ShorterOxfordEnglishDictionary}}</ref><ref name=\"Dictionaries2007m\">{{cite book|author=|title=Spanish Word Histories and Mysteries: English Words That Come From Spanish|url=https://archive.org/details/spanishwordhisto00houg|url-access=registration|year=2007|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|isbn=978-0-547-35021-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/spanishwordhisto00houg/page/142 142]}}</ref> The primary psychoactive component of cannabis is [[tetrahydrocannabinol]] (THC), which is one of the 483 known compounds in the plant,<ref name=\"Russo2013\">{{cite book|first=Ethan B.|last=Russo|name-list-format=vanc|title=Cannabis and Cannabinoids: Pharmacology, Toxicology, and Therapeutic Potential|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qH-2Lj9x7L4C&pg=PP28|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-61493-4|page=28}}</ref> including at least 65 other [[cannabinoids]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Newton|first1=David E.| name-list-format = vanc | title = Marijuana: a reference handbook|date=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=9781610691499|page=7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iWMf95ze8QEC&pg=PA7}}</ref> Cannabis can be used by [[Cannabis smoking|smoking]], [[Vaporizer (inhalation device)|vaporizing]], [[Cannabis edible|within food]], or [[Tincture of cannabis|as an extract]].<ref name=NIH2016/>\n\n<!-- Effects -->\nCannabis has [[effects of cannabis|mental and physical effects]]. It causes a \"[[euphoria|high]]\", or stoned feeling and other effects, including a general [[altered state of consciousness|change in perception]], difficulty thinking, [[Cannabis and memory|impaired short-term memory]], altered sense of time, impaired [[motor skill|body movement]],<ref name=NIH2016/> relaxation,<ref name=\"pmid18365950\"/> and an increase in [[appetite]], otherwise known as \"munchies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adai.uw.edu/marijuana/factsheets/appetite.htm |title=Marijuana: Factsheets: Appetite |publisher=Adai.uw.edu |access-date=12 July 2013}}</ref> At high doses, mental effects include [[Cannabis and psychosis|psychosis]], delusions, hallucinations,<ref name=\"NIH2016\" /> paranoia, and [[Ideas of reference and delusions of reference|ideas of reference]], sometimes with anxiety and panic.<ref name=\"D'Souza\" /> Its physical effects include increased heart rate, difficulty breathing, nausea, and behavioral problems in children whose mothers used cannabis during pregnancy.<ref name=\"NIH2016\" /> Short-term side effects may include a [[xerostomia|dry mouth]], red eyes, and feelings of [[paranoia]] or [[anxiety]].<ref name=NLMNIH>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/000952.htm|title=Marijuana intoxication: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia|publisher=Nlm.nih.gov|access-date=12 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Crippa JA, Zuardi AW, Mart\u00edn-Santos R, Bhattacharyya S, Atakan Z, McGuire P, Fusar-Poli P|title=Cannabis and anxiety: a critical review of the evidence|journal=Human Psychopharmacology|volume=24|issue=7|pages=515\u201323|date=October 2009|pmid=19693792|doi=10.1002/hup.1048}}</ref> Long-term [[adverse effect]]s may include addiction, decreased [[neurocognition|mental ability]] in those who started regular use as [[adolescent]]s, chronic [[cough|coughing]], and susceptibility to [[Respiratory tract infection|respiratory infections]].<ref name=\"Abuse 2019\">{{cite web |publisher=National Institute on Drug Abuse, US National Institutes of Health| title=Commonly Abused Drugs Charts: Marijuana (Cannabis) | date=2019-07-22 | url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/drugs-abuse/commonly-abused-drugs-charts#marijuana-cannabis-| access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> There is a strong relation between cannabis use and the risk of psychosis,<ref name=Leweke2016rev>{{cite journal|vauthors=Leweke FM, Mueller JK, Lange B, Rohleder C|title=Therapeutic Potential of Cannabinoids in Psychosis|journal=Biological Psychiatry|volume=79|issue=7|pages=604\u201312|date=April 2016|pmid=26852073|doi=10.1016/j.biopsych.2015.11.018 |quote=Epidemiological data indicate a strong relationship between cannabis use and psychosis and schizophrenia beyond transient intoxication with an increased risk of any psychotic outcome in individuals who had ever used cannabis}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ortiz-Medina |first1=MB |last2=Perea |first2=M |last3=Torales |first3=J |last4=Ventriglio |first4=A |last5=Vitrani |first5=G |last6=Aguilar |first6=L |last7=Roncero |first7=C |title=Cannabis consumption and psychosis or schizophrenia development. |journal=The International Journal of Social Psychiatry |date=November 2018 |volume=64 |issue=7 |pages=690\u2013704 |doi=10.1177/0020764018801690 |pmid=30442059|quote=Cannabis use doubles the risk of developing psychosis in vulnerable people.}}</ref> though the [[cause and effect]] is debated.<ref name=\"doi:10.1007/s11920-015-0657-y\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Ksir C, Hart CL|title=Cannabis and Psychosis: a Critical Overview of the Relationship|journal=Current Psychiatry Reports|volume=18|issue=2|pages=12|date=February 2016|pmid=26781550|doi=10.1007/s11920-015-0657-y }}</ref> Onset of effects is felt within minutes when smoked, and about 30 to 60 minutes when cooked and eaten.<ref name=NIH2016/><ref name=\"Ri2010\" /> The effects last for two to six hours, depending on the amount of consumption.<ref name=Ri2010>{{cite book|last1=Riviello|first1=Ralph J. | name-list-format = vanc |title=Manual of forensic emergency medicine : a guide for clinicians|date=2010|publisher=Jones and Bartlett Publishers|location=Sudbury, Mass.|isbn=9780763744625|page=41|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=keng9ELAE2IC&pg=PA41}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Usage -->\nCannabis is mostly used for recreational use or as a medicinal drug, although it may also be used for [[Entheogenic use of cannabis|spiritual purposes]]. In 2013, between 128 and 232 million people used cannabis (2.7% to 4.9% of the global population between the ages of 15 and 65).<ref name=WDR2015>{{cite book|title=World Drug Report 2015|chapter-url=http://www.unodc.org/documents/wdr2015/WDR15_Drug_use_health_consequences.pdf|access-date=26 June 2015|chapter=Status and Trend Analysis of {{sic|nolink=y|Illict}} Drug Markets|page=23}}</ref> It is the most commonly used [[illegal drug]] both in the world and the United States,<ref name=NIH2016>{{cite web|title=DrugFacts: Marijuana|url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/publications/drugfacts/marijuana|publisher=National Institute on Drug Abuse, US National Institutes of Health|access-date=20 January 2020|date=1 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=WDR2015/> though it is also legal in some jurisdictions. The countries with the highest use among adults {{as of|2018|lc=y}} are Zambia, the United States, Canada, and Nigeria.<ref>{{cite web |title=UNODC Statistics Online |url=https://data.unodc.org/ |website=data.unodc.org |accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref> In 2016, 51% of people in the United States had used cannabis in their lifetimes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Salvanto |first1=Anthony |last2=Backus |first2=Fred |last3=De Pinto |first3=Jennifer |last4=Dutton |first4=Sarah |title=Marijuana use and support for legal marijuana continue to climb |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/marijuana-use-and-support-for-legal-marijuana-continue-to-climb/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=CBS News |date=April 20, 2016}}</ref> About 12% had used it in the past year, and 7.3% had used it in the past month.<ref name=\"6 facts about marijuana\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/04/14/6-facts-about-marijuana/|title=6 facts about marijuana|last=Motel|first=Seth|name-list-format=vanc|website=Pew Research Center|access-date=26 June 2015|date=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n<!-- History, society and culture -->\nWhile cannabis plants have been grown since at least the 3rd millennium BCE,<ref name=\"Booth2003\">{{cite book|first=Martin|last=Booth|authorlink=Martin Booth|name-list-format=vanc|title=Cannabis: A History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mjn6sCiHoFIC&pg=PA36|year=2003|publisher=Transworld|isbn=978-1-4090-8489-1|page=36}}</ref> evidence suggests that it was being smoked for psychoactive effects at least 2,500 years ago in the [[Pamir Mountains]].<ref name=\"NatGeo2019Jun\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/culture/2019/06/earliest-evidence-cannabis-marijuana-smoking-china-tombs/ |title=Earliest evidence for cannabis smoking discovered in ancient tombs|date= 2019-06-12|first=Michelle |last=Donahue |work=National Geographic}}</ref> Since the early 20th century, cannabis has been subject to legal restrictions. The possession, use, and cultivation of cannabis is [[Legality of cannabis|illegal in most countries of the world]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erowid.org/plants/cannabis/cannabis_law.shtml|title=Cannabis: Legal Status|publisher=Erowid.org|access-date=30 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"UN-WDR-2010\">{{cite book|last=UNODC|title=World Drug Report 2010|publisher=United Nations Publication|page=198|url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/data-and-analysis/WDR-2010.html |access-date=2010-07-19}}</ref> In 2013, Uruguay became the first country to legalize recreational use of cannabis.<ref name=\"newsweek2018\">{{cite news |last1=Lemon |first1=Jason |title=Where Is Weed Legal Around The World? You Can Now Officially Smoke Pot In Canada |url=https://www.newsweek.com/where-weed-legal-around-world-you-can-now-officially-smoke-pot-canada-1173623 |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=Newsweek |date=17 October 2018}}</ref> Other countries to do so are Canada, Georgia, and South Africa, along with 11 states and the District of Columbia in the United States (though the drug remains federally illegal).<ref name=\"newsweek2018\" /><ref name=\"ncsl rec\">{{cite web |title=Marijuana Overview |url=http://www.ncsl.org/research/civil-and-criminal-justice/marijuana-overview.aspx |website=National Conference of State Legislatures |accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> Medical use of cannabis, requiring the approval of a physician, has been legalized in a greater number of countries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Sean |title=These 30 Countries Have Legalized Medical Marijuana in Some Capacity |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2018/07/21/these-30-countries-have-legalized-medical-marijuan.aspx |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=The Motley Fool |date=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Uses==\n===Medical===\n{{Main|Medical cannabis}}\n[[File:Bodily effects of cannabis.svg|thumb|upright=1.1|Main short-term physical effects of cannabis]]\nMedical cannabis, or medical marijuana, can refer to the use of cannabis and its [[cannabinoids]] to treat disease or improve symptoms; however, there is no single agreed-upon definition.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Murnion B|title=Medicinal cannabis| journal=Australian Prescriber|volume=38|issue =6|pages=212\u20135|date=December 2015|pmid=26843715|pmc=4674028|doi=10.18773/austprescr.2015.072 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=What is medical marijuana?|url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/publications/drugfacts/marijuana-medicine|website=National Institute of Drug Abuse|access-date=19 April 2016|date=July 2015|quote=The term medical marijuana refers to using the whole unprocessed marijuana plant or its basic extracts to treat a disease or symptom.}}</ref> The rigorous scientific study of cannabis as a medicine has been hampered by production restrictions and by the fact that it is classified as an illegal drug by many governments.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=|title=Release the strains|journal=Nature Medicine|volume=21|issue=9|pages=963|date=September 2015|pmid=26340110|doi=10.1038/nm.3946}}</ref> There is limited evidence suggesting cannabis can be used to [[antiemetic|reduce nausea and vomiting]] during [[chemotherapy]], to improve appetite in people with [[HIV/AIDS]], or to treat [[chronic pain]] and [[muscle spasms]].<ref name=\"Borgelt2013\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Borgelt LM, Franson KL, Nussbaum AM, Wang GS|date=February 2013|title=The pharmacologic and clinical effects of medical cannabis|journal=Pharmacotherapy|volume=33|issue=2|pages=195\u2013209|doi=10.1002/phar.1187|pmid=23386598|citeseerx=10.1.1.1017.1935}}</ref><ref name=JAMA2015>{{cite journal|vauthors=Whiting PF, Wolff RF, Deshpande S, Di Nisio M, Duffy S, Hernandez AV, Keurentjes JC, Lang S, Misso K, Ryder S, Schmidlkofer S, Westwood M, Kleijnen J|title=Cannabinoids for Medical Use: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis|journal=JAMA|volume=313|issue=24|pages=2456\u201373|date=23 June 2015|pmid=26103030|doi=10.1001/jama.2015.6358|hdl=10757/558499}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Jensen B, Chen J, Furnish T, Wallace M|title=Medical Marijuana and Chronic Pain: a Review of Basic Science and Clinical Evidence|journal=Current Pain and Headache Reports|volume=19|issue=10|pages=50|date=October 2015|pmid=26325482|doi=10.1007/s11916-015-0524-x}}</ref> Its use for other medical applications is insufficient for drawing conclusions about safety or efficacy.\n\n<!-- Side effects -->\nShort-term use increases the risk of both minor and major adverse effects.<ref name=JAMA2015/> Common side effects include dizziness, feeling tired and vomiting.<ref name=JAMA2015/> The [[long-term effects of cannabis]] are not clear.<ref name=JAMA2015/> There are concerns surrounding [[Cannabis and memory|memory and cognition problems]], risk of addiction, risk of [[schizophrenia]] in young people, and the risk of children taking it by accident.<ref name=Borgelt2013/>\n\n===Recreational===\n{{Main|Effects of cannabis}}\nCannabis has psychoactive and physiological effects when consumed.<ref name=\"OnaiviSugiura2005\">{{cite book|first1=Emmanuel S.|last1=Onaivi|first2=Takayuki|last2=Sugiura|first3=Vincenzo|last3=Di Marzo|name-list-format=vanc|title=Endocannabinoids: The Brain and Body's Marijuana and Beyond|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BxfLB4n3uoMC&pg=PA58|year=2005|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-30008-7|page=58}}</ref> The immediate desired effects from consuming cannabis include relaxation and [[euphoria]] (the \"high\" or \"stoned\" feeling), a general [[altered state of consciousness|alteration of conscious perception]], increased awareness of sensation, increased [[libido]]<ref name=\"pmid18365950\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Osborne GB, Fogel C|title=Understanding the motivations for recreational marijuana use among adult Canadians|journal=Substance Use & Misuse|volume=43|issue=3\u20134|pages=539\u201372; discussion 573\u20139, 585\u20137|date=2008|pmid=18365950|doi=10.1080/10826080701884911|url=http://cannabislink.ca/info/MotivationsforCannabisUsebyCanadianAdults-2008.pdf }}</ref> and [[Cannabis and time perception|distortions in the perception of time]] and space. At higher doses, effects can include altered [[body image]], auditory and/or visual [[illusion]]s, [[pseudohallucination]]s and [[ataxia]] from selective impairment of [[Reflex arc|polysynaptic]] [[reflex]]es. In some cases, cannabis can lead to [[dissociation (psychology)|dissociative]] states such as [[depersonalization]]<ref name=\"medscape1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/468728_3|title=Medication-Associated Depersonalization Symptoms }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid15889607\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Shufman E, Lerner A, Witztum E|title=[Depersonalization after withdrawal from cannabis usage]|language=Hebrew|journal=Harefuah|volume=144|issue=4|pages=249\u201351, 303|date=April 2005|pmid=15889607|url=http://www.ima.org.il/Ima/FormStorage/Type3/05-04-07.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050430224332/http://www.ima.org.il/Ima/FormStorage/Type3/05-04-07.pdf|archive-date=30 April 2005}}</ref> and [[derealization]].<ref name=\"Johnson1990\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Johnson BA|title=Psychopharmacological effects of cannabis|journal=British Journal of Hospital Medicine|volume=43|issue=2|pages=114\u20136, 118\u201320, 122|date=February 1990|pmid=2178712}}</ref>\n\nSome immediate undesired side effects include a decrease in short-term memory, dry mouth, impaired motor skills and reddening of the eyes.<ref name=\"HallPacula2003ew\">{{cite book|first1=Wayne|last1=Hall|first2=Rosalie Liccardo|last2=Pacula|name-list-format=vanc |title=Cannabis Use and Dependence: Public Health and Public Policy|url=https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence|url-access=registration|year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-80024-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence/page/n35 38]}}</ref> Aside from a subjective change in perception and mood, the most common short-term physical and neurological effects include increased heart rate, increased appetite and consumption of food, lowered blood pressure, impairment of short-term and working memory,<ref name=\"Mathre1997\">{{cite book|editor-first=Mary Lynn|editor-last=Mathre|name-list-format=vanc|title=Cannabis in Medical Practice: A Legal, Historical, and Pharmacological Overview of the Therapeutic Use of Marijuana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1AWGDhIOvk0C&pg=PA144|year=1997|publisher=University of Virginia Medical Center|isbn=978-0-7864-8390-7|pages=144\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"memoryhindered\">{{cite book|vauthors=Riedel G, Davies SN|chapter=Cannabinoid function in learning, memory and plasticity|volume=168|issue=168|pages=445\u201377|year=2005|pmid=16596784|doi=10.1007/3-540-26573-2_15|isbn=978-3-540-22565-2|series=Handbook of Experimental Pharmacology |title=Cannabinoids}}</ref> [[Motor coordination|psychomotor coordination]], and concentration. Some users may experience an episode of acute [[psychosis]], which usually abates after six hours, but in rare instances, heavy users may find the symptoms continuing for many days.<ref name=\"Barceloux2012\" />\n\nA reduced [[quality of life]] is associated with heavy cannabis use, although the relationship is inconsistent and weaker than for tobacco and other substances.<ref name=Gold2017>{{cite journal|vauthors=Goldenberg M, IsHak WW, Danovitch I|title=Quality of life and recreational cannabis use|journal=The American Journal on Addictions|volume=26|issue=1|pages=8\u201325|date=January 2017|pmid=28000973|doi=10.1111/ajad.12486 }}</ref> The direction of [[causality|cause and effect relationship]], however, is unclear.<ref name=Gold2017/>\n\n===Spiritual===\n[[File:Ganja Smoking - Gangasagar Fair Transit Camp - Kolkata 2013-01-12 2646.JPG|thumb|upright=1.2|A man smoking cannabis]]\n{{Main|Entheogenic use of cannabis}}\nCannabis has held sacred status in several religions and has served as an [[entheogen]] \u2013 a [[chemical substance]] used in [[religion|religious]], [[shamanism|shamanic]], or [[spirituality|spiritual]] contexts<ref>{{cite journal |title=Brazilian Archives of Biology and Technology \u2013 Jurema-Preta (Mimosa tenuiflora [Willd.] Poir.): a review of its traditional use, phytochemistry and pharmacology |journal=Brazilian Archives of Biology and Technology |volume=51 |issue=5 |pages=937\u2013947 |doi=10.1590/S1516-89132008000500010 |year=2008 |last1=Souza |first1=Rafael Sampaio Octaviano de |last2=Albuquerque |first2=Ulysses Paulino de |last3=Monteiro |first3=J\u00falio Marcelino |last4= de Amorim |first4=Elba L\u00facia Cavalcanti | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> \u2013 in the Indian subcontinent since the [[Vedic period]] dating back to approximately 1500 BCE, but perhaps as far back as 2000 BCE. There are several references in Greek mythology to a powerful drug that eliminated anguish and sorrow. [[Herodotus]] wrote about early ceremonial practices by the [[Scythians]], thought to have occurred from the 5th to 2nd century BCE. In modern culture, the spiritual use of cannabis has been spread by the disciples of the [[Rastafari movement]] who use cannabis as a [[sacrament]] and as an aid to meditation. The earliest known reports regarding the sacred status of cannabis in the Indian subcontinent come from the [[Atharva Veda]], estimated to have been composed sometime around 1400 BCE.<ref>{{cite book|title=Forces of Habit: Drugs and the Making of the Modern World|last=Courtwright|first=David|name-list-format=vanc|year=2001|publisher=Harvard Univ. Press|location=|isbn=978-0-674-00458-0|page=39|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GHqV3elHYvMC&pg=PP10&dq=Forces+of+Habit#v=onepage&q=atharva}}</ref>\n\n===Available forms===\n{{Main|Cannabis consumption}}\n[[File:Unrolled joint.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|A joint prior to rolling, with a paper handmade filter on the left]]\nCannabis is consumed in many different ways:<ref name=\"Golub2012a\">{{cite book|first=Andrew|last=Golub|name-list-format=vanc |title=The Cultural/Subcultural Contexts of Marijuana Use at the Turn of the Twenty-First Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KFMtFv2tmbYC&pg=PA82|year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-44627-6|page=82}}</ref>\n* [[Cannabis smoking|smoking]], which typically involves burning and inhaling vaporized cannabinoids (\"smoke\") from [[One hitter (smoking)|small pipes]], [[bong]]s (portable versions of [[hookah]]s with a water chamber), paper-wrapped [[joint (cannabis)|joints]] or tobacco-leaf-wrapped [[blunt (cigar)|blunts]], and other items.<ref name=\"TasmanKay2011\">{{cite book|first1=Allan|last1=Tasman|first2=Jerald|last2=Kay|first3=Jeffrey A.|last3=Lieberman|first4=Michael B.|last4=First|first5=Mario | last5=Maj|name-list-format=vanc|title=Psychiatry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vVG7zz7eaxcC&pg=RA9-PT2217|year=2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-96540-4|page=9}}</ref>\n* [[vaporizer (cannabis)|vaporizer]], which heats any form of cannabis to {{convert|165|\u2013|190|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}},<ref name=\"Rosenthal2002b\">{{cite book|first=Ed|last=Rosenthal|name-list-format=vanc|title=Ask Ed: Marijuana Gold: Trash to Stash |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=obbSwmSB6okC&pg=PT15|year=2002|publisher=Perseus Books Group|isbn=978-1-936807-02-4|page=15}}</ref> causing the active ingredients to evaporate into [[vapor]] without burning the plant material (the boiling point of [[tetrahydrocannabinol|THC]] is {{convert|157|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} at atmospheric pressure).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cannabis-med.org/data/pdf/2001-03-04-7.pdf|title=Cannabis and Cannabis Extracts: Greater Than the Sum of Their Parts?|publisher=Cannabis-med.org|accessdate=7 April 2014}}</ref>\n* [[cannabis tea]], which contains relatively small concentrations of THC because THC is an oil ([[lipophilic]]) and is only slightly water-soluble (with a solubility of 2.8&nbsp;mg per liter).<ref name=\"Physical Properties \u2013 Dronabinol\">{{ChemID|1972-08-3|Dronabinol}}</ref> Cannabis tea is made by first adding a [[saturated fat]] to hot water (e.g. cream or any milk except skim) with a small amount of cannabis.<ref name=\"Ph.D.Rosenthal2008yt\">{{cite book|first1=Dale|last1=Gieringer|first2=Ed|last2=Rosenthal|name-list-format = vanc |title=Marijuana medical handbook: practical guide to therapeutic uses of marijuana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OuAHxDKcpS8C&pg=PA182|year=2008|publisher=QUICK AMER Publishing Company|isbn=978-0-932551-86-3|page=182}}</ref>\n* [[Cannabis foods|edibles]], where cannabis is added as an ingredient to one of a variety of foods, including butter and baked goods. In India it is commonly made into a beverage, [[bhang]].\n* [[Capsule (pharmacy)|capsules]], typically containing [[hash oil|cannabis oil]], and other [[dietary supplement]] products, for which some 220 were approved in Canada in 2018.<ref name=\"canada2018\">{{cite web|title=Health products containing cannabis or for use with cannabis: Guidance for the Cannabis Act, the Food and Drugs Act, and related regulations|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/health-canada/services/drugs-health-products/drug-products/applications-submissions/guidance-documents/guidance-cannabis-act-food-and-drugs-act-related-regulations/document.html |publisher=Government of Canada|date=11 July 2018|accessdate=19 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Adverse effects==\n{{See also|Long-term effects of cannabis}}\n{{Further|Cannabis in pregnancy}}\n[[File:Rational harm assessment of drugs radar plot.svg|thumb|Addiction experts in psychiatry, chemistry, pharmacology, forensic science, epidemiology, and the police and legal services engaged in [[Delphi method|delphic analysis]] regarding 20 popular recreational drugs. Cannabis was ranked 11th in dependence, 17th in physical harm, and 10th in social harm.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Nutt D, King LA, Saulsbury W, Blakemore C | title = Development of a rational scale to assess the harm of drugs of potential misuse|journal=Lancet|volume=369|issue=9566|pages=1047\u201353|date=March 2007|pmid=17382831|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(07)60464-4 }}</ref>]]\n\n===Short term===\nAcute effects may include anxiety and panic, impaired attention and memory, an increased risk of psychotic symptoms,{{efn|Psychotic episodes are well-documented and typically resolve within minutes or hours, while symptoms may last longer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhra.gov.uk/home/groups/par/documents/websiteresources/con084961.pdf |title=Sativex Oral Mucosal Spray Public Assessment Report. Decentralized Procedure. |page=93 |publisher=United Kingdom Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency |access-date=2015-05-07 |quote=There is clear evidence that recreational cannabis can produce a transient toxic psychosis in larger doses or in susceptible individuals, which is said to characteristically resolve within a week or so of absence (Johns 2001). Transient psychotic episodes as a component of acute intoxication are well-documented (Hall et al 1994) }}</ref> The use of a single joint can temporarily induce some psychiatric symptoms.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Katie |title=Single cannabis joint linked with temporary psychiatric symptoms, review finds |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/health/cannabis-psychiatric-symptoms-wellness/index.html |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=CNN |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>}} the inability to think clearly, and an increased risk of accidents.<ref name=\"W. Hall, N. Solowij 1611\u201316\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Hall W, Solowij N|title=Adverse effects of cannabis|journal =Lancet|volume=352|issue=9140|pages=1611\u20136|date=November 1998|pmid=9843121|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(98)05021-1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Abnormal Psychology|last1=Oltmanns|first1=Thomas|first2=Robert|last2=Emery|publisher = Pearson|year=2015|isbn=978-0205970742|location=New Jersey|page=294|name-list-format=vanc}}</ref><ref name=D'Souza>{{cite journal|vauthors=D'Souza DC, Sewell RA, Ranganathan M|title=Cannabis and psychosis/schizophrenia: human studies|journal=European Archives of Psychiatry and Clinical Neuroscience|volume=259|issue=7|pages=413\u201331|date=October 2009|pmid=19609589|pmc=2864503|doi=10.1007/s00406-009-0024-2 }}</ref> Cannabis impairs a person's driving ability, and [[Tetrahydrocannabinol|THC]] was the illicit drug most frequently found in the blood of drivers who have been involved in vehicle crashes. Those with THC in their system are from three to seven times more likely to be the cause of the accident than those who had not used either cannabis or alcohol, although its role is not necessarily causal because THC stays in the bloodstream for days to weeks after intoxication.<ref name=NIH-2>{{cite web |last1=Abuse |first1=National Institute on Drug |title=Does marijuana use affect driving? |url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/publications/research-reports/marijuana/does-marijuana-use-affect-driving |website=www.drugabuse.gov |accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Li MC, Brady JE, DiMaggio CJ, Lusardi AR, Tzong KY, Li G|title=Marijuana use and motor vehicle crashes|journal=Epidemiologic Reviews|volume=34|issue=1|pages=65\u201372|date=4 October 2011|pmid=21976636|pmc=3276316|doi=10.1093/epirev/mxr017 }}</ref>{{efn|A 2016 review also found a statistically significant increase in crash risk associated with marijuana use, but noted that this risk was \"of low to medium magnitude.\"<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Rogeberg O, Elvik R|title=The effects of cannabis intoxication on motor vehicle collision revisited and revised|journal=Addiction|volume=111|issue=8|pages=1348\u201359|date=August 2016|pmid=26878835|doi=10.1111/add.13347|url=https://zenodo.org/record/897625}}</ref> The increase in risk of motor vehicle crash for cannabis use is between 2 and 3 times relative to baseline, whereas that for comparable doses of alcohol is between 6 and 15 times.<ref name=hall2015>{{cite journal|vauthors=Hall W|title=What has research over the past two decades revealed about the adverse health effects of recreational cannabis use?|journal=Addiction|volume=110|issue=1|pages=19\u201335|date=January 2015|pmid=25287883|doi=10.1111/add.12703|url=https://espace.library.uq.edu.au/view/UQ:346328/Hall_2014_20ycann_OA_post.pdf}}</ref>}}\n\nAccording to the United States Department of Health and Human Services, there were 455,000 emergency room visits associated with cannabis use in 2011. These statistics include visits in which the patient was treated for a condition induced by or related to recent cannabis use. The drug use must be \"implicated\" in the emergency department visit, but does not need to be the direct cause of the visit. Most of the illicit drug emergency room visits involved multiple drugs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.samhsa.gov/data/sites/default/files/DAWN2k11ED/DAWN2k11ED/DAWN2k11ED.pdf|work=Drug Abuse Warning Network|title=National Estimates of Drug-Related Emergency Department Visits|publisher=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services|date = 2011 | access-date = 8 May 2015}}</ref> In 129,000 cases, cannabis was the only implicated drug.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.samhsa.gov/data/sites/default/files/Nation_2011_AllMA.xls |title=National Estimates of Drug-related Emergency Department Visits, 2004 \u2013 2011|work=Drug Abuse Warning Network|publisher=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services }}</ref><ref name=NEJM2014>{{cite journal|vauthors=Volkow ND, Baler RD, Compton WM, Weiss SR|title=Adverse health effects of marijuana use|journal=The New England Journal of Medicine|volume=370|issue=23|pages=2219\u201327|date=June 2014|pmid=24897085|pmc=4827335|doi=10.1056/NEJMra1402309}}</ref>\n\nThe short term effects of cannabis can be altered if it has been laced with [[opioid]] drugs such as [[heroin]] or [[fentanyl]].<ref>[https://www.medpagetoday.com/primarycare/opioids/74071 \"Growing Array of Street Drugs Now Laced with Fentanyl\"], ''MedPageToday'', July 17, 2018</ref> The added drugs are meant to enhance the psychoactive properties, add to its weight, and increase profitability, despite the increased danger of overdose.<ref>[https://americanaddictioncenters.org/marijuana-rehab/what-can-marijuana-be-laced-with \"What Can Marijuana Be Laced With?\"], ''American Addiction Centers'', updated Nov. 26, 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/opinion/oped/bs-ed-op-1207-fentanyl-opioid-20181206-story.html \"Is the opioid epidemic now the fentanyl epidemic?\"], ''The Baltimore Sun'', Dec. 7, 2018</ref>{{efn|Advocates of legalizing marijuana for recreational use, such as Illinois state Senator [[Heather Steans]], has said that legalizing it would help reduce such hazardous added drugs: \"Over 95 percent are buying it on the black market. You don't know what you\u2019re buying. It's not a safe product. We've seen it laced with rat poison, fentanyl, all sorts of things. It's funding the cartels and other criminal activity.\"<ref>[https://www.sj-r.com/news/20181215/medical-officials-oppose-effort-to-legalize-recreational-use-of-marijuana \"Medical officials oppose effort to legalize recreational use of marijuana\"], ''State Journal-Register'', (Springfield, IL), Dec. 15, 2018</ref>}}\n\n===Long term===\nHeavy, long-term exposure to marijuana may have biologically based physical, mental, behavioral and social health consequences and may be \"associated with diseases of the liver (particularly with co-existing [[hepatitis C]]), lungs, heart, and vasculature\".<ref name=\"Gordon2013\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Gordon AJ, Conley JW, Gordon JM|title=Medical consequences of marijuana use: a review of current literature|journal=Current Psychiatry Reports|volume=15|issue=12|pages=419|date=December 2013|pmid=24234874|doi=10.1007/s11920-013-0419-7|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1232874}}</ref> Mothers who used marijuana during pregnancy have children with more depression, hyperactivity, and inattention.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nomura |first1=Y |last2=Marks |first2=DJ |last3=Halperin |first3=JM |title=Prenatal exposure to maternal and paternal smoking on attention deficit hyperactivity disorders symptoms and diagnosis in offspring. |journal=The Journal of Nervous and Mental Disease |date=September 2010 |volume=198 |issue=9 |pages=672\u20138 |doi=10.1097/NMD.0b013e3181ef3489 |pmid=20823730|pmc=3124822 }}</ref> It is recommended that cannabis use be stopped before and during [[pregnancy]] as it can result in negative outcomes for both the mother and baby.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Committee Opinion No. 637: Marijuana Use During Pregnancy and Lactation|journal=Obstetrics and Gynecology|volume=126|issue=1|pages=234\u20138|date=July 2015|pmid=26241291|doi=10.1097/01.AOG.0000467192.89321.a6|author1=American College of Obstetricians Gynecologists Committee on Obstetric Practice}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Gunn JK, Rosales CB, Center KE, Nu\u00f1ez A, Gibson SJ, Christ C, Ehiri JE|title=Prenatal exposure to cannabis and maternal and child health outcomes: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=BMJ Open|volume=6|issue=4|pages=e009986|date=April 2016|pmid=27048634|pmc=4823436|doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2015-009986}}</ref> However, maternal use of marijuana during pregnancy does not appear to be associated with low birth weight or early delivery after controlling for tobacco use and other confounding factors.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors = Conner SN, Bedell V, Lipsey K, Macones GA, Cahill AG, Tuuli MG|title=Maternal Marijuana Use and Adverse Neonatal Outcomes: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis|journal=Obstetrics and Gynecology|volume=128|issue=4|pages=713\u201323|date=October 2016|pmid=27607879|doi=10.1097/AOG.0000000000001649}}</ref> A 2014 review found that while cannabis use may be less harmful than alcohol use, the recommendation to substitute it for [[alcoholism|problematic drinking]] was premature without further study.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Subbaraman MS|title = Can cannabis be considered a substitute medication for alcohol?|journal=Alcohol and Alcoholism|volume=49|issue=3|pages=292\u20138|date=8 January 2014|pmid=24402247|pmc=3992908|doi=10.1093/alcalc/agt182}}</ref> Various surveys conducted between 2015 and 2019 found that many users of cannabis substitute it for prescription drugs (including opioids), alcohol, and tobacco; most of those who used it in place of alcohol or tobacco either reduced or stopped their intake of the latter substances.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/opinion/healthcare/428593-marijuana-access-is-associated-with-decreased-use-of-alcohol-tobacco-and|title=Marijuana access is associated with decreased use of alcohol, tobacco and other prescription drugs|last=Armentano|first=Paul|date=5 February 2019|work=The Hill}}</ref>\n\nA limited number of studies have examined the [[Cannabis-associated respiratory disease|effects of cannabis smoking]] on the respiratory system.<ref name=\"MaistoGalizio2014\">{{cite book | first1 = Stephen | last1 = Maisto | first2 = Mark | last2 = Galizio | first3 = Gerard | last3 = Connors | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drug Use and Abuse|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5F08AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA278|year=2014|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-305-17759-8|page=278}}</ref> Chronic heavy marijuana smoking is associated with coughing, production of sputum, wheezing, and other symptoms of chronic bronchitis.<ref name=\"W. Hall, N. Solowij 1611\u201316\"/> The available evidence does not support a causal relationship between cannabis use and [[chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Owen KP, Sutter ME, Albertson TE | title = Marijuana: respiratory tract effects | journal = Clinical Reviews in Allergy & Immunology | volume = 46 | issue = 1 | pages = 65\u201381 | date = February 2014 | pmid = 23715638 | doi = 10.1007/s12016-013-8374-y }}</ref> Short-term use of cannabis is associated with [[bronchodilation]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Tetrault JM, Crothers K, Moore BA, Mehra R, Concato J, Fiellin DA | title = Effects of marijuana smoking on pulmonary function and respiratory complications: a systematic review | journal = Archives of Internal Medicine | volume = 167 | issue = 3 | pages = 221\u20138 | date = February 2007 | pmid = 17296876 | pmc = 2720277 | doi = 10.1001/archinte.167.3.221 }}</ref> Other side effects of cannabis use include [[cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome]] (CHS).<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Sorensen CJ, DeSanto K, Borgelt L, Phillips KT, Monte AA|title=Cannabinoid Hyperemesis Syndrome: Diagnosis, Pathophysiology, and Treatment-a Systematic Review|journal=Journal of Medical Toxicology|volume=13|issue=1|pages=71\u201387|date=March 2017|pmid=28000146|pmc=5330965|doi=10.1007/s13181-016-0595-z}}</ref>\n\nCannabis smoke contains thousands of organic and inorganic chemical compounds. This [[tar (tobacco residue)|tar]] is chemically similar to that found in tobacco smoke,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hashibe M, Straif K, Tashkin DP, Morgenstern H, Greenland S, Zhang ZF | title = Epidemiologic review of marijuana use and cancer risk | journal = Alcohol | volume = 35 | issue = 3 | pages = 265\u201375 | date = April 2005 | pmid = 16054989 | doi = 10.1016/j.alcohol.2005.04.008 }}</ref> and over fifty known [[carcinogen]]s have been identified in cannabis smoke,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Does smoking cannabis cause cancer? |publisher=Cancer Research UK |date=2010-09-20 |url=http://cancerhelp.cancerresearchuk.org/about-cancer/cancer-questions/does-smoking-cannabis-cause-cancer |access-date=2013-01-09 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729115046/http://cancerhelp.cancerresearchuk.org/about-cancer/cancer-questions/does-smoking-cannabis-cause-cancer |archive-date=2012-07-29 |df= }}</ref> including; nitrosamines, reactive aldehydes, and [[Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon|polycylic hydrocarbons]], including benz[a]pyrene.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tashkin |first=Donald |date=March 1997 |title=Effects of marijuana on the lung and its immune defenses |publisher=UCLA School of Medicine |url=http://www.ukcia.org/research/EffectsOfMarijuanaOnLungAndImmuneDefenses.php |access-date=2012-06-23}}</ref> Cannabis smoke is also inhaled more deeply than tobacco smoke.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gates P, Jaffe A, Copeland J | title = Cannabis smoking and respiratory health: consideration of the literature | journal = Respirology | volume = 19 | issue = 5 | pages = 655\u201362 | date = July 2014 | pmid = 24831571 | doi = 10.1111/resp.12298 }}</ref> {{as of|2015}}, there is no consensus regarding whether cannabis smoking is associated with an increased risk of cancer.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Huang YH, Zhang ZF, Tashkin DP, Feng B, Straif K, Hashibe M | title = An epidemiologic review of marijuana and cancer: an update | journal = Cancer Epidemiology, Biomarkers & Prevention | volume = 24 | issue = 1 | pages = 15\u201331 | date = January 2015 | pmid = 25587109 | pmc = 4302404 | doi = 10.1158/1055-9965.EPI-14-1026 }}</ref> Light and moderate use of cannabis is not believed to increase risk of lung or upper airway cancer. Evidence for causing these cancers is mixed concerning heavy, long-term use. In general there are far lower risks of pulmonary complications for regular cannabis smokers when compared with those of tobacco.<ref name=\"Tashkin2013\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tashkin DP | title = Effects of marijuana smoking on the lung | journal = Annals of the American Thoracic Society | volume = 10 | issue = 3 | pages = 239\u201347 | date = June 2013 | pmid = 23802821 | doi = 10.1513/annalsats.201212-127fr }}</ref> A 2015 review found an association between cannabis use and the development of testicular [[germ cell tumor]]s (TGCTs), particularly non-[[seminoma]] TGCTs.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gurney J, Shaw C, Stanley J, Signal V, Sarfati D | title = Cannabis exposure and risk of testicular cancer: a systematic review and meta-analysis | journal = BMC Cancer | volume = 15 | issue = 1 | pages = 897 | date = November 2015 | pmid = 26560314 | pmc = 4642772 | doi = 10.1186/s12885-015-1905-6 }}</ref> Another 2015 meta-analysis found no association between lifetime cannabis use and risk of head or neck cancer.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = de Carvalho MF, Dourado MR, Fernandes IB, Ara\u00fajo CT, Mesquita AT, Ramos-Jorge ML | title = Head and neck cancer among marijuana users: a meta-analysis of matched case-control studies | journal = Archives of Oral Biology | volume = 60 | issue = 12 | pages = 1750\u20135 | date = December 2015 | pmid = 26433192 | doi = 10.1016/j.archoralbio.2015.09.009 }}</ref> Combustion products are not present when using a [[Vaporizer (inhalation device)|vaporizer]], consuming THC in pill form, or consuming [[cannabis foods]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Loflin M, Earleywine M | title = No smoke, no fire: What the initial literature suggests regarding vapourized cannabis and respiratory risk | journal = Canadian Journal of Respiratory Therapy | volume = 51 | issue = 1 | pages = 7\u20139 | date = 2015 | pmid = 26078621 | pmc = 4456813 | doi =  }}</ref>\n\nThere is concern that cannabis may contribute to cardiovascular disease,<ref name=\"Riecher-R\u00f6ssler2014a\">{{cite book| vauthors = Riecher-R\u00f6ssler A |title=Comorbidity of Mental and Physical Disorders|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_pDgBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA88|year=2014|publisher=Karger Medical and Scientific Publishers|isbn=978-3-318-02604-7|page=88}}</ref> but as of 2018, evidence of this relationship was unclear.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ravi D, Ghasemiesfe M, Korenstein D, Cascino T, Keyhani S | title = Associations Between Marijuana Use and Cardiovascular Risk Factors and Outcomes: A Systematic Review | journal = Annals of Internal Medicine | volume = 168 | issue = 3 | pages = 187\u2013194 | date = February 2018 | pmid = 29357394 | pmc = 6157910 | doi = 10.7326/M17-1548 }}</ref> Research in these events is complicated because cannabis is often used in conjunction with tobacco, and drugs such as alcohol and cocaine.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Thomas G, Kloner RA, Rezkalla S | title = Adverse cardiovascular, cerebrovascular, and peripheral vascular effects of marijuana inhalation: what cardiologists need to know | journal = The American Journal of Cardiology | volume = 113 | issue = 1 | pages = 187\u201390 | date = January 2014 | pmid = 24176069 | doi = 10.1016/j.amjcard.2013.09.042 }}</ref> Smoking cannabis has also been shown to increase the risk of [[myocardial infarction]] by 4.8 times for the 60 minutes after consumption.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Franz CA, Frishman WH | title = Marijuana Use and Cardiovascular Disease | journal = Cardiology in Review | volume = 24 | issue = 4 | pages = 158\u201362 | date = 9 February 2016 | pmid = 26886465 | doi = 10.1097/CRD.0000000000000103 }}</ref>\n\n====Neuroimaging====\nAlthough global abnormalities in [[white matter]] and [[grey matter]] are not associated with cannabis abuse, reduced [[hippocampus|hippocampal]] volume is consistently found. [[Amygdala]]r abnormalities are sometimes reported, although findings are inconsistent.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Rocchetti M, Crescini A, Borgwardt S, Caverzasi E, Politi P, Atakan Z, Fusar-Poli P | title = Is cannabis neurotoxic for the healthy brain? A meta-analytical review of structural brain alterations in non-psychotic users | journal = Psychiatry and Clinical Neurosciences | volume = 67 | issue = 7 | pages = 483\u201392 | date = November 2013 | pmid = 24118193 | doi = 10.1111/pcn.12085 }}</ref><ref name=\"Batalla2013\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Batalla A, Bhattacharyya S, Y\u00fccel M, Fusar-Poli P, Crippa JA, Nogu\u00e9 S, Torrens M, Pujol J, Farr\u00e9 M, Martin-Santos R | title = Structural and functional imaging studies in chronic cannabis users: a systematic review of adolescent and adult findings | journal = PLOS One | volume = 8 | issue = 2 | pages = e55821 | date = 2013 | pmid = 23390554 | pmc = 3563634 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0055821 | quote = The most consistently reported brain alteration was reduced hippocampal volume which was shown to persist even after several months of abstinence in one study and also to be related to the amount of cannabis use Other frequently reported morphological brain alterations related to chronic cannabis use were reported in the amygdala the cerebellum and the frontal cortex...These findings may be interpreted as reflecting neuroadaptation, perhaps indicating the recruitment of additional regions as a compensatory mechanism to maintain normal cognitive performance in response to chronic cannabis exposure, particularly within the prefrontal cortex area. | bibcode = 2013PLoSO...855821B }}</ref><ref name=\"Weinstein2016\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Weinstein A, Livny A, Weizman A | title = Brain Imaging Studies on the Cognitive, Pharmacological and Neurobiological Effects of Cannabis in Humans: Evidence from Studies of Adult Users | journal = Current Pharmaceutical Design | volume = 22 | issue = 42 | pages = 6366\u20136379 | date = 2016 | pmid = 27549374 | doi = 10.2174/1381612822666160822151323 | quote = 1)The studies reviewed so far demonstrated that chronic cannabis use has been associated with a volume reduction of the hippocampus...3)The overall conclusion arising from these studies is that recent cannabis users may experience subtle neurophysiological deficits while performing on working memory tasks, and that they compensate for these deficits by \"working harder\" by using additional brain regions to meet the demands of the task. }}</ref>  Preliminary evidence suggests that this effect is largely mediated by THC, and that CBD may even have a protective effect.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lorenzetti V, Solowij N, Y\u00fccel M | title = The Role of Cannabinoids in Neuroanatomic Alterations in Cannabis Users | journal = Biological Psychiatry | volume = 79 | issue = 7 | pages = e17\u201331 | date = April 2016 | pmid = 26858212 | doi = 10.1016/j.biopsych.2015.11.013 }}</ref>\n\nCannabis use is associated with increased recruitment of task-related areas, such as the [[dorsolateral prefrontal cortex]], which is thought to reflect compensatory activity due to reduced processing efficiency.<ref name=\"Weinstein2016\"/><ref name=\"Batalla2013\"/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Blest-Hopley G, Giampietro V, Bhattacharyya S | title = Residual effects of cannabis use in adolescent and adult brains \u2013 A meta-analysis of fMRI studies | journal = Neuroscience and Biobehavioral Reviews | volume = 88 | pages = 26\u201341 | date = May 2018 | pmid = 29535069 | doi = 10.1016/j.neubiorev.2018.03.008 | quote = This may reflect the multitude of cognitive tasks employed by the various studies included in these meta-analyses, all of which involved performing a task thereby requiring the participant to reorient their attention and attempt to solve the problem at hand and suggest that greater engagement of this region indicates less efficient cognitive performance in cannabis users in general, irrespective of their age.| url = https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/files/88441182/Residual_effects_of_cannabis_BLEST_HOPLEY_Publishedonline10March2018_GREEN_AAM_CC_BY_NC_ND_.pdf }}</ref> Cannabis use is also associated with downregulation of [[Cannabinoid receptor type 1|CB<sub>1</sub>]] receptors.  The magnitude of down regulation is associated with cumulative cannabis exposure, and is reversed after one month of abstinence.<ref name=\"Curran2016\"/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Parsons LH, Hurd YL | title = Endocannabinoid signalling in reward and addiction | journal = Nature Reviews. Neuroscience | volume = 16 | issue = 10 | pages = 579\u201394 | date = October 2015 | pmid = 26373473 | pmc = 4652927 | doi = 10.1038/nrn4004 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Zehra A, Burns J, Liu CK, Manza P, Wiers CE, Volkow ND, Wang GJ | title = Cannabis Addiction and the Brain: a Review | journal = Journal of Neuroimmune Pharmacology | volume = 13 | issue = 4 | pages = 438\u2013452 | date = March 2018 | pmid = 29556883 | pmc = 6223748 | doi = 10.1007/s11481-018-9782-9 }}</ref> There is limited evidence that chronic cannabis use can reduce levels of [[glutamate]] metabolites in the human brain.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Colizzi M, McGuire P, Pertwee RG, Bhattacharyya S | title = Effect of cannabis on glutamate signalling in the brain: A systematic review of human and animal evidence | journal = Neuroscience and Biobehavioral Reviews | volume = 64 | pages = 359\u201381 | date = May 2016 | pmid = 26987641 | doi = 10.1016/j.neubiorev.2016.03.010 | url = https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/effect-of-cannabis-on-glutamate-signalling-in-the-brain-a-systematic-review-of-human-and-animal-evidence(9b3d72d2-d3ae-44a6-b9a5-4c13e9690b9d).html }}</ref>\n\n====Cognition====\nA 2015 meta analysis found that, although a longer period of abstinence was associated with smaller magnitudes of impairment, both retrospective and prospective memory were impaired in cannabis users.  The authors concluded that some, but not all, of the deficits associated with cannabis use were reversible.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Schoeler T, Kambeitz J, Behlke I, Murray R, Bhattacharyya S | title = The effects of cannabis on memory function in users with and without psychotic disorder: findings from a combined meta-analysis | journal = Psychological Medicine | volume = 46 | issue = 1 | pages = 177\u201388 | date = January 2016 | pmid = 26353818 | doi = 10.1017/S0033291715001646 | url = https://epub.ub.uni-muenchen.de/43978/ }}</ref>  A 2012 meta analysis found that deficits in most domains of cognition persisted beyond the acute period of intoxication, but was not evident in studies where subjects were abstinent for more than 25 days.<ref name=\"Schreiner 2012\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Schreiner AM, Dunn ME | title = Residual effects of cannabis use on neurocognitive performance after prolonged abstinence: a meta-analysis | journal = Experimental and Clinical Psychopharmacology | volume = 20 | issue = 5 | pages = 420\u2013429 | date = October 2012 | pmid = 22731735 | doi = 10.1037/a0029117 | quote = Therefore, results indicate evidence for small neurocognitive effects that persist after the period of acute intoxication...As hypothesized, the meta-analysis conducted on studies eval- uating users after at least 25 days of abstention found no residual effects on cognitive performance...These results fail to support the idea that heavy cannabis use may result in long-term, persistent effects on neuropsychological functioning. }}</ref>  Few high quality studies have been performed on the long-term effects of cannabis on cognition, and the results were generally inconsistent.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gonzalez R, Carey C, Grant I | title = Nonacute (residual) neuropsychological effects of cannabis use: a qualitative analysis and systematic review | journal = Journal of Clinical Pharmacology | volume = 42 | issue = S1 | pages = 48S\u201357S | date = November 2002 | pmid = 12412836 | doi = 10.1002/j.1552-4604.2002.tb06003.x }}</ref>  Furthermore, [[effect size]]s of significant findings were generally small.<ref name=\"Schreiner 2012\"/>  One review concluded that, although most cognitive faculties were unimpaired by cannabis use, residual deficits occurred in [[executive function]]s.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Crean RD, Crane NA, Mason BJ | title = An evidence based review of acute and long-term effects of cannabis use on executive cognitive functions | journal = Journal of Addiction Medicine | volume = 5 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u20138 | date = March 2011 | pmid = 21321675 | pmc = 3037578 | doi = 10.1097/ADM.0b013e31820c23fa | quote = Cannabis appears to continue to exert impairing effects in executive functions even after 3 weeks of abstinence and beyond. While basic attentional and working memory abilities are largely restored, the most enduring and detectable deficits are seen in decision-making, concept formation and planning. }}</ref>  Impairments in executive functioning are most consistently found in older populations, which may reflect heavier cannabis exposure, or developmental effects associated with adolescent cannabis use.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Broyd SJ, van Hell HH, Beale C, Y\u00fccel M, Solowij N | title = Acute and Chronic Effects of Cannabinoids on Human Cognition-A Systematic Review | journal = Biological Psychiatry | volume = 79 | issue = 7 | pages = 557\u201367 | date = April 2016 | pmid = 26858214 | doi = 10.1016/j.biopsych.2015.12.002 | url = http://ro.uow.edu.au/sspapers/2164 }}</ref> One review found three prospective cohort studies that examined the relationship between self reported cannabis use and [[intelligence quotient|intelligence quotient (IQ)]].  The study following the largest number of heavy cannabis users reported that IQ declined between ages 7\u201313 and age 38. Poorer school performance and increased incidence of leaving school early were both associated with cannabis use, although a causal relationship was not established.<ref name=\"Curran2016\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Curran HV, Freeman TP, Mokrysz C, Lewis DA, Morgan CJ, Parsons LH | title = Keep off the grass? Cannabis, cognition and addiction | journal = Nature Reviews. Neuroscience | volume = 17 | issue = 5 | pages = 293\u2013306 | date = May 2016 | pmid = 27052382 | doi = 10.1038/nrn.2016.28 | url = http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1489385/1/Curran%2520et%2520al%2520NRN-2016%2520pdf.pdf }}</ref> Cannabis users demonstrated increased activity in task-related brain regions, consistent with reduced processing efficiency.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ganzer F, Br\u00f6ning S, Kraft S, Sack PM, Thomasius R | title = Weighing the Evidence: A Systematic Review on Long-Term Neurocognitive Effects of Cannabis Use in Abstinent Adolescents and Adults | journal = Neuropsychology Review | volume = 26 | issue = 2 | pages = 186\u2013222 | date = June 2016 | pmid = 27125202 | doi = 10.1007/s11065-016-9316-2 }}</ref>\n\n===Psychiatric===\n{{See also|Cannabis and psychosis}}\nAt an epidemiological level, a [[dose\u2013response relationship]] exists between cannabis use and increased risk of [[psychosis]]<ref name=Leweke2016rev/><ref name=\"Marconi2016\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Marconi A, Di Forti M, Lewis CM, Murray RM, Vassos E | title = Meta-analysis of the Association Between the Level of Cannabis Use and Risk of Psychosis | journal = Schizophrenia Bulletin | volume = 42 | issue = 5 | pages = 1262\u20139 | date = September 2016 | pmid = 26884547 | pmc = 4988731 | doi = 10.1093/schbul/sbw003 }}</ref><ref name=\"Moore 2007\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Moore TH, Zammit S, Lingford-Hughes A, Barnes TR, Jones PB, Burke M, Lewis G | title = Cannabis use and risk of psychotic or affective mental health outcomes: a systematic review | journal = Lancet | volume = 370 | issue = 9584 | pages = 319\u201328 | date = July 2007 | pmid = 17662880 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(07)61162-3 | url = http://orca.cf.ac.uk/619/1/Appendix%201%20%28search%20strategy%29%20Cannabis%20use%20and%20risk%20of%20developing%20psychotic%20or%20affective%20mental%20health%20outcomes%20a%20systematic%20review.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Semple DM, McIntosh AM, Lawrie SM | title = Cannabis as a risk factor for psychosis: systematic review | journal = Journal of Psychopharmacology | volume = 19 | issue = 2 | pages = 187\u201394 | date = March 2005 | pmid = 15871146 | doi = 10.1177/0269881105049040 }}</ref> and earlier onset of psychosis.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Large M, Sharma S, Compton MT, Slade T, Nielssen O | title = Cannabis use and earlier onset of psychosis: a systematic meta-analysis | journal = Archives of General Psychiatry | volume = 68 | issue = 6 | pages = 555\u201361 | date = June 2011 | pmid = 21300939 | doi = 10.1001/archgenpsychiatry.2011.5 }}</ref> Although the epidemiological association is robust, evidence to prove a causal relationship is lacking.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = McLaren JA, Silins E, Hutchinson D, Mattick RP, Hall W | title = Assessing evidence for a causal link between cannabis and psychosis: a review of cohort studies | journal = The International Journal on Drug Policy | volume = 21 | issue = 1 | pages = 10\u20139 | date = January 2010 | pmid = 19783132 | doi = 10.1016/j.drugpo.2009.09.001 | quote = The contentious issue of whether cannabis use can cause serious psychotic disorders that would not otherwise have occurred cannot be answered based on the existing data }}</ref>  But a biological causal pathway is plausible, especially if there is a genetic predisposition to mental illness, in which case cannabis may be a trigger.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/17/health/cannabis-marijuana-schizophrenia|title=Does Marijuana Use Cause Schizophrenia?|last=Carey|first=Benedict|date=2019-01-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-01-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\nIt is not clear whether cannabis use affects the rate of suicide.<ref name=\"Calabria2010\"/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Borges G, Bagge CL, Orozco R | title = A literature review and meta-analyses of cannabis use and suicidality | journal = Journal of Affective Disorders | volume = 195 | pages = 63\u201374 | date = May 2016 | pmid = 26872332 | doi = 10.1016/j.jad.2016.02.007 }}</ref> Cannabis may also increase the risk of depression, but insufficient research has been performed to draw a conclusion.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lev-Ran S, Roerecke M, Le Foll B, George TP, McKenzie K, Rehm J | title = The association between cannabis use and depression: a systematic review and meta-analysis of longitudinal studies | journal = Psychological Medicine | volume = 44 | issue = 4 | pages = 797\u2013810 | date = March 2014 | pmid = 23795762 | doi = 10.1017/S0033291713001438 }}</ref><ref name=\"Moore 2007\"/>  Cannabis use is associated with increased risk of anxiety disorders, although causality has not been established.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kedzior KK, Laeber LT | title = A positive association between anxiety disorders and cannabis use or cannabis use disorders in the general population\u2014a meta-analysis of 31 studies | journal = BMC Psychiatry | volume = 14 | pages = 136 | date = May 2014 | pmid = 24884989 | pmc = 4032500 | doi = 10.1186/1471-244X-14-136 }}</ref>\n\nA February 2019 review found that cannabis use during adolescence was associated with an increased risk of developing depression and suicidal behavior later in life, while finding no effect on anxiety.<ref name=\"Gobbi\">{{cite journal | last=Gobbi | first=Gabriella | last2=Atkin | first2=Tobias | last3=Zytynski | first3=Tomasz | last4=Wang | first4=Shouao | last5=Askari | first5=Sorayya | last6=Boruff | first6=Jill | last7=Ware | first7=Mark | last8=Marmorstein | first8=Naomi | last9=Cipriani | first9=Andrea | last10=Dendukuri | first10=Nandini | last11=Mayo | first11=Nancy | title=Cannabis Use in Adolescence and Risk of Depression, Anxiety, and Suicidality in Young Adulthood | journal=JAMA Psychiatry | volume=76 | issue=4 | pages=426\u2013434 | date=13 February 2019 | doi=10.1001/jamapsychiatry.2018.4500 | pmid=30758486 | pmc=6450286 }}</ref>\n\n===Reinforcement disorders===\n{{Main|Cannabis dependence}}\nAbout 9% of those who experiment with marijuana eventually become dependent according to [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders|DSM-IV (1994)]] criteria.<ref name=\"NEJM2014\"/>  A 2013 review estimates daily use is associated with a 10\u201320% rate of dependence.<ref name=\"Borgelt2013\"/> The highest risk of cannabis dependence is found in those with a history of poor academic achievement, deviant behavior in childhood and adolescence, rebelliousness, poor parental relationships, or a parental history of drug and alcohol problems.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hall W, Degenhardt L | title = Adverse health effects of non-medical cannabis use | journal = Lancet | volume = 374 | issue = 9698 | pages = 1383\u201391 | date = October 2009 | pmid = 19837255 | doi = 10.1016/s0140-6736(09)61037-0 }}</ref>  Of daily users, about 50% experience withdrawal upon cessation of use (i.e. are dependent), characterized by sleep problems, irritability, dysphoria, and craving.<ref name=\"Curran2016\"/>  Cannabis withdrawal is less severe than withdrawal from alcohol.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Subbaraman MS | title = Can cannabis be considered a substitute medication for alcohol? | journal = Alcohol and Alcoholism | volume = 49 | issue = 3 | pages = 292\u20138 | date = 2014 | pmid = 24402247 | pmc = 3992908 | doi = 10.1093/alcalc/agt182 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[DSM-V]] criteria, 9% of those who are exposed to cannabis develop cannabis use disorder, compared to 20% for [[cocaine]], 23% for [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]] and 68% for [[nicotine]].  Cannabis abuse disorder in the DSM-V involves a combination of DSM-IV criteria for cannabis abuse and dependence, plus the addition of craving, minus the criterion related to legal troubles.<ref name=\"Curran2016\"/>\n\n==Overdose==\nTHC, the principal [[psychoactive constituent]] of the cannabis plant, has low [[toxicity]]. The dose of THC needed to kill 50% of tested rodents is extremely high. Cannabis has not been reported to cause fatal [[overdose]] in humans.<ref name=\"Calabria2010\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Calabria B, Degenhardt L, Hall W, Lynskey M | title = Does cannabis use increase the risk of death? Systematic review of epidemiological evidence on adverse effects of cannabis use | journal = Drug and Alcohol Review | volume = 29 | issue = 3 | pages = 318\u201330 | date = May 2010 | pmid = 20565525 | doi = 10.1111/j.1465-3362.2009.00149.x }}</ref>\n\n==Pharmacology==\n\n===Mechanism of action===\n{{see also|Effects of cannabis#Biochemical mechanisms in the brain}}\nThe high [[lipophilicity|lipid-solubility]] of cannabinoids results in their persisting in the body for long periods of time.<ref name=\"HallPacula2003hj\">{{cite book| first1 = Wayne | last1 = Hall | first2 = Rosalie Liccardo | last2 = Pacula | name-list-format = vanc|title=Cannabis Use and Dependence: Public Health and Public Policy|url=https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence| url-access = registration |year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-80024-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence/page/n12 15]}}</ref> Even after a single administration of THC, detectable levels of THC can be found in the body for weeks or longer (depending on the amount administered and the sensitivity of the assessment method).<ref name=\"HallPacula2003hj\" /> A number of investigators have suggested that this is an important factor in marijuana's effects, perhaps because cannabinoids may accumulate in the body, particularly in the lipid membranes of neurons.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.lycaeum.org/drugwar/marij1.html | first = Leo E. | last = Hollister  | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 1986 |title=Health aspects of cannabis |journal=Pharma Review |issue=38 |pages=1\u201320 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130415094338/http://www.lycaeum.org/drugwar/marij1.html |archive-date=2013-04-15 |access-date=2011-02-17 |display-authors=etal |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nNot until the end of the 20th century was the specific mechanism of action of THC at the neuronal level studied.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}} Researchers have subsequently confirmed that THC exerts its most prominent effects via its actions on two types of [[cannabinoid receptors]], the [[CB1 receptor|CB<sub>1</sub> receptor]] and the [[CB2 receptor|CB<sub>2</sub> receptor]], both of which are [[G protein-coupled receptor]]s.<ref name=\"IovannaIsmailov2009\">{{cite book | first1 = Juan | last1 = Iovanna | first2 = Uktam | last2 = Ismailov | name-list-format = vanc |title=Pancreatology: From Bench to Bedside|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3B5dp9BXaKwC&pg=PA40|year=2009|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-642-00152-9|page=40}}</ref> The CB<sub>1</sub> receptor is found primarily in the brain as well as in some peripheral tissues, and the CB<sub>2</sub> receptor is found primarily in peripheral tissues, but is also expressed in [[neuroglia|neuroglial cells]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wilson RI, Nicoll RA | title = Endocannabinoid signaling in the brain | journal = Science | volume = 296 | issue = 5568 | pages = 678\u201382 | date = April 2002 | pmid = 11976437 | doi = 10.1126/science.1063545 | bibcode = 2002Sci...296..678W }}</ref> THC appears to alter mood and cognition through its agonist actions on the CB<sub>1</sub> receptors, which inhibit a [[secondary messenger system]] ([[adenylate cyclase]]) in a dose-dependent manner. These actions can be blocked by the selective CB<sub>1</sub> receptor [[receptor antagonist|antagonist]] [[rimonabant]] (SR141716), which has been shown in clinical trials to be an effective treatment for [[smoking cessation]], [[weight loss]], and as a means of controlling or reducing [[metabolic syndrome]] risk factors.<ref name=\"pmid15134285\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fernandez JR, Allison DB | title = Rimonabant Sanofi-Synth\u00e9labo | journal = Current Opinion in Investigational Drugs | volume = 5 | issue = 4 | pages = 430\u20135 | date = April 2004 | pmid = 15134285 | doi = | url = }}</ref> However, due to the [[dysphoria|dysphoric]] effect of CB<sub>1</sub> receptor antagonists, this drug is often discontinued due to these side effects.<ref name=\"RahmanReitz2005\">{{cite book| first1 = Atta | last1 = Ur-Rahman | first2 = Allen B. | last2 = Reitz | name-list-format = vanc |title=Frontiers in Medicinal Chemistry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tCyDoIHToBQC&pg=PA150|year=2005|publisher=Bentham Science Publishers|isbn=978-1-60805-205-9|page=150}}</ref>\n\nVia CB<sub>1</sub> receptor activation, THC indirectly increases [[dopamine]] release and produces [[psychotropic]] effects.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Oleson EB, Cheer JF | title = A brain on cannabinoids: the role of dopamine release in reward seeking | journal = Cold Spring Harbor Perspectives in Medicine | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = a012229 | date = August 2012 | pmid = 22908200 | pmc = 3405830 | doi = 10.1101/cshperspect.a012229 }}</ref> [[Cannabidiol]] (CBD) also acts as an [[allosteric modulator]] of the [[\u03bc-opioid receptor|\u03bc-]] and [[\u03b4-opioid receptor]]s.<ref name=\"pmid16489449\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kathmann M, Flau K, Redmer A, Tr\u00e4nkle C, Schlicker E | title = Cannabidiol is an allosteric modulator at mu- and delta-opioid receptors | journal = Naunyn-Schmiedeberg's Archives of Pharmacology | volume = 372 | issue = 5 | pages = 354\u201361 | date = February 2006 | pmid = 16489449 | doi = 10.1007/s00210-006-0033-x }}</ref> THC also potentiates the effects of the [[glycine receptor]]s.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hejazi N, Zhou C, Oz M, Sun H, Ye JH, Zhang L | title = Delta9-tetrahydrocannabinol and endogenous cannabinoid anandamide directly potentiate the function of glycine receptors | journal = Molecular Pharmacology | volume = 69 | issue = 3 | pages = 991\u20137 | date = March 2006 | pmid = 16332990 | doi = 10.1124/mol.105.019174 }}</ref> It is unknown if or how these actions contribute to the effects of cannabis.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Xiong W, Cheng K, Cui T, Godlewski G, Rice KC, Xu Y, Zhang L | title = Cannabinoid potentiation of glycine receptors contributes to cannabis-induced analgesia | journal = Nature Chemical Biology | volume = 7 | issue = 5 | pages = 296\u2013303 | date = May 2011 | pmid = 21460829 | pmc = 3388539 | doi = 10.1038/nchembio.552 }}</ref>\n\n==Chemistry==\n===Detection in body fluids===\n{{Main|Cannabis drug testing}}\n\nTHC and its major (inactive) metabolite, THC-COOH, can be measured in blood, urine, hair, oral fluid or sweat using [[chromatographic]] techniques as part of a drug use testing program or a forensic investigation of a traffic or other criminal offense.<ref name=\"Barceloux2012\">{{cite book| first= Donald G. | last = Barceloux | name-list-format = vanc |title=Medical Toxicology of Drug Abuse: Synthesized Chemicals and Psychoactive Plants | chapter = Chapter 60: Marijuana (Cannabis sativa L.) and synthetic cannabinoids |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9JLiJcjdqkcC&pg=PA910|access-date=14 July 2013|date=3 February 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-10605-1|pages=910\u2013}}</ref> The concentrations obtained from such analyses can often be helpful in distinguishing active use from passive exposure, elapsed time since use, and extent or duration of use. These tests cannot, however, distinguish authorized cannabis smoking for medical purposes from unauthorized recreational smoking.<ref name=\"Baselt2008\">{{cite book | first = Randall Clint | last = Baselt  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Disposition of Toxic Drugs and Chemicals in Man |year=2008 |publisher=Biomedical Publications |isbn=978-0-9626523-7-0 |pages=1513\u20131518}}</ref> Commercial cannabinoid [[immunoassay]]s, often employed as the initial screening method when testing physiological specimens for marijuana presence, have different degrees of cross-reactivity with THC and its metabolites.<ref name=\"ShawKwong2001\">{{cite book | first1 = Leslie M. | last1 = Shaw | first2 = Tai C. | last2 = Kwong | name-list-format = vanc |title=The Clinical Toxicology Laboratory: Contemporary Practice of Poisoning Evaluation | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=pXvFGqz44pYC&pg=PA51 |year=2001 |publisher=Amer. Assoc. for Clinical Chemistry |isbn=978-1-890883-53-9 |page=51}}</ref> Urine contains predominantly THC-COOH, while hair, oral fluid and sweat contain primarily THC.<ref name=\"Barceloux2012\" /> Blood may contain both substances, with the relative amounts dependent on the recency and extent of usage.<ref name=\"Barceloux2012\" />\n\nThe [[Duquenois\u2013Levine test]] is commonly used as a [[Presumptive and confirmatory tests|screening test]] in the field, but it cannot definitively confirm the presence of cannabis, as a large range of substances have been shown to give false positives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266888426|title=The Non-Specificity of the Duquenois-Levine Field Test for Marijuana|website=ResearchGate}}</ref> Researchers at John Jay College of Criminal Justice reported that dietary zinc supplements can mask the presence of THC and other drugs in urine.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Venkatratnam A, Lents NH | title = Zinc reduces the detection of cocaine, methamphetamine, and THC by ELISA urine testing | journal = Journal of Analytical Toxicology | volume = 35 | issue = 6 | pages = 333\u201340 | date = July 2011 | pmid = 21740689 | doi = 10.1093/anatox/35.6.333 }}</ref> However, a 2013 study conducted by researchers at the University of Utah School of Medicine refute the possibility of self-administered zinc producing false-negative urine drug tests.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lin CN, Strathmann FG | title = Elevated urine zinc concentration reduces the detection of methamphetamine, cocaine, THC and opiates in urine by EMIT | journal = Journal of Analytical Toxicology | volume = 37 | issue = 9 | pages = 665\u20139 | date = July 10, 2013 | pmid = 23843421 | doi = 10.1093/jat/bkt056 | url = http://jat.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2013/07/09/jat.bkt056.full.pdf }}</ref>\n\n==Varieties and strains==\n[[File:Cannab2 new.png|thumb|right|Types of cannabis]]\n\nCBD is a [[5-HT1A receptor|5-HT<sub>1A</sub> receptor]] agonist, which may also contribute to an [[anxiolytic]] effect.<ref name=\"joy\">{{Cite book |title=Marijuana and Medicine: Assessing The Science Base |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences Press]] |year=1999 |url=https://www.nap.edu/catalog/6376/marijuana-and-medicine-assessing-the-science-base |isbn=978-0-585-05800-9 | vauthors = Joy JE, Watson SJ, Benson JA |doi=10.17226/6376 |pmid=25101425 }}</ref> This likely means the high concentrations of CBD found in ''[[Cannabis indica]]'' mitigate the [[anxiogenic]] effect of THC significantly.<ref name=\"joy\" /> It is often claimed that sativa strains provide a more stimulating psychoactive high while indica strains are more sedating with a body high.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://herb.co/marijuana/news/indica-vs-sativa-whats-the-difference|title=The Ultimate Guide on Indicas vs. Sativas|last=Elliott|first=Steve | name-list-format = vanc |website=Herb|access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref> However this is disputed by researchers.<ref name=\"pmid28861479\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Piomelli D, Russo EB | title = The Cannabis sativa Versus Cannabis indica Debate: An Interview with Ethan Russo, MD | journal = Cannabis and Cannabinoid Research | volume = 1 | issue = 1 | pages = 44\u201346 | date = 2016 | pmid = 28861479 | pmc = 5576603 | doi = 10.1089/can.2015.29003.ebr }}</ref>\n\n===Psychoactive ingredients===\nAccording to the [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] (UNODC), \"the amount of THC present in a cannabis sample is generally used as a measure of cannabis potency.\"<ref name=\"Why Does Cannabis Potency Matter?\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/frontpage/2009/June/why-does-cannabis-potency-matter.html |title=Why Does Cannabis Potency Matter? |date=2009-06-29 |publisher=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime}}</ref> The three main forms of cannabis products are the flower/fruit, resin (hashish), and oil (hash oil). The UNODC states that cannabis often contains 5% THC content, resin \"can contain up to 20% THC content\", and that \"Cannabis oil may contain more than 60% THC content.\"<ref name=\"Why Does Cannabis Potency Matter?\" />\n\nA 2012 review found that the THC content in marijuana had increased worldwide from 1970 to 2009.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cascini F, Aiello C, Di Tanna G | title = Increasing delta-9-tetrahydrocannabinol (\u0394-9-THC) content in herbal cannabis over time: systematic review and meta-analysis | journal = Current Drug Abuse Reviews | volume = 5 | issue = 1 | pages = 32\u201340 | date = March 2012 | pmid = 22150622 | doi = 10.2174/1874473711205010032 }}</ref> It is unclear, however, whether the increase in THC content has caused people to consume more THC or if users adjust based on the potency of the cannabis. It is likely that the higher THC content allows people to ingest less tar. At the same time, CBD levels in seized samples have lowered, in part because of the desire to produce higher THC levels and because more illegal growers cultivate indoors using artificial lights. This helps avoid detection but reduces the CBD production of the plant.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2014/jan/17/cannabis-memory-loss-cbd|title=Cannabis and memory loss: dude, where's my CBD?| first = Dana | last = Smith  | name-list-format = vanc |newspaper=the Guardian|date=2014-01-17}}</ref>\n\nAustralia's [[National Cannabis Prevention and Information Centre]] (NCPIC) states that the buds ([[infructescence]]s) of the female cannabis plant contain the highest concentration of THC, followed by the leaves. The stalks and seeds have \"much lower THC levels\".<ref name=\"urlCannabis Potency\">{{Cite web |url=http://ncpic.org.au/ncpic/publications/factsheets/article/cannabis-potency |title=Cannabis Potency |publisher=National Cannabis Prevention and Information Centre |access-date=2011-12-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111206100249/http://ncpic.org.au/ncpic/publications/factsheets/article/cannabis-potency |archive-date=2011-12-06 |df= }}</ref> The UN states that the leaves can contain ten times less THC than the buds, and the stalks one hundred times less THC.<ref name=\"Why Does Cannabis Potency Matter?\" />\n\nAfter revisions to [[Cannabis reclassification in the United Kingdom|cannabis scheduling]] in the UK, the government moved cannabis back from a [[class C drug|class C]] to a [[class B drug]]. A purported reason was the appearance of high potency cannabis. They believe [[Skunk (cannabis strain)|skunk]] accounts for between 70 and 80% of samples seized by police<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7386889.stm |title=BBC: Cannabis laws to be strengthened. May 2008 20:55 UK |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-05-07 |access-date=2010-09-20}}</ref> (despite the fact that skunk can sometimes be incorrectly mistaken for all types of herbal cannabis).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Di Forti M, Morgan C, Dazzan P, Pariante C, Mondelli V, Marques TR, Handley R, Luzi S, Russo M, Paparelli A, Butt A, Stilo SA, Wiffen B, Powell J, Murray RM | title = High-potency cannabis and the risk of psychosis | journal = The British Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 195 | issue = 6 | pages = 488\u201391 | date = December 2009 | pmid = 19949195 | pmc = 2801827 | doi = 10.1192/bjp.bp.109.064220 | displayauthors = 8 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1577798/Use-of-extra-strong-skunk-cannabis-soars.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Christopher |last=Hope |title=Use of extra strong 'skunk' cannabis soars |date=2008-02-06}}</ref> Extracts such as [[hashish]] and [[hash oil]] typically contain more THC than high potency cannabis infructescences.<ref name=\"Doweiko2011\">{{cite book| first = Harold | last = Doweiko  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Concepts of Chemical Dependency|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RWMIAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA124|year=2011|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-133-17081-5|page=124}}</ref>\n\n==Preparations==\n<gallery>\nFile:Marijuana-Cannabis-Weed-Bud-Gram.jpg|Dried flower buds (marijuana)\nFile:Kief (yellow).jpg|A gram of [[kief]]\nFile:Hashish-2.jpg|Hashish\nFile:Drop of cannabis oil.jpg|Hash oil\nFile:Cannabis Butter.JPG|Infusion (dairy butter)\nFile:Resin.jpg|Pipe residue\n</gallery>\n\n===Marijuana===\n{{further|Marijuana (word)}}\nMarijuana or marihuana (herbal cannabis)<ref name=\"Dictionaries2007m\"/> consists of the dried flowers and fruits and subtending leaves and stems of the female ''Cannabis'' plant.<ref name=\"PotterBouchard2013\">{{cite book| first1 = Gary | last1 = Potter | first2 = Martin | last2 = Bouchard | first3 = Tom | last3 = Decorte | name-list-format = vanc |title=World Wide Weed: Global Trends in Cannabis Cultivation and its Control|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ENOhAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA17 |edition=revised |year=2013 |publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-1-4094-9438-6|page=17}}</ref><ref name=\"HallPacula2003\">{{cite book | first1 = Wayne | last1 = Hall | first2 = Rosalie Liccardo | last2 = Pacula | name-list-format = vanc |title=Cannabis Use and Dependence: Public Health and Public Policy|url=https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence| url-access = registration |year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-80024-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/CannabisUseAndDependence/page/n10 13]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|title=Recommended Methods for the Identification and Analysis of Cannabis and Cannabis Products|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MLR3bFaUZj0C&pg=PA15|year=2009|publisher=United Nations Publications|isbn=978-92-1-148242-3|page=15}}</ref><ref name=\"Houck2015\">{{cite book|first = Max M. | last = Houck  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Forensic Chemistry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=POpDBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA131|date= 2015|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-0-12-800624-5|page=131}}</ref> This is the most widely consumed form,<ref name=\"Houck2015\"/> containing 3% to 20% THC,<ref name=\"AdlerAdler2012\">{{cite book| first1 = Patricia A. | last1 = Adler | first2 = Peter | last2 = Adler | first3 = Patrick K. | last3 =  O'Brien | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drugs and the American Dream: An Anthology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_s_9tfNlfGkC&pg=PA330|date=February 28, 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=978-0-470-67027-9|pages=330\u2013}}</ref> with reports of up to 33% THC.<ref name=\"MosherAkins2013\">{{cite book| first1 = Clayton J. | last1 = Mosher | first2 = Scott M. | last2 = Akins | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drugs and Drug Policy: The Control of Consciousness Alteration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2UQXBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA17|date=August 20, 2013|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-4833-2188-2|page=17}}</ref> This is the stock material from which all other preparations are derived. Although herbal cannabis and [[Hemp|industrial hemp]] derive from the same species and contain the psychoactive component (THC), they are distinct strains with unique biochemical compositions and uses. Hemp has lower concentrations of THC and higher concentrations of CBD, which gives lesser psychoactive effects.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naihc.org/hemp_information/hemp_facts.html |title=Hemp Facts |publisher=Naihc.org |access-date=2013-01-09}}</ref><ref name=\"Earleywine2002\">{{cite book |last=Earleywine |first=Mitch |title=Understanding Marijuana: A New Look at the Scientific Evidence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QUn92XLQqf8C&pg=PA3|date= 2002|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-988143-7|page=3}}</ref>\n\n===Kief===\n{{Main|Kief}}\n[[Kief]] is a powder, rich in [[trichome]]s,<ref name=\"Rosenthal2002\">{{cite book| first = Ed | last = Rosenthal  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Ask Ed : Marijuana Gold: Trash to Stash|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H_QDJ7CWf2sC&pg=PA116|year=2002|publisher=QUICK AMER Publishing Company|isbn=978-0-932551-52-8|page=116}}</ref> which can be sifted from the leaves, flowers and fruits of [[Cannabis sativa|cannabis plants]] and either [[One hitter (smoking)|consumed in powder form]] or compressed to produce cakes of [[hashish]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cannabisculture.com/articles/4220.html |title=Kief |publisher=Cannabisculture.com |date=2005-03-09 |access-date=2010-01-02 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605025019/http://www.cannabisculture.com/articles/4220.html |archive-date=2009-06-05 |df= }}</ref> The word \"kif\" derives from [[colloquial Arabic]] {{lang|ar|\u0643\u064a\u0641}} ''{{transl|ar|2=k\u0113f<span style=\"margin:1.5px\">/</span>k\u012bf}}'', meaning ''pleasure''.<ref name=\"Bukszpan2012\">{{cite book| first = David | last = Bukszpan  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Is That a Word?: From AA to ZZZ, the Weird and Wonderful Language of SCRABBLE|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eA8vlPcMXTUC&pg=PA94|year=2012|publisher=Chronicle Books|isbn=978-1-4521-0824-7|page=94}}</ref>\n\n===Hashish===\n{{Main|Hashish}}\n\nHashish (also spelled hasheesh, hashisha, or simply hash) is a concentrated [[resin]] cake or ball produced from pressed kief, the detached trichomes and fine material that falls off cannabis fruits, flowers and leaves.<ref name=\"urlHashish - Definitions from Dictionary.com\">{{cite web |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/Hashish |title=Hashish |publisher=dictionary.reference.com}}</ref> or from scraping the resin from the surface of the plants and rolling it into balls. It varies in color from black to golden brown depending upon purity and variety of cultivar it was obtained from.<ref name=\"Castle1\">{{cite book |author=Castle/Murray/D'Souza |title=Marijuana and Madness |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0QqyOSJEeykC&pg=PA35 |year=2004 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1-139-50267-2 |page=35}}</ref> It can be consumed orally or smoked, and is also vaporized, or 'vaped'.<ref name=\"Goldberg2012q\">{{cite book | first = Raymond | last = Goldberg  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drugs Across the Spectrum | edition = 7th |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U9TjZHWVGoIC&pg=PA255 |year=2012 |publisher=Cengage Learning |isbn=978-1-133-59416-1 |page=255}}</ref> The term \"rosin hash\" refers to a high quality solventless product obtained through heat and pressure.<ref>Alchimia Blog, ''[http://www.alchimiaweb.com/blogen/rosin-hash/ Rosin Hash]''</ref>\n\n===Tincture===\n{{main|Tincture of cannabis}}\n\nCannabinoids can be [[Extraction (chemistry)|extracted]] from cannabis plant matter using high-[[alcoholic proof|proof]] [[herbalism#Routes of administration|spirits]] (often [[rectified spirit|grain alcohol]]) to create a [[tincture]], often referred to as \"green dragon\".<ref name=\"Iversen2000s\">{{cite book |first = Leslie L. | last = Iversen  | name-list-format = vanc |title=The Science of Marijuana |url=https://archive.org/details/scienceofmarijua00iver |url-access = registration |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-515110-7 |page=[https://archive.org/details/scienceofmarijua00iver/page/17 17]}}</ref> [[Nabiximols]] is a branded product name from a tincture manufacturing pharmaceutical company.<ref name=\"CohenRudick2011\">{{cite book | first1 = Jeffrey A. | last1 = Cohen | first2 = Richard A. | last2 = Rudick | name-list-format = vanc |title=Multiple Sclerosis Therapeutics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LxQkUu2tfXcC&pg=PA670 |year=2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1-139-50237-5 |page=670}}</ref>\n\n===Hash oil===\n{{Main|Hash oil}}\n\nHash oil is a [[resin]]ous matrix of [[cannabinoid]]s obtained from the ''Cannabis'' plant by [[solvent extraction]],<ref name=\"King2009c\">{{cite book|first = Leslie A. | last = King  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Forensic Chemistry of Substance Misuse: A Guide to Drug Control|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x9Z1QZ5NIEIC&pg=PA78|year=2009|publisher=Royal Society of Chemistry|isbn=978-0-85404-178-7|page=78}}</ref> formed into a hardened or viscous mass.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/101445332 |title=Dabs\u2014marijuana's explosive secret |publisher=Cnbc.com |date=2014-02-24 |access-date=2014-02-28}}</ref> Hash oil can be the most potent of the main cannabis products because of its high level of psychoactive compound per its volume, which can vary depending on the plant's mix of essential oils and psychoactive compounds.<ref name=\"WD2009_98\">{{cite book |year=2009 |title=World Drug Report|publisher=United Nations Publications |page=[https://archive.org/details/worlddrugreport20000unse/page/98 98] |url=https://archive.org/details/worlddrugreport20000unse|url-access=registration |isbn=9789211482409}}</ref> [[Butane]] and [[Supercritical fluid|supercritical]] [[carbon dioxide]] hash oil have become popular in recent years.<ref>Alison Hallett for Wired. Feb. 20, 2013 [https://www.wired.com/2013/02/hash-oil-explosion/How Hash Oil is Blowing Up Across the U.S. \u2013Literally]</ref>\n\n===Infusions===\nThere are many varieties of cannabis infusions owing to the variety of non-volatile solvents used.<ref name=\"Kintz2014\">{{cite book|first = Pascal | last = Kintz  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Toxicological Aspects of Drug-Facilitated Crimes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YgnUAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA141|year=2014|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-0-12-416969-2|page=141}}</ref> The plant material is mixed with the solvent and then pressed and filtered to express the oils of the plant into the solvent. Examples of solvents used in this process are cocoa butter, dairy butter, cooking oil, [[glycerine]], and skin moisturizers. Depending on the solvent, these may be used in [[cannabis foods]] or applied topically.<ref name=\"McDonoughMagazine2012\">{{cite book | first1 = Elise | last1 = McDonough | name-list-format = vanc  |title=The Official High Times Cannabis Cookbook: More Than 50 Irresistible Recipes That Will Get You High |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W-vas6K75YYC&pg=PA17 |year=2012 |publisher=Chronicle Books |isbn=978-1-4521-0133-0 |page=17}}</ref>\n\n===Medical use===\n{{Further|Medical cannabis}}\n\nMedical marijuana refers to the use of the ''Cannabis'' plant as a physician-recommended [[herbal therapy]] as well as synthetic<ref name=\"Backes2014\">{{cite book|first = Michael | last = Backes  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Cannabis Pharmacy: The Practical Guide to Medical Marijuana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7z2FwBywoJ0C&pg=PT46|year=2014|publisher=Hachette Books|isbn=978-1-60376-334-9|page=46}}</ref> THC and cannabinoids. So far, the medical use of cannabis is legal only in a limited number of territories, including Canada,<ref name=canada2018/> [[Belgium]], Australia, the [[Netherlands]], Spain, and [[Medical cannabis in the United States|many U.S. states]]. This usage generally requires a prescription, and distribution is usually done within a framework defined by local laws. There is evidence supporting the use of cannabis or its derivatives in the treatment of chemotherapy-induced nausea and vomiting, neuropathic pain, and multiple sclerosis. Lower levels of evidence support its use for AIDS wasting syndrome, epilepsy, rheumatoid arthritis, and glaucoma.<ref name = NEJM2014 />\n\n[[File:Cannabissativadior.jpg|thumb|upright|''Cannabis sativa'' from [[Vienna Dioscurides]], c.&nbsp;512 CE]]\n\n==History==\n{{See also|History of cannabis|Timeline of cannabis law}}\n\n===Ancient history===\n\nCannabis is [[indigenous (ecology)|indigenous]] to Central Asia<ref>{{cite book|last=Schultes|first=Richard Evans|authorlink=Richard Evans Schultes|title=Hallucinogenic Plants|others=Illustrated by Elmer W. Smith|publisher=[[Western Publishing|Golden Press]]|location=New York|year=1976|isbn=978-0-307-24362-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/hallucinogenicpl00schu_0/page/31 31]|url=https://archive.org/details/hallucinogenicpl00schu_0/page/31}}</ref> and the Indian subcontinent,<ref>\"Marijuana and the Cannabinoids\", ElSohly (p. 8).</ref> and its uses for fabric and rope dates back to the [[Neolithic age]] in China and Japan.<ref name=\"StaffordBigwood1992\">{{cite book|first1=Peter G.|last1=Stafford|first2=Jeremy|last2=Bigwood|name-list-format=vanc|title=Psychedelics Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o4_pLqCOyDsC&pg=PA157|year=1992|publisher=Ronin Publishing|isbn=978-0-914171-51-5|page=157}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|vauthors=Barber EJ|year=1992|title=Prehistoric Textiles: The Development of Cloth in the Neolithic and Bronze Ages with Special Reference to the Aegean|publisher=Princeton University Press|pages=17}}</ref> It is unclear when cannabis first became known for its psychoactive properties. The oldest archeological evidence for the burning of cannabis was found in Romanian [[Kurgan|kurgans]] dated 3,500 BC, and scholars suggest that the drug was first used in ritual ceremonies by [[Proto-Indo-Europeans|Proto-Indo-European]] tribes living in the [[Pontic\u2013Caspian steppe|Pontic-Caspian steppe]] during the [[Chalcolithic|Chalcolithic period]], a custom they eventually spread throughout western Eurasia during the [[Indo-European migrations|Indo-Europan migrations]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=mTxQmQEACAAJ|title=The Horse, the Wheel, and Language: How Bronze-Age Riders from the Eurasian Steppes Shaped the Modern World|last=Anthony|first=David W.|date=2007|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-05887-0|location=|pages=362|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nBvFBAAAQBAJ|title=Seeking the Sacred with Psychoactive Substances: Chemical Paths to Spirituality and to God|last=Ellens|first=J. Harold|date=2014|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1440830884|location=|pages=24, 31|language=en}}</ref> Some research suggests that the ancient [[Indo-Iranians|Indo-Iranian]] drug [[soma (drink)|soma]], mentioned in the [[Veda]]s, sometimes contained cannabis. This is based on the discovery of a basin containing cannabis in a shrine of the [[second millennium BC]] in [[Turkmenistan]].<ref name=\"Rudgley-Encyclopedia\">{{cite book|last=Rudgley|first=Richard|name-list-format=vanc|year=1998|chapter-url=http://www.huxley.net/soma/index.html|chapter=Soma|title=The Encyclopedia of Psychoactive Substances|publisher=Little, Brown and Company|isbn=978-0-349-11127-8}}</ref> \n\nCannabis was known to the [[History of the Assyrian people|ancient Assyrians]], who discovered its psychoactive properties through the Iranians.<ref>{{cite book|last=Franck|first=Mel|name-list-format=vanc|title=Marijuana Grower's Guide|publisher=Red Eye Press|year=1997|isbn=978-0-929349-03-9|page=3}}</ref> Using it in some religious ceremonies, they called it ''qunubu'' (meaning \"way to produce smoke\"), a probable origin of the modern word \"cannabis\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Rubin|first=Vera D.|name-list-format=vanc|title=Cannabis and Culture|publisher=Campus Verlag|year=1976|isbn=978-3-593-37442-0|page=305}}</ref> The Iranians also introduced cannabis to the [[Scythia]]ns, [[Thracians]] and [[Dacia]]ns, whose [[shamanism|shamans]] (the ''[[kapnobatai]]''\u2014\"those who walk on smoke/clouds\") burned cannabis infructescences to induce [[trance]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Cunliffe|first=Barry W.|name-list-format=vanc|title=The Oxford Illustrated History of Prehistoric Europe|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|isbn=978-0-19-285441-4|page=405}}</ref> The plant was used in China before 2800 BC, and found therapeutic use in India by 1000 BC, where it was used [[cannabis edible|in food and drink]], including ''[[bhang]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Schultes|first=Richard Evans|title=Hallucinogenic Plants|others=Illustrated by Elmer W. Smith|publisher=Golden Press|location=New York|year=1976|isbn=978-0-307-24362-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/hallucinogenicpl00schu_0/page/34 34]|url=https://archive.org/details/hallucinogenicpl00schu_0/page/34}}</ref><ref name=vice>{{cite web|url=https://munchies.vice.com/en_us/article/kbx94a/httpmunchies-vice-comarticlesthe-bhang-lassi-is-how-hindus-drink-themselves-high-for-shiva |title=The Bhang Lassi Is How Hindus Drink Themselves High for Shiva |author=Staelens, Stefanie|website=Vice.com|accessdate=10 August 2017|date=2015-03-10 }}</ref>\n[[File:Bhang eaters before two huts (6124556163).jpg|thumb|left|300px|[[Hindus]] eating [[bhang]] (c. 1790)]]\n\nCannabis has an ancient history of ritual use and is found in [[pharmacological cult]]s around the world. The earliest evidence of cannabis smoking has been found in the 2,500-year-old tombs of Jirzankal Cemetery in the [[Pamir Mountains]] in Western China, where cannabis residue were found in burners with charred pebbles possibly used during funeral rituals.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ren M, Tang Z, Wu X, Spengler R, Jiang H, Yang Y, Boivin N | title = The origins of cannabis smoking: Chemical residue evidence from the first millennium BCE in the Pamirs | journal = Science Advances | volume = 5 | issue = 6 | pages = eaaw1391 | date = June 2019 | pmid = 31206023 | pmc = 6561734 | doi = 10.1126/sciadv.aaw1391 | bibcode = 2019SciA....5.1391R }}</ref><ref name=\"NatGeo2019Jun\" /> Hemp seeds discovered by archaeologists at [[Pazyryk burials|Pazyryk]] suggest early ceremonial practices like eating by the Scythians occurred during the 5th to 2nd century BC, confirming previous historical reports by [[Herodotus]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Walton|first=Robert P.|name-list-format=vanc|title=Marijuana, America's New Drug Problem|publisher=JB Lippincott|year=1938|page=6}}</ref> It was used by Muslims in various [[Sufi]] orders as early as the [[Mamluk]] period, for example by the [[Qalandariyya|Qalandars]].<ref>{{cite book|language=FR|title=Le haschich et l'extase|first=Ibn|last=Taymiyya|name-list-format=vanc|author-link=Ibn Taymiyya|isbn=978-2-84161-174-4|year=2001|publisher=Albouraq|location=Beyrouth}}</ref> Smoking pipes uncovered in Ethiopia and carbon-dated to around c. AD 1320 were found to have traces of cannabis.<ref name=\"Rubin1975\">{{cite book|first=Vera|last=Rubin|name-list-format=vanc|title=Cannabis and Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gCRNRGOhNA4C&pg=PA77|date=1 January 1975|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-081206-0|pages=77\u2013|quote=Cannabis Smoking in 13th-14th Century Ethiopia: Chemical Evidence}}</ref>\n\n===Modern history===\n\nFollowing an 1836\u20131840 travel in North Africa and the Middle East, French physician [[Jacques-Joseph Moreau]] wrote on the psychological effects of cannabis use; he was a member of Paris' [[Club des Hashischins]].{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} In 1842, Irish physician [[William Brooke O'Shaughnessy]], who had studied the drug while working as a medical officer in Bengal with the East India company, brought a quantity of cannabis with him on his return to Britain, provoking renewed interest in the West.<ref name=\"Iversen2007\">{{cite book|first=Leslie L.|last=Iversen|name-list-format=vanc|title=The Science of Marijuana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sshsCAAAQBAJ&pg=PT110|date=7 December 2007|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-988693-7|pages=110\u2013}}</ref> Examples of classic literature of the period featuring cannabis include ''[[Les paradis artificiels]]'' (1860) by [[Charles Baudelaire]] and ''[[The Hasheesh Eater]]'' (1857) by [[Fitz Hugh Ludlow]].\n\n[[File:Killerdrug.jpg|thumb|Cannabis propaganda from 1935]]\nCannabis was criminalized in various countries beginning in the 19th century. The British colonies of Mauritius banned cannabis in 1840 over concerns on its effect on Indian indentured workers;<ref>{{cite book|title=A Collection of the Laws of Mauritius and Its Dependencies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ktHAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA541|year=1867|publisher=By the authority of the Government|pages=541\u2013}}</ref> the same occurred in British Singapore in 1870.<ref name=\"Bunyapraphats\u014dn_1999\">{{cite book|first=Nanthawan|last=Bunyapraphats\u014dn|name-list-format=vanc|title=Medicinal and poisonous plants|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ifDwAAAAMAAJ|year=1999|publisher=Backhuys Publishers|isbn=978-90-5782-042-7|page=169}}</ref> In the United States, the first restrictions on sale of cannabis came in 1906 (in [[District of Columbia]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.druglibrary.org/schaffer/hemp/taxact/woodward.htm |title=Statement of Dr. William C. Woodward |publisher= Drug library |access-date= 2010-09-20}}</ref> Canada criminalized cannabis in ''The Opium and Narcotic Drug Act, 1923'',<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title  =The Opium and Narcotic Drug Act, 1923|abbr =S.C.|year =1923|chapter =22|link= https://archive.org/stream/actsofparl1923v01cana#page/134/mode/2up}}</ref> before any reports of the use of the drug in Canada, but eventually legalized its consumption for recreational and medicinal purposes in 2018.<ref name=canada2018/>\n\n[[File:Drug bottle containing cannabis.jpg|thumb|upright|Cannabis indica fluid extract, American Druggists Syndicate ({{nowrap|pre-1937}})]]\nIn 1925, a compromise was made at an international conference in [[The Hague]] about the [[International Opium Convention]] that banned exportation of \"Indian hemp\" to countries that had prohibited its use, and requiring importing countries to issue certificates approving the importation and stating that the shipment was required \"exclusively for medical or scientific purposes\". It also required parties to \"exercise an effective control of such a nature as to prevent the illicit international traffic in Indian hemp and especially in the resin\".<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.druglibrary.org/schaffer/history/e1920/willoughby.htm | vauthors = Willoughby WW |title=Opium as an international problem | location=Baltimore |publisher=The Johns Hopkins Press |year=1925 |access-date=2010-09-20}}</ref><ref>{{Google books|GJm-XDLJe1QC|Opium as an international problem: the Geneva conferences&nbsp;\u2013 Westel Woodbury Willoughby}}</ref> In the United States in 1937, the [[Marihuana Tax Act of 1937|Marihuana Tax Act]] was passed,<ref>{{USStatute|75|238|50|551|1937|8|2}}</ref> and prohibited the production of hemp in addition to cannabis.\n\nIn 1972, the Dutch government divided drugs into more- and less-dangerous categories, with cannabis being in the lesser category. Accordingly, possession of {{convert|30|g||||}} or less was made a misdemeanor.<ref name=\"Booth2005\">{{cite book| first = Martin | last = Booth  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Cannabis: A History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O7AoY6ljSygC&pg=PA338|date=1 June 2005|publisher=Picador|isbn=978-0-312-42494-7|pages=338\u2013}}</ref> Cannabis has been available for recreational use in [[Coffeeshop (Netherlands)|coffee shops]] since 1976.<ref name=\"Tonry2015\">{{cite book|author=Michael Tonry|title=Crime and Justice | volume = 44 | series = A Review of Research|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TMauCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT261|date=22 September 2015|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-34102-6|pages=261\u2013}}</ref> Cannabis products are only sold openly in certain local \"coffeeshops\" and possession of up to {{convert|5|g||||}} for personal use is decriminalized, however: the police may still confiscate it, which often happens in car checks near the border. Other types of sales and transportation are not permitted, although the general approach toward cannabis was lenient even before official [[decriminalization]].<ref>{{citation |url = http://eldd.emcdda.europa.eu/html.cfm/index5174EN.html# |title = Use drop-down menu on site to view Netherlands entry.) |publisher = Eldd.emcdda.europa.eu |date =  |access-date = 2011-02-17 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url = http://www.ukcia.org/research/dutch.php |title = Drugs Policy in the Netherlands |publisher = Ukcia.org |date =  |access-date = 2011-02-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.theatlanticwire.com/global/2011/05/amsterdam-ban-pot-sales-tourists/38248/ |title = Amsterdam Will Ban Tourists from Pot Coffee Shops |work = Atlantic Wire |access-date = 2011-06-23 |last =  |first =  |date = 27 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn Uruguay, President [[Jose Mujica]] signed legislation to [[Cannabis in Uruguay|legalize recreational cannabis]] in December 2013, making Uruguay the first country in the modern era to legalize cannabis. In August 2014, Uruguay legalized growing up to six plants at home, as well as the formation of growing clubs, and a state-controlled [[marijuana dispensary]] regime.\n\nAs of 17 October 2018 when recreational use of cannabis was legalized in Canada, [[dietary supplement]]s for human use and [[Holistic veterinary medicine|veterinary health products]] containing not more than 10 parts per million of THC [[extract]] were approved for marketing; [[Nabiximols]] (as Sativex) is used as a [[prescription drug]] in Canada.<ref name=canada2018/>\n\nThe United Nations' ''World Drug Report'' stated that cannabis \"was the world's most widely produced, trafficked, and consumed drug in the world in 2010\", and estimated between 128 million and 238 million users globally in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marijuana Now the Most Popular Drug in the World|url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2012/06/29/marijuana-now-the-most-popular-drug-in-the-world/|work=Time NewsFeed|publisher=Time Inc|access-date=16 March 2013| first = Eliana | last = Dockterman  | name-list-format = vanc |date=29 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=World Drug Report 2017 |chapter=Factsheet |chapter-url=https://www.unodc.org/wdr2017/index.html |publisher=United Nation Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC) |access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Society and culture==\n{{See also|Cannabis culture}}\n\n===Legal status===\n{{Main|Legality of cannabis}}\n{{See also|Prohibition of drugs|Drug liberalization}}\n[[File:Map-of-world-cannabis-laws.svg|thumb|right|380px|alt=Map of world cannabis laws|\n'''Legal status of cannabis possession for non-medical use'''\n----\n{{legend|#0d00f2|Legal}}\n{{legend|#ffb700|Illegal but decriminalized}}\n{{legend|#ff9e9e|Illegal but often unenforced}}\n{{legend|#ff3c3c|Illegal}}\n----\n<small>See also [[:File:Map-of-world-medical-cannabis-laws.svg|countries that have legalized medical use of cannabis]]</small>]]\n<!-- PLEASE, keep this section relatively compact, contributions are more than welcome at [[Legality of cannabis]]. THANKS. -->\nSince the beginning of the 20th century, most countries have enacted [[prohibition (drugs)|laws]] against the cultivation, possession or transfer of cannabis.<ref name=\"Levinson2002\">{{cite book|first = David | last = Levinson  | name-list-format = vanc  |title=Encyclopedia of Crime and Punishment|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aiQ09D7nWxYC&pg=PA572|year=2002|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-0-7619-2258-2|page=572}}</ref> These laws have impacted adversely on cannabis cultivation for non-recreational purposes, but there are many regions where handling of cannabis is legal or licensed. Many jurisdictions have lessened the penalties for possession of small quantities of cannabis so that it is punished by confiscation and sometimes a fine, rather than imprisonment, focusing more on those who traffic the drug on the [[black market]].\n\nIn some areas where cannabis use had been historically tolerated, new restrictions were instituted, such as the closing of cannabis coffee shops near the borders of the Netherlands,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.expatica.com/nl/leisure/arts_culture/many-dutch-coffee-shops-close-as-liberal-policies-change-46376.html |title=Many Dutch coffee shops close as liberal policies change, Exaptica |date=2007-11-27 |publisher=Expatica.com |access-date=2010-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429192229/http://www.expatica.com/nl/leisure/arts_culture/many-dutch-coffee-shops-close-as-liberal-policies-change-46376.html |archive-date=2011-04-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and closing of coffee shops near secondary schools in the Netherlands.<ref>[http://www.rnw.nl/internationaljustice/news/international/6061587/43-Amsterdam-coffee-shops-to-close-doors \"43 Amsterdam coffee shops to close door\"], Radio Netherlands, Friday 21 November 2008 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202130012/http://www.rnw.nl/internationaljustice/news/international/6061587/43-Amsterdam-coffee-shops-to-close-doors |date=December 2, 2008 }}</ref> In [[Copenhagen]], Denmark in 2014, mayor [[Frank Jensen]] discussed possibilities for the city to legalize cannabis production and commerce.<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Sullivan|first1=Feargus | name-list-format = vanc |title=Why the Mayor of Copenhagen Wants to Get Into the Marijuana Business|url=https://www.citylab.com/equity/2014/03/why-mayor-copenhagen-wants-get-marijuana-business/8527/|access-date=23 January 2018|date=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nSome jurisdictions use free voluntary treatment programs and/or mandatory treatment programs for frequent known users. Simple possession can carry long prison terms in some countries, particularly in East Asia, where the sale of cannabis may lead to a sentence of life in prison or even execution. Political parties, non-profit organizations, and causes based on the legalization of medical cannabis and/or legalizing the plant entirely (with some restrictions) have emerged in such countries as China and Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johnston|first1=Ian| name-list-format = vanc |title=As cannabis is widely legalised, China cashes in on an unprecedented boom|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/as-cannabis-is-widely-legalised-china-cashes-in-on-an-unprecedented-boom-9039191.html|publisher=Independent|access-date=23 January 2018|date=5 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Liljas|first1=Per| name-list-format = vanc |title=Could Thailand, which gave world the bong, legalise cannabis for medicinal use? After failed war on drugs, attitudes have softened|url=http://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/long-reads/article/2097464/could-thailand-which-gave-world-bong-legalise|publisher=Post Magazine|access-date=23 January 2018|date=3 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, the U.S. state of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] became the first state to officially legalize cannabis in a state law ([[Washington Initiative 502]]) (but still illegal by [[Cannabis in the United States|federal law]]),<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/12/07/uk-usa-marijuana-washington-idUSLNE8B502120121207|title=Marijuana goes legal in Washington state amid mixed messages |newspaper=Reuters |access-date=December 14, 2012|date=2012-12-07 }}</ref> with the state of [[Colorado]] following close behind ([[Colorado Amendment 64]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/11/07/politics/marijuana-legalization/index.html |title=2 states legalize pot, but don't 'break out the Cheetos' yet | first = Alan | last = Duke  | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=CNN.com |date=2012-11-08 |access-date=2013-01-02}}</ref> On 1 January 2013, the first marijuana \"club\" for private marijuana smoking (no buying or selling, however) was allowed for the first time in Colorado.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/marijuana-clubs-ring-year-colorado-legalized-pot-smoking/story?id=18108083 |title=Marijuana clubs ring in new year in Colorado as legalized pot smoking begins |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2013-01-01 |access-date=2013-01-02}}</ref> The California Supreme Court decided in May 2013 that local governments can ban medical marijuana dispensaries despite a state law in California that permits the use of cannabis for medical purposes. At least 180 cities across California have enacted bans in recent years.<ref>{{cite news|first = Horward | last = Mintz  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Medical pot: California Supreme Court allows cities to ban weed dispensaries |work=Marin Independent Journal |date=2013-05-06 |url=http://www.marinij.com/digitalfirstmedia/ci_23184556/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102202631/http://www.marinij.com/digitalfirstmedia/ci_23184556/ |archive-date=November 2, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, [[Uruguay]] became the first country to legalize growing, sale and use of cannabis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2013/dec/11/uruguay-marijuana-laws-around-world|title=Marijuana laws around the world: what you need to know| first = Vicky | last = Baker | name-list-format = vanc |newspaper=the Guardian|date=2013-12-11}}</ref>  After a long delay in implementing the retail component of the law, in 2017 sixteen pharmacies were authorized to sell cannabis commercially.<ref name=UrGuardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jul/19/uruguay-marijuana-sale-pharmacies|title=Uruguay pharmacies start selling cannabis straight to consumers|last=Reuters|date=19 July 2017|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> On 19 June 2018, the Canadian Senate passed a bill and the Prime Minister announced the effective legalization date as 17 October 2018.<ref name=canada2018/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4285946/marijuana-legal-date-october-17-canada-trudeau-confirms/|title=Marijuana to be legal in Canada starting October 17, Trudeau confirms|date=2018-06-20}}</ref> Canada is the second country to legalize the drug.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/20/health/canada-legalizes-marijuana/index.html|title=Canada becomes second nation in the world to legalize marijuana|first=Bani |last=Sapra}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, [[Uttarakhand]] became the first state of [[India]] to legalize the cultivation of hemp for industrial purposes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uttarakhand To Become First Indian State To Legalise Cannabis Cultivation|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/uttarakhand-to-become-first-indian-state-to-legalise-cannabis-cultivation-247769.html|website=Indiatimes|access-date=12 March 2017|language=en|date=2015-11-27}}</ref> Usage within the Hindu and Buddhist cultures of the [[Indian subcontinent]] is common, with many street vendors in India openly selling products infused with cannabis, and traditional medical practitioners in Sri Lanka selling products infused with cannabis for recreational purposes and well as for religious celebrations.<ref name=\":1\" /> It was criminalized in the Indian subcontinent by the Dutch and then the British. India and Sri Lanka have allowed cannabis to be taken in the context of traditional culture for recreational/celebratory purposes and also for medicinal purposes.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/pdf/india/publications/south_Asia_Regional_Profile_Sept_2005/13_srilanka.pdf|title=South Asia Regional Profile Report|last=|first=|date=|website=UNODC|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 October 2015, Australian health minister Sussan Ley presented a new law that will allow the [[Agriculture|cultivation]] of cannabis for scientific research and medical trials on patients.<ref>Alchimia Blog, ''[https://www.alchimiaweb.com/blogen/medical-marijuana-news-december-2015/ Medical marijuana news, December 2015]''</ref>\n\nOn 17 October 2018, Canada legalized cannabis for recreational adult use<ref name=\"Butler\">{{cite news |last=Butler|first=Patrick|date=17 October 2018|title=Cannabis is legal in Canada \u2014 here's what you need to know|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/marijuana-faq-legalization-need-to-know-1.4862207/|work=CBC|access-date=1 November 2018 }}</ref> making it the second country in the world to do so after Uruguay and the first G7 nation.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sapra|first=Bani|date=20 June 2018|title=Canada becomes second nation in the world to legalize marijuana|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/20/health/canada-legalizes-marijuana/index.html|work=CNN|access-date=1 November 2018 }}</ref> The [[List of licensed producers of medical marijuana in Canada|Canadian Licensed Producer]] system aims to become the Gold Standard in the world for safe and secure cannabis production,<ref>{{cite web|title=This Application Seems Rigorous. Are All These Hoops Necessary?|url=https://licensedproducerscanada.ca/faq/application-seems-rigorous-hoops-necessary|work=LicensedProducersCanada.com|access-date=1 November 2018}}</ref> including provisions for a robust craft cannabis industry where many expect opportunities for experimenting with different strains.<ref>{{cite web|title=Will Craft Cannabis Growers in Canada Succeed Like Craft Brewers?|url=https://licensedproducerscanada.ca/faq/will-craft-cannabis-growers-in-canada-succeed-like-craft-brewers|work=LicensedProducersCanada.com|access-date=1 November 2018}}</ref> Laws around use vary from province to province including age limits, retail structure, and growing at home.<ref name=\"Butler\"/>\n\nAs the drug has increasingly been seen as a health issue instead of criminal behavior, marijuana has also been legalized or [[Decriminalization|decriminalized]] in: [[Czech Republic]],<ref name=\"Cz expl rep\">{{Citation | last = Parliament of the Czech Republic | year = 1998 | title = Explanatory Report to Act No. 112/1998 Coll., which amends the Act No. 140/1961 Coll., the Criminal Code, and the Act No. 200/1990 Coll., on misdemeanors | location = Prague | page = | url = | access-date = | language = Czech}} \"''Podle \u010dl. 36 Jednotn\u00e9 \u00famluvy o omamn\u00fdch l\u00e1tk\u00e1ch ze dne 31. b\u0159ezna 1961 (\u010d. 47/1965 Sb.) se signat\u00e1\u0159i zavazuj\u00ed k trestn\u00edmu postihu tam uveden\u00fdch forem nakl\u00e1d\u00e1n\u00ed s drogami v\u010detn\u011b jejich dr\u017eby. N\u00e1vrh upou\u0161t\u00ed od dosavadn\u00ed beztrestnosti dr\u017eby omamn\u00fdch a psychotropn\u00edch l\u00e1tek a jed\u016f pro svoji pot\u0159ebu. Dosavadn\u00ed beztrestnost toti\u017e eliminuje v \u0159ad\u011b p\u0159\u00edpad\u016f mo\u017enost postihu dealer\u016f a distributor\u016f drog.''\"</ref> [[Colombia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2012/03/2012327125714281880.html|title=The summit of muted intentions| first = Jorge G | last = Castaneda  | name-list-format = vanc |work=aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noticiasrcn.com/nacional-pais/congreso-aprobo-ultimo-debate-uso-medicinal-marihuana|title=Congreso aprob\u00f3, en \u00faltimo debate, uso medicinal de la marihuana|date=25 May 2016}}</ref> [[Ecuador]],<ref>[http://www.elcomercio.com/seguridad/Dosis-maximas-droga-consumo-vigentes_0_941905849.html \"Dosis m\u00e1ximas de droga para consumo ya est\u00e1n vigentes\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624025336/http://www.elcomercio.com/seguridad/Dosis-maximas-droga-consumo-vigentes_0_941905849.html |date=2013-06-24 }} at [[El Comercio (Ecuador)|El Comercio]].com.</ref><ref>[http://www.elnuevoherald.com/2013/06/21/1505650/ecuador-aprueban-tenencia-de-drogas.html \"Ecuador: Aprueban tenencia de drogas para consumo\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625023421/http://www.elnuevoherald.com/2013/06/21/1505650/ecuador-aprueban-tenencia-de-drogas.html |date=2013-06-25 }} at ''[[El Nuevo Herald]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegrafo.com.ec/english-bulletin/item/ecuador-could-regulate-drug-sales.html|title=Ecuador could regulate the drug industry|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130624225110/http://www.telegrafo.com.ec/english-bulletin/item/ecuador-could-regulate-drug-sales.html|archive-date=2013-06-24|df=}}</ref> [[Portugal]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emcdda.europa.eu/system/files/publications/642/PolicyProfile_Portugal_WEB_Final_289201.pdf |title=Drug policy profiles \u2014 Portugal |date=2011-06-01 |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref> [[Cannabis in South Africa|South Africa]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/09/18/dagga-users-celebrate-following-concourt-ruling-on-private-use|title=Dagga users celebrate following ConCourt ruling on private use|last=Lindeque|first=Mia|access-date=2018-11-03|language=en}}</ref> and [[Canada]].<ref name=canada2018/> Medical marijuana was legalized in [[Mexico]] in mid-2017; legislators plan to legalize its recreational use by late 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Williams |first1=Sean |title=Mexico Aims to Legalize Recreational Marijuana Before October \u2013 |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/04/28/mexico-aims-to-legalize-recreational-marijuana-bef.aspx |website=The Motley Fool |accessdate=April 29, 2019 |language=en |date=April 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>[http://www.elpensador.com.mx/2009/10/17/Ley-de-Narcomenudeo/ Ley de Narcomenudeo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130224127/http://www.elpensador.com.mx/2009/10/17/Ley-de-Narcomenudeo/ |date=2010-11-30 }}, ''El Pensador'' {{in lang|es}}, 17 October 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.druglawreform.info/index.php?option=com_flexicontent&view=items&cid=97%3Alegislative-reform-of-drug-policies&id=220%3Amexico-the-law-against-small-scale-drug-dealing&Itemid=34&lang=en Mexico: The Law Against Small-Scale Drug Dealing. A Doubtful Venture], Jorge Hern\u00e1ndez Tinajero & Carlos Zamudio Angles, Series on Legislative Reform of Drug Policies Nr. 3, November 2009</ref>\n\n===Usage===\n{{Global estimates of illicit drug users}}\nIn 2013, between 128 and 232 million people used cannabis (2.7% to 4.9% of the global population between the ages of 15 and 65).<ref name=WDR2015/> Cannabis is by far the most widely used illicit substance.<ref name=\"CaulkinsHawken2012\">{{cite book | first1 = Jonathan P. | last1 = Caulkins | first2 = Angela | last2 = Hawken | first3 = Beau | last3 = Kilmer | first4 = Mark A.R. | last4 = Kleiman | name-list-format = vanc | title = Marijuana Legalization: What Everyone Needs to Know | publisher = Oxford University Press | isbn = 978-0199913732 | page = [https://archive.org/details/marijuanalegaliz0000unse/page/16 16] | date = 2012-09-27 | url = https://archive.org/details/marijuanalegaliz0000unse/page/16 }}</ref>\n\n====United States====\nBetween 1973 and 1978, eleven states decriminalized marijuana.<ref name=\"tandfonline.com\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1080/17541328.2015.1058480 | volume=8 | title=The business of getting high: head shops, countercultural capitalism, and the marijuana legalization movement | year=2015 | journal=The Sixties | pages=27\u201349 | first = Clark Davis | last = Joshua  | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> In 2001, [[Nevada]] reduced marijuana possession to a misdemeanor and since 2012, several other states have decriminalized and even legalized marijuana.<ref name=\"tandfonline.com\"/>\n\nIn 2015, almost half of the people in the United States had tried marijuana, 12% had used it in the past year, and 7.3% had used it in the past month.<ref name=\"6 facts about marijuana\"/> In 2014, daily marijuana use amongst US college students had reached its highest level since records began in 1980, rising from 3.5% in 2007 to 5.9% in 2014 and had surpassed daily [[cigarette]] use.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://record.umich.edu/articles/daily-marijuana-use-among-college-students-highest-1980|title=Daily marijuana use among college students highest since 1980|work=The University Record}}</ref>\n\nIn the US, men are over twice as likely to use marijuana as women, and 18{{ndash}}29-year-olds are six times more likely to use as over-65-year-olds.<ref name=\"gallup.com\">{{cite news |last1=McCarthy |first1=Justin |title=More Than Four in 10 Americans Say They Have Tried Marijuana |url=https://news.gallup.com/poll/184298/four-americans-say-tried-marijuana.aspx |work=Gallup |date=22 July 2015}}</ref> In 2015, a record 44% of the US population has tried marijuana in their lifetime, an increase from 38% in 2013 and 33% in 1985.<ref name=\"gallup.com\"/>\n\nMarijuana use in the United States is three times above the global average, but in line with other Western democracies. Forty-four percent of American 12th graders have tried the drug at least once, and the typical age of first-use is 16, similar to the typical age of first-use for alcohol but lower than the first-use age for other [[Illegal drug trade|illicit drugs]].<ref name=\"CaulkinsHawken2012\"/>\n\n===Economics===\n\n====Production====\n{{Main|Cannabis cultivation}}\n[[File:Woman selling Cannabis and Bhang in Guwahati, Assam, India.jpg|thumb|Woman selling cannabis and [[bhang]] in [[Guwahati]], Assam, [[India]]]]\n<!-- PLEASE, do not add more detail to this section, contributions are more than welcome at [[Cannabis (drug) cultivation]]. THANKS. -->\n\n''Sinsemilla'' (Spanish for \"without seed\") is the dried, seedless (i.e. [[Parthenocarpy|parthenocarpic]]) [[infructescence]]s of female [[Cannabis sativa|cannabis plants]]. Because THC production drops off once pollination occurs, the male plants (which produce little THC themselves) are eliminated before they shed pollen to prevent pollination, thus inducing the development of [[Parthenocarpy|parthenocarpic]] fruits gathered in dense [[infructescence]]s. Advanced cultivation techniques such as [[Cannabis (drug) cultivation#Hydroponic cultivation|hydroponics]], [[Cannabis (drug) cultivation#Feminized seeds|cloning]], [[Cannabis (drug) cultivation#Light|high-intensity artificial lighting]], and [[Cannabis (drug) cultivation#SOG|the sea of green method]] are frequently employed as a response (in part) to prohibition enforcement efforts that make outdoor cultivation more risky.\n\n{{anchor|Skunk}}\n\"Skunk\" refers to several named strains of potent cannabis, grown through selective breeding and sometimes [[hydroponics]]. It is a cross-breed of ''Cannabis sativa'' and ''C. indica'' (although other strains of this mix exist in abundance). Skunk cannabis potency ranges usually from 6% to 15% and rarely as high as 20%. The average THC level in coffee shops in the Netherlands is about 18\u201319%.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/data-and-analysis/WDR-2006.html |title=World Drug Report 2006 |publisher=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime}} Ch. 2.3.</ref>\n\nThe average levels of THC in cannabis sold in the [[United States Of America|United States]] rose dramatically between the [[1970s (decade)|1970s]] and [[2000s (decade)|2000]].<ref name=Giz /> This is disputed for various reasons, and there is little consensus as to whether this is a fact or an artifact of poor testing methodologies.<ref name=Giz /> According to Daniel Forbes writing for slate.com, the relative strength of modern strains are likely skewed because undue weight is given to much more expensive and potent, but less prevalent, samples.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2074151 |publisher=Slate.com |title=The Myth of Potent Pot | first = Daniel | last = Forbes  | name-list-format = vanc |date=2002-11-19}}</ref> Some suggest that results are skewed by older testing methods that included low-THC-content plant material such as leaves in the samples, which are excluded in contemporary tests. Others believe that modern strains actually are significantly more potent than older ones.<ref name=Giz>{{cite web|last=Turco|first=Bucky|title=Why is Weed Getting More Potent|work=Gizmodo|url=https://gizmodo.com/why-is-weed-getting-more-potent-1818662872|date=25 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Price====\nThe price or street value of cannabis varies widely depending on geographic area and potency.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unodc.org/pdf/WDR_2005/volume_2_chap7_cannabis.pdf |title=Cannabis: Wholesale, street prices and purity levels |publisher=UNODC.org |year=2005 |access-date=2013-01-09}}</ref> Prices and overall markets have also varied considerably over time.\n\n* In 1997, cannabis was estimated to be overall the number four value crop in the US, and number one or two in many states, including California, New York, and Florida.  This estimate is based on a value to growers of ~60% of retail value, or {{convert|3000|$/lb|$/kg}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Report on U.S. Domestic Marijuana Production|url=http://norml.org/index.cfm?Group_ID=4444|url-status=dead|publisher=NORML|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226011927/http://www.norml.org//index.cfm?Group_ID=4444|archive-date=December 26, 2009|access-date=2010-01-02}}</ref>\n* In 2006, cannabis was estimated to have been a $36&nbsp;billion market.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2006-12-20|title=Marijuana Called Top U.S. Cash Crop|url=http://abcnews.go.com/business/story?id=2735017&page=1|publisher=2008 ABCNews Internet Ventures}}</ref> This estimate has been challenged as exaggerated.<ref name=\"CaulkinsHawken2012\" /> The UN World Drug Report (2008) estimated that 2006 street prices in the US and Canada ranged from about US$8.8 to $25 per gram (approximately $250 to $700 per ounce), depending on quality.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.unodc.org/documents/wdr/WDR_2008/WDR_2008_eng_web.pdf|title=World drug report|author=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|publisher=United Nations Publications|year=2008|isbn=978-92-1-148229-4|location=|page=268}}</ref> Typical U.S. retail prices were $10\u201315 per gram (approximately $280\u2013420 per [[ounce]]). \n* In 2017, the U.S. was estimated to constitute 90% of the worldwide $9.5 billion trade in cannabis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investopedia.com/insights/how-federal-legalization-could-transform-us-cannabis-market/|title=How Federal Legalization Could Transform The US Cannabis Market|last=Sharma|first=Rakesh|date=2019-06-25|website=Investopedia|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n\nAfter some U.S. states legalized cannabis, street prices began to drop.  In Colorado, the price of smokable buds (infructescences) dropped 40 percent between 2014 and 2019, from $200 per ounce to $120 per ounce ($7 per gram to $4.19 per gram).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2019/05/23/pot-growers-push-organic-cannabis-cleaner-option-but-buyers-remain-skeptical/1206364001/|title=As marijuana prices drop, growers push 'organic' cannabis \u2013 with a higher price tag|last=Hughes|first=Trevor|date=2019-05-23|website=USA TODAY|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and Drug Addiction]] reports that typical retail prices in Europe for cannabis varied from \u20ac2 to \u20ac20 per gram in 2008, with a majority of European countries reporting prices in the range \u20ac4\u201310.<ref>{{cite book |author=European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and Drug Addiction |title=Annual report: the state of the drugs problem in Europe |year=2008 |publisher=Office for Official Publications of the European Communities |location=Luxembourg |isbn=978-92-9168-324-6 |url=http://www.emcdda.europa.eu/attachements.cfm/att_64227_EN_EMCDDA_AR08_en.pdf |page=38}}</ref>\n\n===Gateway drug===\n{{main|Gateway drug theory}}\nThe gateway hypothesis states that cannabis use increases the probability of trying \"harder\" drugs. The hypothesis has been hotly debated as it is regarded by some as the primary rationale for the United States prohibition on cannabis use.<ref name=\"Rand\">{{Cite web |date=2002-12-02 |url=https://www.rand.org/news/press.02/gateway.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061104124529/https://www.rand.org/news/press.02/gateway.html |archive-date=2006-11-04 |title=RAND study casts doubt on claims that marijuana acts as a \"gateway\" to the use of cocaine and heroin|publisher=RAND Corporation}}</ref><ref name=\"Benavie2009x\">{{cite book| first = Arthur | last = Benavie  | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drugs: America's Holy War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DQxXDgLnKD8C&pg=PA90|year=2009|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-7890-3840-1|pages=90\u2013}}</ref> A Pew Research Center poll found that political opposition to marijuana use was significantly associated with concerns about the health effects and whether legalization would increase marijuana use by children.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people-press.org/2014/04/02/section-2-views-of-marijuana-legalization-decriminalization-concerns/ |title=Public Views of Marijuana \u2013 Legalization, Decriminalization, Concerns &#124; Pew Research Center for the People and the Press |website= |access-date=|date=2014-04-02 }}</ref>\n\nSome studies state that while there is no proof for the gateway hypothesis,<ref name=\"MosherAkins2007\">{{cite book | first1 = Clayton J. | last1 = Mosher | first2 = Scott | last2 = Akins | name-list-format = vanc |title=Drugs and Drug Policy: The Control of Consciousness Alteration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aDMvoMxx0-IC&pg=PA18|year=2007|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-0-7619-3007-5|page=18}}</ref> young cannabis users should still be considered as a risk group for intervention programs.<ref name=\"journalwatch\">{{cite journal | last = Saitz | first = Richard | name-list-format = vanc |title=Is marijuana a gateway drug? |journal=Journal Watch |date=2003-02-18 |volume=2003 |issue=218 |page=1 |url=http://general-medicine.jwatch.org/cgi/content/full/2003/218/1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030710150041/http://general-medicine.jwatch.org/cgi/content/full/2003/218/1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-07-10 }}</ref> Other findings indicate that [[hard and soft drugs|hard drug]] users are likely to be [[poly drug use|poly-drug users]], and that interventions must address the use of multiple drugs instead of a single hard drug.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Degenhardt L, Coffey C, Carlin JB, Moran P, Patton GC | title = Who are the new amphetamine users? A 10-year prospective study of young Australians | journal = Addiction | volume = 102 | issue = 8 | pages = 1269\u201379 | date = August 2007 | pmid = 17624977 | doi = 10.1111/j.1360-0443.2007.01906.x }}</ref> Almost two-thirds of the poly drug users in the 2009-2010 Scottish Crime and Justice Survey used cannabis.<ref>{{cite web|title=3 The Experience of Drug Users|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Publications/2011/01/21134813/7|work=2009/10 Scottish Crime and Justice Survey: Drug Use|publisher=The Scottish Government|access-date=5 November 2013|date=21 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe gateway effect may appear due to social factors involved in using any illegal drug. Because of the illegal status of cannabis, its consumers are likely to find themselves in situations allowing them to acquaint with individuals using or selling other illegal drugs.<ref name=\"morral2002\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Morral AR, McCaffrey DF, Paddock SM | title = Reassessing the marijuana gateway effect | journal = Addiction | volume = 97 | issue = 12 | pages = 1493\u2013504 | date = December 2002 | pmid = 12472629 | doi = 10.1046/j.1360-0443.2002.00280.x }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mpp.org/about/faq.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622204803/http://www.mpp.org/about/faq.html|archive-date=2008-06-22|title=Marijuana Policy Project \u2013 FAQ}}</ref> Studies have shown that alcohol and tobacco may additionally be regarded as gateway drugs;<ref name=\"pmid8246462\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Torabi MR, Bailey WJ, Majd-Jabbari M | title = Cigarette smoking as a predictor of alcohol and other drug use by children and adolescents: evidence of the \"gateway drug effect\" | journal = The Journal of School Health | volume = 63 | issue = 7 | pages = 302\u20136 | date = September 1993 | pmid = 8246462 | doi = 10.1111/j.1746-1561.1993.tb06150.x }}</ref> however, a more parsimonious explanation could be that cannabis is simply more readily available (and at an earlier age) than illegal hard drugs. In turn, alcohol and tobacco are typically easier to obtain at an earlier age than is cannabis (though the reverse may be true in some areas), thus leading to the \"gateway sequence\" in those individuals, since they are most likely to experiment with any drug offered.<ref name=\"Rand\" />\n\nA related alternative to the gateway hypothesis is the common liability to addiction (CLA) theory. It states that some individuals are, for various reasons, willing to try multiple recreational substances. The \"gateway\" drugs are merely those that are (usually) available at an earlier age than the harder drugs. Researchers have noted in an extensive review that it is dangerous to present the sequence of events described in gateway \"theory\" in causative terms as this hinders both research and intervention.<ref name=Vanyukov2012>{{cite journal | vauthors = Vanyukov MM, Tarter RE, Kirillova GP, Kirisci L, Reynolds MD, Kreek MJ, Conway KP, Maher BS, Iacono WG, Bierut L, Neale MC, Clark DB, Ridenour TA | title = Common liability to addiction and \"gateway hypothesis\": theoretical, empirical and evolutionary perspective | journal = Drug and Alcohol Dependence | volume = 123 Suppl 1 | issue =  | pages = S3\u201317 | date = June 2012 | pmid = 22261179 | pmc = 3600369 | doi = 10.1016/j.drugalcdep.2011.12.018 | type = Review }}</ref>\n\n==Research==\n{{Further|Medical cannabis#Research}}\n\nCannabis research is challenging since the plant is illegal in most countries.<ref>{{cite journal | author =  | url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=marijuana-research | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101107192934/http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=marijuana-research | archive-date = 7 November 2010 | url-status=dead | title = Marijuana Research: Current restrictions on marijuana research are absurd | journal = Scientific American |date=2004-11-22 |access-date=2013-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ponto LL | title = Challenges of marijuana research | journal = Brain | volume = 129 | issue = Pt 5 | pages = 1081\u20133 | date = May 2006 | pmid = 16627464 | doi = 10.1093/brain/awl092 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | first = Alok | last = Jha | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/may/31/ecstasy-cannabis-study-david-nutt |title=Ecstasy and cannabis should be freely available for study, says David Nutt |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2012-05-31 |access-date=2013-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stanford.edu/group/hopes/cgi-bin/wordpress/2012/05/medical-marijuana-policy-in-the-united-states/#medical-marijuana-and-research |title=Medical Marijuana Policy in the United States |publisher=Stanford.edu |date=2012-05-15 |access-date=2013-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | first = Chelsea | last = Conaboy | name-list-format = vanc | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/health-wellness/2012/10/18/research-into-marijuana-medical-benefits-limited-scientists-cite-challenge-studying-illegal-drug/f6Ydip4xF5VfFWEV9mpwYJ/story.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121021003220/https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/health-wellness/2012/10/18/research-into-marijuana-medical-benefits-limited-scientists-cite-challenge-studying-illegal-drug/f6Ydip4xF5VfFWEV9mpwYJ/story.html | archive-date = 21 October 2012 |title=Research into marijuana's medical benefits limited; scientists cite challenge of studying an illegal drug | work  = Boston Globe |date=2012-10-19 |access-date=2013-01-15}}</ref> Research-grade samples of the drug are difficult to obtain for research purposes, unless granted under authority of national regulatory agencies, such as the US [[Food and Drug Administration]].<ref name=\"fda20\">{{cite web |title=FDA and Cannabis: Research and Drug Approval Process |url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/public-health-focus/fda-and-cannabis-research-and-drug-approval-process |publisher=US Food and Drug Administration |accessdate=21 January 2020 |date=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere are also other difficulties in researching the effects of cannabis. Many people who smoke cannabis also smoke tobacco.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Peters EN, Budney AJ, Carroll KM | title = Clinical correlates of co-occurring cannabis and tobacco use: a systematic review | journal = Addiction | volume = 107 | issue = 8 | pages = 1404\u201317 | date = August 2012 | pmid = 22340422 | pmc = 3377777 | doi = 10.1111/j.1360-0443.2012.03843.x }}</ref> This causes confounding factors, where questions arise as to whether the tobacco, the cannabis, or both that have caused a cancer. Another difficulty researchers have is in recruiting people who smoke cannabis into studies. Because cannabis is an illegal drug in many countries, people may be reluctant to take part in research, and if they do agree to take part, they may not say how much cannabis they actually smoke.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cancerresearchuk.org/cancer-help/about-cancer/cancer-questions/does-smoking-cannabis-cause-cancer | title = Does smoking cannabis cause cancer? |work = Cancer Research UK (CRUK) | date = 2017-08-30 }}</ref>\n\nA 2015 review found that the use of high CBD-to-THC strains of cannabis showed significantly fewer [[positive symptoms]] such as delusions and hallucinations, better [[cognitive function]] and both lower risk for developing psychosis, as well as a later age of onset of the illness, compared to cannabis with low CBD-to-THC ratios.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Iseger TA, Bossong MG | title = A systematic review of the antipsychotic properties of cannabidiol in humans | journal = Schizophrenia Research | volume = 162 | issue = 1\u20133 | pages = 153\u201361 | date = March 2015 | pmid = 25667194 | doi = 10.1016/j.schres.2015.01.033 }}</ref> Reviews in 2019 found that research was insufficient to determine the safety and efficacy of using cannabis to treat schizophrenia, psychosis, or other [[mental disorder]]s.<ref name=\"black\">{{Cite journal|last=Black|first=Nicola|last2=Stockings|first2=Emily|last3=Campbell|first3=Gabrielle|last4=Tran|first4=Lucy T.|last5=Zagic|first5=Dino|last6=Hall|first6=Wayne D.|last7=Farrell|first7=Michael|last8=Degenhardt|first8=Louisa|date=December 2019|title=Cannabinoids for the treatment of mental disorders and symptoms of mental disorders: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=The Lancet. Psychiatry|volume=6|issue=12|pages=995\u20131010|doi=10.1016/S2215-0366(19)30401-8|issn=2215-0374|pmc=6949116|pmid=31672337}}</ref><ref name=\"mayo\">{{Cite journal|last=VanDolah|first=Harrison J.|last2=Bauer|first2=Brent A.|last3=Mauck|first3=Karen F.|date=September 2019|title=Clinicians' Guide to Cannabidiol and Hemp\u00a0Oils|journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings|volume=94|issue=9|pages=1840\u20131851|doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2019.01.003|issn=1942-5546|pmid=31447137}}</ref> There is preliminary evidence that cannabis interferes with the [[anticoagulant]] properties of [[prescription drug]]s used for [[thrombosis|treating blood clots]].<ref name=\"Greger\">{{cite journal | last=Greger | first=Jessica | last2=Bates | first2=Vernice | last3=Mechtler | first3=Laszlo | last4=Gengo | first4=Fran | title=A review of cannabis and interactions with anticoagulant and antiplatelet agents | journal=The Journal of Clinical Pharmacology | volume=60 | issue=4 | pages=432\u2013438 | issn=0091-2700 | doi=10.1002/jcph.1557 | pmid=31724188| year=2020 }}</ref> {{as of|2019}}, the [[Mechanism of action|mechanisms]] for the [[anti-inflammatory]] and possible [[Analgesic|pain relieving]] effects of cannabis were not defined, and there were no governmental regulatory approvals or clinical practices for use of cannabis as a drug.<ref name=mayo/>\n\n== By country ==\n{{main|Legality of cannabis}}\n\n[[Cannabis in Uruguay|Uruguay]] and [[Cannabis in Canada|Canada]] are the only countries that have fully legalized the consumption and sale of recreational cannabis nationwide.<!--Whereas decriminalization would simply remove laws restricting the use of cannabis products, as has been implemented in many countries, legalization allows for the taxation of legally produced cannabis--><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/06/all-eyes-on-canada-as-first-g7-nation-prepares-to-make-marijuana-legal|title=All eyes on Canada as first G7 nation prepares to make marijuana legal|last=Ross|first=Selena|date=6 June 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/20/health/canada-legalizes-marijuana/index.html|title=Canada becomes second nation in the world to legalize marijuana|last=Sapra|first=Bani|date=20 June 2018|work=[[CNN]]|access-date=}}</ref> In the [[Legality of cannabis by U.S. jurisdiction|United States, 11 states]] and the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]] have legalized the recreational use of cannabis \u2013 though the drug remains illegal at the federal level.<ref name=\"ncsl rec\" /> Laws vary from state to state when it comes to the commercial sale. Court rulings in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and [[South Africa]] have led to the legalization of cannabis consumption, but not legal sales. A policy of limited enforcement has also been adopted in many countries, in particular [[Spain]] and the [[Netherlands]] where the sale of cannabis is tolerated at licensed establishments.<ref name=\"clubs jane\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Tasha |title=\"New Amsterdam\" No More? Spain's Cannabis Clubs Fight to Stay Open |url=https://merryjane.com/culture/spains-cannabis-social-clubs-feature-june-2018 |accessdate=23 August 2018 |work=Merry Jane |date=5 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"coffeeshops\">{{cite news |last1=Haines |first1=Gavin |title=Everything you need to know about marijuana smoking in the Netherlands |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/netherlands/amsterdam/articles/everything-you-need-to-know-about-smoking-marijuana-in-the-netherlands/ |accessdate=22 July 2018 |work=The Telegraph |date=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Occupational health concerns of cannabis use]]\n* [[The Green Rush]]\n\n== References ==\n'''Footnotes'''\n<!-- Please do not add any more nicknames, this should give an overview of the most common ones. -->\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary|marijuana}}\n{{Commons category-inline|Cannabis}}\n* [[wikt:Appendix:Cannabis slang|Wiktionary Appendix of Cannabis Slang]]\n\n{{Cannabis|state=expanded}}\n{{Cannabinoids}}\n{{Cannabinoid receptor modulators}}\n{{Analgesics}}\n{{Euphoriants}}\n{{Psychoactive substance use}}\n{{Drug use}}\n{{Portalbar|Cannabis|Pharmacy and Pharmacology}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cannabis (Drug)}}\n[[Category:Appetite stimulants]]\n[[Category:Cannabis| ]]\n[[Category:Cannabis smoking]]\n[[Category:Entheogens]]\n[[Category:Euphoriants]]\n[[Category:Herbalism]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n", "name_user": "HelloItsKane", "label": "safe", "comment": "Capitalisations :", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cannabis_(drug)"}
{"title_page": "Ciacova", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map              = Ciacova jud Timis.png\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|name                 =Ciacova\n|leader_name          =Petru Filip<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-06 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party         = PNL\n|image_skyline        =Ciacova catholic church.jpg\n|area_total_km2          = 138.49\n|coordinates          = {{coord|45|30|N|21|8|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Ciacova''' ({{lang-de|Tschakowa}}; {{lang-hu|Cs\u00e1k}}, before 1913 ''Cs\u00e1kova''; {{lang-sr|\u0427\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e/\u010cakovo}}; {{lang-tr|\u00c7akova}}) is a town in [[Timi\u0219 County]], western [[Romania]], in the [[Banat]] region. According to the 2011 census, it had 5,348 inhabitants.\n\nCiacova is located at {{convert|28|km|0|abbr=on}} from [[Timi\u0219oara]] and {{convert|30|km|0|abbr=on}} from the [[Serbia]]n border. The town administers four villages: Cebza (''Csebze''), Macedonia (''Maced\u00f3nia''), Obad (''Ob\u00e1d'') and Petroman (''Petrom\u00e1ny''). When it was declared a town in 2004, Gad and Ghilad villages, which it administered up to that point, were split off to form [[Ghilad]] Commune.\n\n==Demographics==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"margin: 0 1em 0 1em;\" width=\"60%\" \n|-\n! align=\"center\" colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#ccccff;\" | '''Census'''<ref name=\"Varga\">[http://www.kia.hu/konyvtar/erdely/erdstat/tmetn.pdf Varga E. ''Census data for Timi\u0219 County 1880 - 1992'']</ref>\n! align=\"center\" colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:#ccccff;\" | '''Ethnicity'''\n|-\n!'''Year'''\n!'''Population'''\n![[Romanians]]\n![[Germans]]\n![[Hungarians]]\n![[Romani people|Roma]