{"title_page": "Ali in Wonderland", "text_new": "{{short description|1981 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ali in Wonderland\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Ahmed Rachedi (film director)|Ahmed Rachedi]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Rachid Boudjedra]]<br>Ahmed Rachedi\n| starring       = [[Dj\u00e9loul Beghoura]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1981|7}}\n| runtime        = 122 minutes\n| country        = Algeria\n| language       = French\n}}\n\n'''''Ali in Wonderland''''' ({{lang-fr|Ali au pays des mirages}}) is a 1981 Algerian [[drama film]] directed by [[Ahmed Rachedi (film director)|Ahmed Rachedi]]. It was entered into the [[12th Moscow International Film Festival]] where it won a Special Prize.<ref name=\"Moscow1981\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1981 |title=12th Moscow International Film Festival (1981) |accessdate=25 January 2013 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421050907/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1981 |archivedate=21 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Donato Bastos]]\n* [[Dj\u00e9loul Beghoura]] as Ali (as Djelloul Beghoura)\n* [[Corinne Brodbeck]] as Th\u00e9r\u00e8se\n* [[Albert Delpy]] as Jean-Christophe\n* [[Sa\u00efd Helmi]] as Salah\n* [[Henri Poirier]]\n* [[Ahmed Snoussi]] as Ahmed\n* [[Andr\u00e9e Tainsy]]\n* [[Jean Valmont]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0327407|Ali in Wonderland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ali In Wonderland}}\n[[Category:1981 films]]\n[[Category:1980s drama films]]\n[[Category:Algerian films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Algerian drama films]]\n{{Algeria-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1981 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ali in Wonderland\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Ahmed Rachedi (film director)|Ahmed Rachedi]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Rachid Boudjedra]]<br>Ahmed Rachedi\n| starring       = [[Dj\u00e9loul Beghoura]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1981|7}}\n| runtime        = 122 minutes\n| country        = Algeria\n| language       = French\n}}\n\n'''''Ali in Wonderland''''' ({{lang-fr|Ali au pays des mirages}}) is a 1981 Algerian [[drama film]] directed by [[Ahmed Rachedi (film director)|Ahmed Rachedi]]. It was entered into the [[12th Moscow International Film Festival]] where it won a Special Prize.<ref name=\"Moscow1981\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1981 |title=12th Moscow International Film Festival (1981) |accessdate=25 January 2013 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421050907/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1981 |archivedate=21 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Donato Bastos]]\n* [[Dj\u00e9loul Beghoura]] as Ali (as Djelloul Beghoura)\n* [[Corinne Brodbeck]] as Th\u00e9r\u00e8se\n* [[Albert Delpy]] as Jean-Christophe\n* [[Sa\u00efd Helmi]] as Salah\n* [[Henri Poirier]]\n* [[Ahmed Snoussi]] as Ahmed\n* [[Andr\u00e9e Tainsy]]\n* [[Jean Valmont]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0327407|Ali in Wonderland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ali In Wonderland}}\n[[Category:1981 films]]\n[[Category:1980s drama films]]\n[[Category:Algerian films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Algerian drama films]]\n{{Algeria-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ali_in_Wonderland"}
{"title_page": "Cronulla and National Park Ferry Cruises", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox Water transit\n|name            = Cronulla and National Park Ferry Cruises\n|logo            = {{TFNSW lines|BUNC|size=1.5}}\n|logo_size       = \n|image           = Ferry from Cronulla to Bundeena.jpg\n|image_size      = \n|locale          = [[Southern Sydney]]\n|waterway        = [[Port Hacking]] \n|transit_type    = Passenger and cruise ferry\n|began_operation = 1915\n|ended_operation = \n|system_length   = \n|lines           = \n|vessels         = 4\n|terminals       = 2\n|ridership       =\n|marks           =\n|operator        = \n|owner           = Carl Rogan\n|website         = [http://cronullaferries.com.au/ www.cronullaferries.com.au]}}\n\n'''Cronulla and National Park Ferry Cruises''' is a ferry operator on [[Port Hacking]] in [[Southern Sydney]] Australia. \n\nIt operates a scheduled service from [[Cronulla]] to [[Bundeena]] at the northern end of [[Royal National Park]] making the ferry service popular with bushwalkers as well as local residents.<ref>[http://cronullaferries.com.au/ferries-to-bundeena/bundeena-timetable/ Bundeena Timetable] Cronulla and National Park Ferry Cruises</ref> The company also operates scenic cruises around Port Hacking.\n\nThe Cronulla to Bundeena service commenced operating in 1915 when Captain R Ryall commenced operating the service. The business was purchased by HC Mallam in the late 1940s who sold it to Jack Gowland in the late 1960s. It has since been sold a number of times and is now owned by Carl Rogan.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Andrews|first1=Graeme|title=Ferries of Sydney|date=1994|publisher=Sydney University Press|location=Sydney|isbn=0424002027|pages=205-208}}</ref><ref>[http://www.theleader.com.au/story/4219148/photos-curranulla-is-sailing-with-the-sharks/ Curranulla is sailing with the Sharks] ''[[St George and Sutherland Shire Leader|The Leader]]'' 12 October 2016</ref>\n\n==Fleet==\nCronulla and National Park Ferry Cruises operate four vessels:<ref>[http://cronullaferries.com.au/our-vessels/ Our Vessels] Cronulla and National Park Ferry Cruises</ref>\n*''Curranulla'', named after the rowboat used by [[George Bass]] and [[Matthew Flinders]] to explore [[Port Hacking]]. The 53 foot ferry was built by [[Morrison & Sinclair]], [[Balmain, New South Wales|Balmain]] entering service on 12 May 1939, Originally powered by a 3-cylinder K3 12 litre 66HP hand start Kelvin diesel, replaced in 1986 by a 5LW [[L. Gardner and Sons|Gardner]]. ''Curranulla'' is the oldest commuter ferry still operating in Australia.\n  \n*''Tom Thumb III'' built in 1946 in [[Forster, New South Wales|Forster]] by Alf Jahnsan as the ''Alma G'' powered with a 4LW Gardner engine. Purchased in 1952 by Cliff Mallam and moved to Cronulla where she had her engine converted to a 2-cylinder K2 Kelvin 8 litre 44HP handstart Diesel engine. Renamed ''[[Gymea, New South Wales|Gymea]]'' before becoming the ''Tom Thumb III'' in 1982 when repowered with a 5LW Gardner engine.\n*''Gunnamatta'', named after [[Gunnamatta Bay]], was built in 1989 by Broadwater Craft, [[Nerang, Queensland|Nerang]] as a catamaran to operate cruises\n*''Port Hacking Explorer II'' is a cruise vessel\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--*{{commons category-inline}}-->\n*[http://www.cronullaferries.com.au/ Company website]\n*[http://bundeenainfo.com/cronulla-bundeena-ferry-timetable.html Cronulla Bundeena Ferry Timetable & Video]\n\n{{Sydney public transport|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Ferry companies of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Ferry transport in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Transport companies established in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Cronulla, New South Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox Water transit\n|name            = Cronulla and National Park Ferry Cruises\n|logo            = {{TFNSW lines|BUNC|size=1.5}\n|logo_size       = \n|image           = Ferry from Cronulla to Bundeena.jpg\n|image_size      = \n|locale          = [[Southern Sydney]]\n|waterway        = [[Port Hacking]] \n|transit_type    = Passenger and cruise ferry\n|began_operation = 1915\n|ended_operation = \n|system_length   = \n|lines           = \n|vessels         = 4\n|terminals       = 2\n|ridership       =\n|marks           =\n|operator        = \n|owner           = Carl Rogan\n|website         = [http://cronullaferries.com.au/ www.cronullaferries.com.au]}}\n\n'''Cronulla and National Park Ferry Cruises''' is a ferry operator on [[Port Hacking]] in [[Southern Sydney]] Australia. \n\nIt operates a scheduled service from [[Cronulla]] to [[Bundeena]] at the northern end of [[Royal National Park]] making the ferry service popular with bushwalkers as well as local residents.<ref>[http://cronullaferries.com.au/ferries-to-bundeena/bundeena-timetable/ Bundeena Timetable] Cronulla and National Park Ferry Cruises</ref> The company also operates scenic cruises around Port Hacking.\n\nThe Cronulla to Bundeena service commenced operating in 1915 when Captain R Ryall commenced operating the service. The business was purchased by HC Mallam in the late 1940s who sold it to Jack Gowland in the late 1960s. It has since been sold a number of times and is now owned by Carl Rogan.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Andrews|first1=Graeme|title=Ferries of Sydney|date=1994|publisher=Sydney University Press|location=Sydney|isbn=0424002027|pages=205-208}}</ref><ref>[http://www.theleader.com.au/story/4219148/photos-curranulla-is-sailing-with-the-sharks/ Curranulla is sailing with the Sharks] ''[[St George and Sutherland Shire Leader|The Leader]]'' 12 October 2016</ref>\n\n==Fleet==\nCronulla and National Park Ferry Cruises operate four vessels:<ref>[http://cronullaferries.com.au/our-vessels/ Our Vessels] Cronulla and National Park Ferry Cruises</ref>\n*''Curranulla'', named after the rowboat used by [[George Bass]] and [[Matthew Flinders]] to explore [[Port Hacking]]. The 53 foot ferry was built by [[Morrison & Sinclair]], [[Balmain, New South Wales|Balmain]] entering service on 12 May 1939, Originally powered by a 3-cylinder K3 12 litre 66HP hand start Kelvin diesel, replaced in 1986 by a 5LW [[L. Gardner and Sons|Gardner]]. ''Curranulla'' is the oldest commuter ferry still operating in Australia.\n  \n*''Tom Thumb III'' built in 1946 in [[Forster, New South Wales|Forster]] by Alf Jahnsan as the ''Alma G'' powered with a 4LW Gardner engine. Purchased in 1952 by Cliff Mallam and moved to Cronulla where she had her engine converted to a 2-cylinder K2 Kelvin 8 litre 44HP handstart Diesel engine. Renamed ''[[Gymea, New South Wales|Gymea]]'' before becoming the ''Tom Thumb III'' in 1982 when repowered with a 5LW Gardner engine.\n*''Gunnamatta'', named after [[Gunnamatta Bay]], was built in 1989 by Broadwater Craft, [[Nerang, Queensland|Nerang]] as a catamaran to operate cruises\n*''Port Hacking Explorer II'' is a cruise vessel\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--*{{commons category-inline}}-->\n*[http://www.cronullaferries.com.au/ Company website]\n*[http://bundeenainfo.com/cronulla-bundeena-ferry-timetable.html Cronulla Bundeena Ferry Timetable & Video]\n\n{{Sydney public transport|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Ferry companies of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Ferry transport in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Transport companies established in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Cronulla, New South Wales]]\n", "name_user": "JivanZa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cronulla_and_National_Park_Ferry_Cruises"}
{"title_page": "Buzia\u0219", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|official_name         = Buzia\u0219\n|image_map              = Buzias jud Timis.png\n|image_skyline         = Buzias Ansamblu balnear (2).jpg\n|image_caption         =\n|image_shield          = ROU TM Buzias CoA.png\n|leader_name           = Sorin Munteanu<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-06 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party          = PNL\n|area_total_km2        = 105.2\n|coordinates           = {{coord|45|39|N|21|36|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website               = {{url|https://www.primariabuzias.ro}}\n}} \n'''Buzia\u0219''' is a town in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Romania]]. As of 2011, it had a population of 6,504.\n\n==Name==\nIn {{lang-de|(Bad) Busiasch}}, in {{lang-hu|Buzi\u00e1s}} or ''Buzi\u00e1sf\u00fcrd\u0151'', in {{lang-sr|\u0411\u0443\u0437\u0458\u0430\u0448 or Buzja\u0161}}.\n\n==History==\nThe town was first mentioned in 1321 in a document of [[Charles I of Hungary]]. It was declared a city in 1956. It administers two villages, Bacova (''Bakowa'', ''Bak\u00f3v\u00e1r'') and Silagiu (''Nagyszilas'').\n\n==Health spa==\nBuzia\u0219 is an old health [[Spa town|spa]], the first establishments being built in 1819. In 1839 was declared a spa. The mineral waters of Buzia\u0219 are used in the treatment of a wide range of diseases. They were also bottled for common use.\n\n==Dendrological park==\nThe park of Buzia\u0219, with a surface of over 20 ha, is a dendrological park with many rare species of trees, the most important being the plane (''[[Platanus]]''). The architectural symbolic element of the spa is the covered colonnade of the park built in Turkish-Byzantine style, unique to Romania. The only two other similar promenades in Europe are found in [[Karlovy Vary]] and [[Baden-Baden]].\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Buzia\u015f train stn.JPG|right|300px|thumb|Buzia\u0219 train station]]\nTrain services to [[Gataia]] and [[Jamu Mare]] are operated by [[Regiotrans]].\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to 2011 census:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ethnic group\n! Number\n! Percentage\n|-\n| [[Romanians]]\n| 5,847\n| 89.89%\n|-\n| [[Hungarians]]\n| 204\n| 3.13%\n|-\n| [[Germans]]\n| 148\n| 2.27%\n|-\n| [[Romani people|Romani]]\n| 206\n| 3.16%\n|-\n| Other\n| 98\n| 1.7%\n|-\n| '''Total'''\n| '''6,504'''\n| '''100%'''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: font-size:93%;width:300px;height:16;border:0px;text-align:left;line-height:120%;margin-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"text-align:center; background: #F4F4F4\" height=24px |'''Historical population of Buzia\u0219'''<ref>[http://varga.adatbank.transindex.ro/?pg=3&action=etnik&id=3616 Erd\u00e9ly etnikai \u00e9s felekezeti statisztik\u00e1ja<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n|-\n! Year\n! Population\n! Romanians\n! Hungarians\n! Germans\n|-\n| 1880\n| 6,091\n| 40.5%\n| 10.3%\n| 42.3%\n|-\n| 1890\n| 6,776 \n| 41.7%\n| 10.5%\n| 46.4%\n|- \n| 1900\n| 7,191\n| 41.1%\n| 12.5%\n| 45.4%\n|- \n| 1910\n| 7,141\n| 41.6%\n| 15.5%\n| 41.6%\n|- \n| 1920\n| 6,651\n| 41.6%\n| 9%\n| 47.7%\n|- \n| 1930\n| 6,764 \n| 39.6%\n| 10.6%\n| 46.6%\n|-\n| 1941\n| 6,547\n| 41.6%\n| 7.7%\n| 47.2%\n|-\n| 1956\n| 7,203 \n| 54.5%\n| 8.1%\n| 34.4%\n|- \n| 1966\n| 7,310 \n| 60.7%\n| 7.4%\n| 30.7%\n|- \n| 1977\n| 7,976 \n| 65.8%\n| 6.1%\n| 24.7%\n|- \n| 1992\n| 8,041\n| 84.1%\n| 4.8%\n| 6.4%\n|- \n| 2002<ref>[http://www.edrc.ro/recensamant.jsp?regiune_id=1832&judet_id=2057&localitate_id=2060 Structura Etno-demografic\u0103 a Rom\u00e2niei<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| 12,772\n| 87.4%\n| 4.1%\n| 3.6%\n|- \n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Endre Misteth]], engineer and mi